iences</em></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>','2019-04-03','2019-05-07',NULL,'Presidential Events',NULL,'presidentialevents@ucf.edu','Presidential Events','Publish',124),(2877,'Live Music Night with H2O!','live-music-night-with-h2o','<p><strong>Hey there! </strong><span>Do you like live music, fresh air, and free food? </span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Well then, H2O College is inviting YOU, your kids, DOGS, and friends to a Live Music Night! </span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Thursday, April 11th at 7:30PM on the stage in-front of the CFE arena</strong>, there will be performances by local </span></p>\n<p><span>musicians including Carey Gautreaux and Jessi Tobin, Ryan Wyker and Savannah Zona, Bobby Hegedish, </span></p>\n<p><span>and more! There will be free food, drinks, and fun times!! Seating: There is lawn seating and some chair</span></p>\n<p><span> seating available. Bring blankets and lawn chairs to get comfy! There is food directly next to the venue </span></p>\n<p><span>(including Gringos Locos, Jimmy Johns, Pop Parlour, and more), and we will have pizza! </span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Parking:</strong> Free Parking is available in nearby parking Garage F, by meter, or by day pass in other nearby parking facilities.</span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Message us for any questions or visit our f<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/events/2236655906399847/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">acebook page for more information!</a></span></p>','2019-04-03','2019-04-12','https://www.facebook.com/events/2236655906399847/','Savannah Zona','(561) 235-9586','savannahzona@knights.ucf.edu','Savannah Zona','Pending',103),(2881,'Need 3 credits for Summer? Take Basic Sport First Aid and CPR','do-you-need-3-credits-for-summer-take-basic-sport-first-aid-and-cpr-apk2300','<p>Learn how to care for and prevent injuries! As a coach, athletic trainer, or professional in sports science, you may be responsible for medical emergencies. Learn what to do in an emergency situation and become CPR/AED certified by the American Red Cross.</p>\n<p><br>This course is open to any student from any major!</p>\n<p>Register for APK 2300 B001 (62060)</p>\n<p>Tuesday and Thursday - 12:00pm-3:50pm</p>','2019-04-15','2019-06-20','https://healthprofessions.ucf.edu/kpt/kinesiology/bachelors/','Sport and Exercise Science Advising','(407) 823-0623','SESadvising@ucf.edu','Division of Kinesiology','Publish',13),(2882,'Get Fit While Earning Course Credit','do-you-want-to-get-fit-1','<p>The College of Health Professions and Sciences is offering Personal Fitness in the Summer 2019 semester.</p>\n<p>This course is three credit hours and is open to all students from any major!</p>\n<p>Search MyUCF for PEM 2104</p>\n<p>PEM 2104 B001 (class number 60100)</p>\n<p>Monday and Wednesday 12:00pm- 3:50pm</p>','2019-04-08','2019-06-24','https://healthprofessions.ucf.edu/kpt/kinesiology/bachelors/','Division of Kinesiology','(407) 823-0623','sesadvising@ucf.edu','Division of Kinesiology','Publish',13),(2885,'SUS Florida Hazing Prevention Summit','sus-florida-hazing-prevention-summit-1','<p><strong>The Florida SUS Hazing Prevention Summit</strong> will be held at the University of Central Florida on May 17, 2019. We invite you to register to be a part of this important event. The target audience is staff, faculty, advisors, and graduate students. There will be a variety of sessions, case studies and discussions on hazing prevention strategies for clubs, organizations, fraternities, sororities, athletics, band, and ROTC.  You will also have the opportunity to learn from parent experiences and network with representatives from other institutions in the state of Florida.</p>\n<p>Registration for the 2019 Hazing Prevention Summit:<span> <a href=\"http://www.fau.edu/student/hazingpreventionsummit/#Registration\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.fau.edu/student/hazingpreventionsummit/#Registration</a></span></p>\n<p><span></span>For more information please contact Germayne Graham at  407-823-2223 or <span> </span><a href=\"mailto:germayne.graham@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">germayne.graham@ucf.edu</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>','2019-04-15','2019-05-18','http://www.fau.edu/student/hazingpreventionsummit/#Registration','Germayne Graham','(407) 823-2223','germayne.graham@ucf.edu','Germayne Graham','Publish',41),(2886,'Call For Art: Hidden Artists Exhibit','call-for-art-hidden-artists-exhibit','<p>CALL FOR ART</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Hidden Artist Exhibit at the John C. Hitt Library</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>You might find them in front of the classroom or in the office down the hall and yet never suspect they make art. They are “Hidden Artists”. Hidden Artists is a group of UCF faculty and staff from various departments who create art on their own time. The exhibit is an opportunity for faculty and staff to show their artistic talents.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Hidden Artists are looking for <em>original</em> artwork created by UCF Faculty and Staff to be displayed for its exhibit from August 1, 2019 – September 27, 2019 at the John C. Hitt Library’s art wall located on the main floor. Artwork must be ready to hang. Up to 2 artworks per artist with the maximum of 24 inches wide and up to 72 inches height. 3D art is accepted but must be able to fit display cases.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Please email submission with photo documentation of artwork for approval by <strong>June 29, 2019</strong> to Chris at <a href=\"mailto:christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For more information email Chris at <a href=\"mailto:christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>For more announcements go to: <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/hiddenartists/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/hiddenartists/</a></p>','2019-05-02','2019-06-29','http://www.facebook.com/hiddenartists','Christopher Saclolo','(407) 823-0703','christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu','Christopher Saclolo, Hidden Artists Exhibit','Publish',198),(2891,'UCF Women\'s Golf Earns Bid To NCAA Regionals','ucf-womens-golf-earns-bid-to-ncaa-regionals','<p>Coming off a runner-up finish at the American Athletic Conference Championship, the UCF women\'s golf team will compete as the<span> </span><span>No. 13 seed at the NCAA Cle Elum Region.</span></p>\n<p>UCF is one of 18<span> schools selected for the Cle Elum, Washington</span> Regional hosted by the University of Washington. It will take place May 6-8 at the Tumble Creek Club.</p>\n<p>This is the 14th<span> r</span>egional appearance for the program and the sixth appearance in the last nine seasons. UCF finished second at the American Athletic Conference Championship for the second-straight season, while AAC Freshman of the Year Elizabeth Moon finished second overall with a 210(-6). Her second-place finish is her third top-five finish this season and sixth top-10 finish.</p>\n<p>Moon was also recently named to The American All-Conference Team along with junior Maria Balcazar.</p>','2019-04-25','2019-05-06','http://ucfknights.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34100&ATCLID=211800887','Kelly Cartner','(407) 823-3213','kcartner@athletics.ucf.edu','Jenna Lee','Publish',165),(2892,'USPS Employee of the Month (April) - Natalia Giron','usps-employee-of-the-month-april-natalia-giron','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for April 2019: Natalia Giron. Natalia is the Admissions Specialist in International Student and Scholar Services in UCF Global. She has worked at the university since August 2013. Her nominators had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>          “Natalia is highly dependable with exemplary work ethic. Her multiple qualities in areas of customer service, organization and leadership skills are invaluable to the International Student and Scholar Services team and UCF Global. She demonstrates a high level of professionalism and conscientiousness in her work to ensure that immigration documents are always issued by the deadline. She constantly contributes her ideas to optimize workflow, create efficiencies and improve the experience for students.</em></p>\n<p><em>          During a recent UCF Global campaign, Natalia gave the following testimonial ‘I know there is somebody on the other side of the world waiting to hear from me.’ She believes in UCF’s promise to attract and cultivate exceptional diverse students.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Natalia receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Annual Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>','2019-04-29','2019-05-06','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbac@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(2893,'UCF Libraries Awards Stillman Scholarship','ucf-libraries-awards-stillman-scholarship','<p>The University of Central Florida Libraries is proud to announce that Stefani Hammond is the 2019 recipient of the June S. Stillman Memorial Endowed Scholarship.</p>\n<p>Hammond is a junior majoring in anthropology. She plans to obtain a doctoral degree, specializing in biological anthropology, and to become a professor at an established research university. A first-generation student, she began working as a student assistant in circulation services in the John C. Hitt Library in August 2017. </p>\n<p>Hammond’s research career includes the McNair Scholars Program, the Research and Mentorship Program (RAMP), and presentations at UCF Undergraduate Research conferences. She has also participated in research fellowships, written manuscripts for publication in academic research journals, and worked with faculty mentor John Starbuck in UCF’s Morphometric Research Lab.</p>\n<p>Hammond has served as a mentor for UCF’s Resident Leadership Conference and is the current secretary of the Lambda Alpha Anthropology Honors Society. She has also been a resident assistant and a conference assistant with the UCF Department of Housing &amp; Residence Life, a role with which she credits with teaching her empathy and compassion in leadership.</p>\n<p>This is the 21st awarding of the Stillman scholarship, which is given to a student or staff member of the UCF Libraries. June S. Stillman was one of the first two librarians hired when UCF (then Florida Technological University) opened in 1968. Her impact on students can be seen from a 25th anniversary survey of the first graduating class, a majority of whom listed her as a key figure from their student days. Stillman received her second master’s degree in English Literature from UCF while working as the Head of Reference Services at the Library. She retired in 1996 and tragically passed away in 1998. Her friends and family established the June S. Stillman Memorial Endowed Scholarship in her honor. She is remembered as a consummate professional, the epitome of gentility and compassion, and a proponent of lifelong learning.          </p>','2019-05-01','2019-05-09',NULL,'Katie Burroughs','(407) 823-3222','Katie.Burroughs@ucf.edu','Jenna Lee','Publish',165),(2896,'ChargeOn Tour Hits Florida Cities — including Orlando — This Week','chargeon-tour-hits-florida-cities-including-orlando-this-week-1-2','<p><span>UCF Athletics\' annual ChargeOn Tour makes stops in three Florida cities this week. These events, which run from 6-8 p.m., feature autograph opportunities and a Q&amp;A session with UCF head coaches at each stop. It is free to the public with no registration required.</span></p>\n<p><span></span><span><strong>May 7: Fort Lauderdale</strong><br><em>Bubba Gump Shrimp Company (429 South Fort Lauderdale Beach Boulevard)<br></em></span><span>H</span>osted by Voice of the Knights Marc Daniels, UCF Director of Athletics and Danny White and head football coach Josh Heupel will also make appearances.</p>\n<p><strong>May 8: Port Canaveral</strong><br><em>Gators Dockside (683 Dave Nisbet Drive, Cape Canaveral)<br></em>The Space Coast’s own Mark Moses will host the event that will include appearances from White, Heupel and men’s basketball head coach Johnny Dawkins.  </p>\n<p><strong>May 9: Downtown Orlando<br></strong><em>Wall Street Plaza (<span>25 Wall Street)</span></em><br>Marc Daniels will be back to host the event at Wall Street Plaza to celebrate Orlando’s Hometown Team. White, Heupel, Dawkins and women’s basketball head coach Katie Abrahamson-Henderson will be on hand to meet and greet the fans.</p>','2019-05-06','2019-05-10','http://ucfknights.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34100&ATCLID=211800573','Jimmy Skiles','(407) 823-3198','jskiles@athletics.ucf.edu','Jenna Lee','Publish',165),(2897,'UCF I-Corps Program is Looking for Applicants','ucf-i-corps-program-aimed-at-moving-research-to-marketplace-is-looking-for-applicants','<p><span>The purpose of the I-Corps Site is to foster innovation among faculty, students, and local entrepreneurs in order to nurture and support them as teams, which can then work together to transition their inventions into the marketplace.  Once teams complete the UCF I-Corps program, the path to commercial market continues with opportunities for funding from NSF’s national I-Corps program, Small Business Innovation Research/Small Business Technology Transfer (SBIR/STTR) grant funding, or from seed capital sources. Teams are also able to tap into the entrepreneurial ecosystem within UCF’s Center for Innovation and Entrepreneurship and the broader community.</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Applications are now open</strong></span> for the next I-Corps cohort, which begins in June of 2019.  The cohort will be held at UCF, and is open to students, faculty, and entrepreneurs at universities and research centers from around the state.</span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Information about the program, including application and requirements for participation, can be found at the UCF I-Corps website <a href=\"https://icorps.cie.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://icorps.cie.ucf.edu/</a>.  Additionally, interested individuals are encouraged to attend our information session on <strong></strong><strong>Thursday, May 23rd at 1:00 PM </strong> in Trevor Colburn Hall Room 213.</span></p>','2019-05-20','2019-05-31','https://icorps.cie.ucf.edu/','Daniel Elbrecht','(407) 882-0663','daniel.elbrecht@ucf.edu','UCF Office of Research and Commercialization','Publish',191),(2901,'CPNM Accepting Applications for Summer Capacity Building Seminars','cpnm-accepting-applications-for-summer-capacity-building-seminars','<p>If your nonprofit agency has a health and human services mission and is located in, and serving residents of, Ora<span>nge County, Florida, you may be eligible to participate in a valuable capacity building opportunity.</span></p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida Center for Public and Nonprofit Management (CPNM) has partnered with Orange County Citizens’ Commission for Children (OCCCC) to provide capacity building training (five face-to-face and one online session) and technical assistance (provided by one graduate research assistant for up to 4 hours/week). Fifteen agencies will be accepted for the training program (June 21 through August 9, 2019) focused on grant writing, organization governance, financial management, and strategic planning and program evaluation. The training program, free of charge to participants, is funded entirely by OCCCC. Please note that agencies will receive training and technical assistance, but no financial assistance.</p>\n<p>Preference will be given to 501(C)(3) not-for-profit organizations with a health and human service mission that are both located and provide services in Orange County, and have been in operation for a minimum of one (1) year. Additional eligibility criteria are listed on the application website.</p>\n<p>To apply for the program and to get more information:</p>\n<p>Go to<span> </span><a data-ft=\'{\"tn\":\"-U\"}\' data-lynx-mode=\"asynclazy\" href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ce.ucf.edu%2Fcapacitybuilding%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR3EcN_ll10kcLt8KRcVMXw437xTadGuoSHlTAz0y-uJPZfmNgccXeYIE34&amp;h=AT3QnWpyBJlHkSYQn9eWPDX-9uVpZE9LSYJesFCQDoa4yYZMVn4t8QT3fcTI_iXMf4bkn0one5UEAxrjjHdM8zNtxpW7PssBUOP0PSHDIjWeoailcSAOzKvD46ro9O4nLUAqow1cr26PSwnRKietWtlhlQ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.ce.ucf.edu/capacitybuilding</a><span> </span>or contact Ms. Sara Iman, Project Coordinator, at CPNM@ucf.edu. Application is due by 5 p.m., Friday, May 24, 2019. Early application is encouraged. Selection notification will occur by close of business on May 29, 2019.</p>','2019-05-14','2019-05-24','http://www.ce.ucf.edu/capacitybuilding','Sara Iman',NULL,'cpnm@ucf.edu','Center for Public and Nonprofit Management','Publish',155),(2902,'UCF Rosen College Launches Research Focused Magazine','ucf-rosen-college-launches-research-focused-magazine','<p>The Rosen Research Review reflects the changing times in hospitality research and academia as the college works in collaboration with its industry partners to address their needs and share knowledge gained in analyzing the ever-changing industry.</p>\n<p>The goal of the magazine is to help hospitality and tourism practitioners navigate the future of how we enjoy all aspects of hospitality, attractions, events, entertainment, foodservice, restaurants and more.</p>\n<p>Each article speaks to a different segment of the hospitality industry and introduces experts in the field who are members of the Rosen College faculty. </p>\n<p><span>To read the Rosen Research Review visit: </span><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fhospitality.ucf.edu%2Frosen-research-review%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7CZenaida.Kotala%40ucf.edu%7Cd0120485e0a5422b16e008d6d867ee54%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C636934338605588904&amp;sdata=KjzJFcdvD9OZnfQpeCDNS7RT2kWdmUt3iT9yxzXhdjc%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">hospitality.ucf.edu/rosen-research-review/</a></p>','2019-05-16','2019-05-20','https://today.ucf.edu/ucf-rosen-college-launches-research-focused-magazine/','Susan Vernon-Devlin','(407) 903-8151','Susan.Vernon-Devlin@ucf.edu','Jenna Lee','Publish',165),(2903,'Call for 2018-2019 A&P Excellence Award Nominations','call-for-2018-2019-ap-excellence-award-nominations','<p>You are invited to submit nominations for UCF\'s annual Gabor Administrative and Professional (A&amp;P) Excellence Award. Sponsored by The Gabor Agency, the award was established to recognize, appreciate, and celebrate the outstanding job performance of a selected A&amp;P employee. The chosen candidate for the award will be announced at the Annual Employee Awards Program on September 25, 2019, and will receive a check for $2,500.</p>\n<p>All nominations must be received in Human Resources by 5:00 p.m. on Friday, July 12, 2019.</p>\n<p>Eligibility criteria and additional information about the award: <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/</a></p>\n<p>Nomination form: <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/2019-Gabor-Nom-Form.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/2019-Gabor-Nom-Form.pdf</a> (best viewed in Internet Explorer)</p>\n<p>If you have questions, or for more information, please contact the Human Resources Learning &amp; Organizational Effectiveness team at 407-823-0440 or email <a href=\"mailto:HRLearning@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">HRLearning@ucf.edu</a>.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your active participation in recognizing UCF A&amp;P employees for their outstanding contributions!</p>','2019-06-03','2019-07-12','https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/','HR Learning & Organizational Effectiveness','(407) 823-0440','HRLearning@ucf.edu','Lee Williams','Publish',24),(2905,'Now Accepting Proposals: Pabst Steinmetz Foundation Arts & Wellness Innovation Awards','now-accepting-proposals-pabst-steinmetz-foundation-arts-wellness-innovation-awards-1','<p><strong>The Pabst Steinmetz Foundation Arts &amp; Wellness Innovation Awards are open for submission from Monday, May 20-Thursday, October 10, 2019. Two winners will be selected and receive $25,000 each.</strong></p>\n<p>The purpose of the<span> </span><a href=\"https://www.cah.ucf.edu/arts-wellness-innovation-awards/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Pabst Steinmetz Foundation Arts &amp; Wellness Innovation Awards</a><span> </span>is to build sustainable models for arts and wellness innovation across the community and UCF campus. Interdisciplinary collaboration and evidence-based community impact will be recognized as guides for building sustainability.</p>\n<p><strong>Award Criteria</strong></p>\n<p>All submissions must meet all of the following criteria:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Preference will be given to initiatives that are interdisciplinary, community-focused and sustainable.</strong></li>\n<li>Cross-disciplinary: Applicants must involve the UCF College of Arts and Humanities and at least one other college, unit or center at the University of Central Florida in each submission.</li>\n<li>All programs, initiatives or projects must contain an evaluation framework (quantitative or qualitative.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Topic Examples</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Caregiving for loved ones with cognitive disorders</li>\n<li>Enforcing positivity with youth populations/mental health/bullying</li>\n<li>Daily wellness and self-care</li>\n<li>Read about the<span> </span><a href=\"https://news.cah.ucf.edu/news/pabst-steinmetz-foundation-arts-wellness-innovation-awards/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">2018 recipients</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Nomination Form and Selection Process</strong></p>\n<p>More information about the award, including the nomination form, is available at<span> </span><a href=\"https://www.cah.ucf.edu/arts-wellness-innovation-awards/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.cah.ucf.edu/arts-wellness-innovation-awards</a>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Nominations open May 20 and are due <strong>October 10, 2019</strong>.</li>\n<li>The selection committee comprises a representative from the UCF College of Arts and Humanities, the UCF College of Nursing, and the UCF College of Medicine, as well as up to three at-large members from the arts and wellness community.</li>\n<li>If a team is selected as the winner, the team leader will receive the award.</li>\n<li>Award presentations will be made in Spring 2020.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For questions, please contact Kara Robertson, Director for Advancement for UCF College of Arts and Humanities, at<span> </span><a href=\"mailto:Kara.Robertson@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">Kara.Robertson@ucf.edu</a>.</p>','2019-06-06','2019-10-09','https://www.cah.ucf.edu/research/arts-wellness-innovation-awards/','Kara Robertson','(407) 823-3448','kara.robertson@ucf.edu','Heather Gibson','Publish',56),(2906,'Having difficulty passing the FTCE General Knowledge Review? Take our Boot Camp class starting July 15, 2019!','having-difficulty-passing-the-ftce-general-knowledge-review-take-our-boot-camp-class-starting-july-15-2019','<p><em>Offered online or in-class in partnership with Master Mind Educational Consulting</em></p>\n<p>UCF has developed a comprehensive FTCE General Knowledge Review Program to empower teaching professionals and prospective students with the knowledge to receive high scores on the FTCE General Knowledge exam\'s English Language Skills, Reading, Essay and Mathematics sections.</p>\n<p>Our FTCE General Knowledge Review Program is taught by professional educators who are able to connect with the class to convey important test information and explain test-taking strategies that are easy to remember and apply.</p>\n<p><strong>In-class option:</strong> Meet at our UCF Continuing Education building in Orlando, FL. </p>\n<p><strong>Online option:</strong> Login to view the live online sessions streamed during Eastern Standard Time. You will be able to hear the instructor lead the course discussions, view the course handouts, and engage in an online chat discussion with students and your instructor. </p>\n<p><em>Registration is on a first come first serve basis and seats tend to fill up quickly. Register early as both the IN-PERSON and ONLINE sessions have a cap on enrollment.  </em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"></span></em></p>\n<p><strong><em><span style=\"text-decoration: none;\">THIS IS A BOOT CAMP COURSE THAT WILL BE HELD July 15th, 16th, 18th, and 19th FROM 9AM-4PM. </span></em></strong></p>\n<p>FTCE General Knowledge Review Series </p>\n<p><em>English Language Skills, Critical Reading, Essay and Mathematics - 24 hrs - 4 sessions</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This course will provide the same test strategies that are listed in the review programs for English and Mathematics below.</li>\n<li>Both in-class and online students will have access to an online repository of resources throughout the English and Math courses.</li>\n<li>Registration Fee (In-Class or Online): $499</li>\n</ul>\n<p><br> <strong>FTCE General Knowledge English Review - July 15th and 16th from 9AM-4PM.</strong></p>\n<p><em>English Language Skills, Critical Reading, and Essay Review - 12 hrs - 2 sessions</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This course will provide a framework for successful test taking strategies for conceptual understanding and mastering the concepts applied to English Language Skills, Critical Reading and Essay sections.</li>\n<li>Both in-class and online students will have access to an online repository of additional resources throughout the course.</li>\n<li>Registration Fee (In-Class or Online): $279</li>\n</ul>\n<p><br><strong> FTCE General Knowledge Math Review- July 18th and 19th from 9AM-4PM. </strong></p>\n<p><em>Mathematics Review - 12 hrs - 2 sessions</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This course will provide exercises to aid the process of mastering the concepts of all four math domains (number sense, concepts, and operations, geometry and measurement, algebraic thinking and coordinate plane, and probability, statistics, and data interpretation).</li>\n<li>Both in-class and online students will take an online diagnostic test before starting the FTCE GK Math review program. The diagnostic is intended to assess foundational skills needed to succeed in the FTCE GK Math domains. Based on the results, both IN-PERSON and ONLINE students will have access to an online repository of resources to help improve their areas of weakness.</li>\n<li>Registration Fee (In-Class or Online): $279</li>\n</ul>','2019-05-23','2019-07-13','https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program/FTCE-General-Knowledge-Review-Program','Alexis Cason','(407) 882-0251','alexis.cason@ucf.edu','UCF Continuing Education','Publish',84),(2907,'UCF Track & Field 4x100 Relay Qualifies for NCAA Championship','ucf-track-field-4x100-relay-to-compete-at-ncaa-championship','<p>The UCF 4x100 relay team\'s season-best performance at the NCAA East Preliminary Round punched its ticket to the NCAA Championship in Austin, Texas. </p>\n<p>The Knights clinched the automatic berth as the third-place team in their heat and finished eighth in the race overall with their time of 43.72.</p>\n<p>“It was a great day for the program,” UCF head coach Dana Boone<span> </span>said. “It was a great step to move forward and make it to nationals with this relay. I’m super proud of the girls and how they performed. We had to make a substitution this week, but they didn’t let that bother them; they handled it well. Now we’re on our way to Austin. I’m super proud of the ladies.”</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The Knights’ 4x1 squad will line up in semifinal action on Thursday, June 6, at 8:02 p.m. at Mike A. Myers Stadium in Austin, Texas.</p>','2019-05-29','2019-06-06','http://ucfknights.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34100&ATCLID=211804304','Megan Herboth','(407) 823-3213','mherboth@athletics.ucf.edu','Jenna Lee','Publish',165),(2908,'2019 Summer Knights Reading Challenge','2019-summer-knights-reading-challenge','<p>The Summer Knights Reading Challenge <strong>starts June 1 and ends August 1, 2019.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Open to all UCF students, faculty, and staff.</li>\n<li>It\'s easy! Just track the number of pages for each unique book read using this <a href=\"http://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_b2X5uwjBiXH6SQR\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">form</a> (available beginning Saturday, June 1).</li>\n<li>For e-books and audiobooks, simply verify the number of pages in the actual book using Amazon or another source.</li>\n<li>Reach the goal of reading 500 pages and win a prize pack!</li>\n<li>All participants will be entered into weekly drawings for gift cards and merchandise from<em> </em><em>BurgerFi, Catalyst Surf &amp; Skate, Ice &amp; Bites Cafe, Jeremiah\'s Italian Ice, KIND, Lazy Moon, Sport Clips, and Starbucks.</em></li>\n<li>The top four people* who read the most pages overall will win grand prizes. <br>(*Previous top prize winners are not eligible for top prizes.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span>Grand prize winners will be announced August 5.</span></p>','2019-06-10','2019-08-01','https://guides.ucf.edu/readingchallenge','Lindsey Ritzert','(407) 823-0000','lindsey.ritzert@ucf.edu','Jenna Lee','Publish',165),(2909,'Applied Project Management Certificate Program - Project Management Professional (PMP) - Classes start in June!','applied-project-management-certificate-program-project-management-professional-pmp-classes-starts-in-june','<p><strong>Want the Big Bucks? Get PMP-certified.</strong></p>\n<p>Those who are PMP-certified earn around 16% more than their non-certified counterparts. That works out to about $14,500 in real money. The short term challenge of gaining certification will pay off over the course of your career.</p>\n<p><strong>More benefits to PMP© Certification: </strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Earn a prestigious certification recognized around the globe.</li>\n<li>Build skills and knowledge that are transferable between industries, market segments and geographic locations.</li>\n<li>Gain an advantage over non-certified project managers.</li>\n<li>Prove your project management knowledge, commitment, and experience.</li>\n<li>Join a global network of over 774,000 PMP credential holders.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Expert guidance for PMP® exam success.</strong></p>\n<p>If you’re looking for an expert to lead your PMP exam preparation, interpret the content, and answer your questions, we can help! <a href=\"https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program/Applied-Project-Management-Certificate-Project-Management-Professional-PMP\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">UCF Continuing Education’s Applied Project Management Certificate Program</a> combines live instruction and discussion with <em>The CertWise® Learning System for PMP Exam Preparation</em> for an interactive, premium quality study experience. Prepare to pass the PMP exam and learn critical skills demanded by global employers.</p>\n<p><strong>Our summer course is filling quickly. Don’t miss out!</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Tuesday evenings</strong> <br> June 25 – September 10        <br> 5:30pm - 9:30pm <br> <br> UCF East Orlando location: Innovative Center <br> 3280 Progress Drive, Suite 700<br> Orlando, FL 32826</p>\n<p>Course fee is <strong>$2,495</strong> which includes course instruction, textbooks, materials and Continuing Education Units (CEUs). </p>\n<p>Discounted registration fee available for UCF Alumni, Staff, Faculty and Students of <strong>$2,395</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program-Search/954/Pmp-Project-Management-Professional---A-Premier-Classroom-Face-to-face-Program/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>REGISTER NOW</strong></a></p>','2019-05-30','2019-06-25','https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program/Applied-Project-Management-Certificate-Project-Management-Professional-PMP','Lisa Ruscigno','(407) 882-0337','Lisa.Ruscigno@ucf.edu','Lisa Ruscigno, UCF Continuing Education','Publish',30),(2911,'Fall 2019 Students: Are you interested in Jiu-Jitsu or Judo?','are-you-interested-in-jiu-jitsu-or-judo-and-need-2-credits-for-fall','<p>The <a href=\"../../../../college/health-professions-sciences/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">College of Health Professions and Sciences</a> has the following courses available for the Fall 2019 semester.</p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>***Exciting New Course***</strong></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PEM 2402 – Beginning Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu (2 credit hour elective)</strong></span></p>\n<p>Study and application of basic skills; falling, takedowns, ground techniques, basic self-defense, terminology, philosophy, culture and fitness training involved in Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu.</p>\n<p>PEM 2402 0001 (93429) – Tuesday - 10:30am-12:20pm</p>\n<p>PEM 2402 0002 (93430) – Thursday - 10:30am-12:20pm</p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong></strong></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PEM 2431 – Beginning Judo (2 credit hour elective)</strong></span></p>\n<p>Study and application of basic skills; falling, throwing, ground techniques, basic self-defense, terminology, philosophy and fitness training involved in the Olympic sport of Judo.</p>\n<p>PEM 2431 0001 (88774) – Wednesday - 12:20pm-2:20pm</p>\n<p>PEM 2431 0002 (88825) – Wednesday - 2:30pm-4:20pm</p>\n<p>PEM 2431 0001 (88774) – Tuesday – 7:00pm-8:50pm</p>\n<p></p>','2019-06-10','2019-08-10','https://healthprofessions.ucf.edu/healthsciences/judo/','SES Advising','(407) 823-0623','sesadvising@ucf.edu','Division of Kinesiology','Publish',13),(2913,'Special Lecture w/ Elena Gladun, Institute of State and Law at the University of Tyumen','test','<p>Professor Thomas Bryer and the School of Public Administration invite students, staff, and faculty for a special lecture with Elena Gladun, Doctor of Law and Professor at the Institute of State and Law, University of Tyumen in Russia.</p>\n<p>Date: June 25, 2019</p>\n<p>Time: 3:00 - 5:00 p.m. </p>\n<p>Location: HPA 1, Room 213 </p>\n<p><span>Elena Gladun is a Doctor of Law, Professor at the Institute of State and Law, the University of Tyumen, Russia. She leads the Research Division “Legal and economic frameworks for sustainable development of the northern territories in Russia”. Elena is the leader of Thematic Network “Arctic Law” in the National Arctic Consortium and a member of UArctic Thematic Network “Philosophy of Law in the Arctic”. For the last 15 years, the focus of her research is rights and interests of northern indigenous peoples and legal regulations of natural resource use and environmental protection in the Arctic. Prof Gladun teaches several master degree courses, including “Law and Policy for Sustainable Development of the Russian Arctic”, “Global Environmental Management”, “Legal Regulations of Petroleum Industry in Russia”.</span></p>\n<p>Please RSVP to <a href=\"mailto: thomas.bryer@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">Thomas Bryer</a>.</p>','2019-06-12','2019-06-26',NULL,'Thomas Bryer','(407) 823-2604','thomas.bryer@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Pending',155),(2914,'Changes Ahead to Bike-share Service at UCF','changes-ahead-to-bike-share-service-at-ucf','<p>At the close of summer session A, the Lime bike share program will end on the main campus. Starting June 21, Lime will remove the 600 pedal bikes from service.</p>\n<p>Lime is reevaluating its campus and city partnerships across the country. Based on the strong interest they\'ve seen for electric scooters, Lime is phasing out most of its bicycle options across the country. Our campus offices are working to evaluate what transportation services will most safely and effectively serve our students moving forward.</p>\n<p>Bike N Gold, UCF\'s bike share program hosted by the Student Government Association, will continue to offer free long-term bike rentals for periods of up to one semester.  For information, visit the bike shop located on the first floor of the Student Union, or call 407-823-6484.</p>\n<p>Pedestrian safety is of the utmost importance at UCF. For bicycle safety tips, see here:<a href=\"https://parking.ucf.edu/bicycles/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://parking.ucf.edu/bicycles/</a>.  For a map of bike racks around campus, see here:<a href=\"https://map.ucf.edu/bikeracks/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://map.ucf.edu/bikeracks/</a>.</p>\n<p>A mobile version of the map also is available on the UCF Mobile App.</p>','2019-06-27','2019-06-30',NULL,'Sustainability Initiatives','(407) 823-0960','sustainable@ucf.edu','Yara Watson','Publish',203),(2918,'Become an Effective Nurse Leader and Nurse Executive with UCF\'s Online MSN and DNP Programs','become-an-effective-nurse-leader-and-nurse-executive-with-ucfs-online-msn-and-dnp-programs','<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">The online<strong> MSN degree in Nursing Leadership and Management</strong> prepares students for advanced leadership roles by developing independent expertise in the critical analysis and evidence-based evaluation of complex problems associated with organizations and systems.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">The UCF College of Nursing also offers an online<strong> Nurse Executive Doctor of Nursing Practice (DNP) program</strong>. This program is a dynamic and engaging academic curriculum that prepares students for executive leadership and decision-making at the highest level by examining practice innovations and outcomes. The Nurse Executive DNP track extends and enhances the knowledge, skill and performance of healthcare system leaders in a wide variety of clinical and administrative environments.</span><br><br><span style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">Please join our information session to learn additional information about the programs listed above. Information on how to connect to the session is listed below: </span><br><br><span style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">Join Zoom Meeting:</span><br><a data-lynx-mode=\"hover\" href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fzoom.us%2Fj%2F212324429%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR3sUoD0hdmz8dTijIQBGXi2vMU-lwn8m_n8OWxjo3Tvpzjj7IxOMet6fqA&amp;h=AT33tSjV6wrHyNu1VCD6oQLoJq8ewo1iHjx6rh4UqN12UIWquvMK_qV2Gio_R389Z3KMf1rHMa2UCF0gK6rg207v4PbxMBM-RbAv5tZnY6gWXz88nqbMWafZsv-GhWSTrkvE\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\" target=\"_blank\">https://zoom.us/j/212324429</a><br><span style