,'Enhancing Relationships & Empowering Careers (For Couples)','enhancing-relationships-empowering-careers-for-couples-1-2-3','<p><strong><span>Holidays putting stress on your relationship?</span></strong><span>  Want to enjoy a <em><strong>date night</strong></em> with your partner? Parents, what about a <strong><em>FUN</em></strong> <strong>place for your child </strong>to enjoy and engage in arts and crafts? How about enjoy delicious, fresh, <em><strong>catered</strong></em><strong> </strong><em><strong>meals </strong></em>and<em> </em>earn up to <strong>$100 in <em>gift cards</em></strong>?  If you answered <strong><u>YES</u></strong> to any of the questions above, please <u>call</u> us at <strong>407-823-1748. </strong>Project Harmony offers couples the opportunity at <strong><em>NO COST </em></strong>to spend quality time together, while enhancing their ability to resolve conflicts, improve communication skills, and manage stress. The program also includes a workshop that can assist with financial goals, as well as help explore one’s strengths and experiences to create a more fulfilling career path. Workshops are available in both English and Spanish.</span></p>\n<p><span>Funding for this project was provided by the United States Department of Health and Human Services, Administration for Children and Families, Grant: # 90FM0078. These services are available to all eligible persons, regardless of race, gender, age, disability, or religion. Project Harmony is classified as a research study at the University of Central Florida, UCF IRB SBE-15-11828. This study is under the direction of Dr. Sejal Barden, Principal Investigator and Dr. Dalena Dillman Taylor, Co-Principal Investigator.</span></p>','2019-12-07','2019-12-07','https://mfri.ucf.edu/contact-us/','Project Harmony','(407) 823-1748','mfri@ucf.edu','Project Harmony at UCF','Pending',237),(3057,'Belinda Hyppolite - Farewell to an Outstanding Leader','dr-belinda-hyppolite-farewell-to-an-outstanding-leader','<p>It’s time to celebrate the contributions of one of UCF’s most outstanding leaders. <span>Assistant Vice President for Community Support </span>Belinda Hyppolite has been providing leadership and advocacy in the Division of Student Development and Enrollment Services, as well as in many other areas of the institution, for the past 15 years. She has accepted the position of vice president for Diversity and Inclusion and chief diversity officer at the University of Oklahoma, serving on the Norman, HSC and Tulsa Campuses, where she will begin work on Jan. 6, 2020.</p>\n<p>Hyppolite has worked as a professional in Higher Education for 23 years, serving in a variety of leadership roles and responsibilities. She started in Student Affairs working on retention efforts for at-risk students and working with the residential students within Housing and Residential Life. Hyppolite has supported and advocated for a number of student populations such as fraternity and sorority students, multicultural, low-income, first-generation, foster care, religious and non-religious, DACA/TPS, and undocumented students. Hyppolite has worked in Academic Affairs, Student Affairs, Greek Life, and Multicultural Affairs and has and continues to support and confront social justice issues plaguing student success.</p>\n<p>While we will miss her here, we want to send her off with suitable recognition of her many talents and successes. Toward that end, we will be having a reception on <strong>Dec. 10 from 3 to 5 p.m. in the Student Union Pegasus Ballroom. </strong>There will be an opportunity to share your message, either personally or publicly, starting at 3:30 p.m. Please join us if you are able. If not, be sure to say farewell to Hyppolite prior to the end of fall semester.</p>','2019-12-03','2019-12-11',NULL,'Cheryll Kinlaw','(407) 823-4242','CCheryll.Kinlaw@ucf.edu','Student Development and Enrollment Services','Publish',239),(3058,'Enhancing Relationships & Empowering Careers (For Couples)','en