o enjoy a <em><strong>date night</strong></em> with your partner? Parents, what about a <strong><em>FUN</em></strong> <strong>place for your child</strong> to enjoy and engage arts and crafts projects? How about enjoy delicious, fresh, <em><strong>catered</strong></em><strong> </strong><em><strong>meals </strong></em>and<em> </em>earn up to <strong>$100 in <em>gift cards</em></strong>?  If you answered <strong><u>YES</u></strong> to any of the questions above, please <u>call</u> us at <strong>407-823-1748. </strong>Project Harmony offers couples the opportunity at <strong><em>NO COST</em></strong> to spend quality time together, while enhancing their ability to resolve conflicts, improve communication skills, and manage stress. The program also includes a workshop that can assist with financial goals, as well as help explore one’s strengths and experiences to create a more fulfilling career path. </span></p>\n<p><span>Funding for this project was provided by the United States Department of Health and Human Services, Administration for Children and Families, Grant: # 90FM0078. These services are available to all eligible persons, regardless of race, gender, age, disability, or religion. Project Harmony is classified as a research study at the University of Central Florida, UCF IRB SBE-15-11828. This study is under the direction of Dr. Sejal Barden, Principal Investigator and Dr. Dalena Dillman Taylor, Co-Principal Investigator.</span></p>','2019-12-14','2019-12-14','https://mfri.ucf.edu/contact-us/','UCF Marriage and Family Research','(407) 823-1748','mfri@ucf.edu','UCF Marriage and Family Research Institute','Pending',242),(3060,'UCF Employee Appreciation Days at the UCF Bookstore','ucf-employee-appreciation-days-at-the-ucf-bookstore','<p>UCF Employees,</p>\n<p>Back by popular demand, the UCF Bookstore is going to host UCF Employee Appreciation Days.</p>\n<p>Show your Faculty or Staff ID at the John T. Washington Center Bookstore location on December 16 &amp; 17, to receive an additional 10% discount on UCF apparel and gifts. This means that your regular discount of 10% off is now doubled to 20% off!</p>\n<p>The additional discount applies to almost all UCF merchandise and general reading books, however, there are a few exclusions. The additional 10% discount does not include cosmetics, electronic gaming products, gift cards, cafe, convenience food/drink items, textbooks, digital books, special orders, and already discounted items. The additional discount is available in-store only and cannot be applied to any online purchases.</p>\n<p>For additional information, please visit the UCF Bookstore in the John T. Washington Center or call 407-823-6186.</p>','2019-12-13','2019-12-18',NULL,'Sue Gonzalez','(407) 823-3539','sue.gonzalez@ucf.edu','Sue Gonzalez','Pending',97),(3061,'UCF Urban Knights Meeting Fri Jan 10 at 6 PM','ucf-urban-knights-meeting-fri-jan-10-at-6-pm','<p>This meeting will begin at 6 PM. The meeting will take place at GAI Consultants at 618 E South St Ste 700, Orlando, Florida 32801. Suggested parking is on the 4th floor. Signs are posted on entry doors regarding access to the meeting.</p>\n<p><span>6 - 7 PM is a social and networking hour. At 7 PM, we will have a resume building and interview skills workshop. </span><br><br>We will discuss organization business as well as current job postings, ways to get involved and upcoming events.</p>\n<p>A meeting agenda will be available online via our social media and website, or via email, closer to the meeting date.<br><br>Current UCF students who are interested in our organization, urban planning and or public administration are welcomed to join and check us out.<br><br>E-mail urbanknights3@gmail.com with any questions, comments or concerns! We can also be found and contact on UCF Knight Connect, Instagram, Twitter, Facebook, and LinkedIn!</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/events/2535864593161016/?event_time_id=2656420704438737\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/events/2535864593161016/?event_time_id=2656420704438737</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://knightconnect.campuslabs.com/engage/event/5321788\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://knightconnect.campuslabs.com/engage/event/5321788</a></p>\n<p></p>','2020-01-04','2020-01-11','https://www.facebook.com/events/2535864593161016/?event_time_id=2656420704438737','Heather Croney, Urban Knights President','(321) 946-9752','heather.croney@knights.ucf.edu','Heather Croney, Urban Knights President','Pending',224),(3063,'Online Info Session: Research Administration Graduate Programs','online-info-session-research-administration-graduate-programs-1','<p>Are you a research administration professional looking to take the next steps in your career? Have you considered a graduate degree in research administration? UCF offers a graduate degree and graduate certificate in research administration. The fully online program focuses on cutting-edge research administration techniques and emphasizes a curriculum that can be designed to suit our specific needs. Learn more at the next online info session. </p>\n<p>Registration is required: <a href=\"https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/Feb1320\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/Feb1320</a></p>','2020-01-13','2020-02-13','https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/Feb1320','Angela White-Jones','(407) 823-5786','angela.white-jones@ucf.edu','School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3065,'Joust New Venture Competition 2020 Applications Open','joust-new-venture-competition-2020-applications-open','<p>The Joust New Venture Competition presented by Viatek celebrates the entrepreneurial efforts of student starters across our campus, introduces them to community leaders, and provides key resources to help launch their ventures. The top four ventures will earn up to $75,000 in cash and essential business services provided by some of our region’s most forward-thinking sponsors and donors.</p>\n<p>The Joust is open to all UCF students and accepts all types of venture proposals. This competition brings together big ideas, big prizes, and prominent leaders to create one of UCF’s most exciting student events.</p>','2020-01-27','2020-02-03','https://cel.ucf.edu/events/the-joust-new-venture-competition/','Kourtney Dinkins',NULL,'cel@bus.ucf.edu','Nicole Dudenhoefer','Publish',166),(3066,'Presentation on LOTIS, a GIS mapping program/tool','presentation-on-lotis-a-gis-mapping-programtool','<p>Come join UCF’s Masters in Urban and Regional Planning Students at the new UCF Downtown Campus for an exclusive presentation on LOTIS – an innovative GIS mapping program which overlays street network data with land parcel data to create an amazing interactive tool that helps planners identify opportunities in their community both from a transportation and land use perspective. </p>\n<p> Join us Wednesday, February 5, 2020, at the new UCF Downtown Campus in the </p>\n<p>Dr. Phillips Academic Commons in Classroom DPAC 152 starting at 6:00 pm</p>\n<p>528 W Livingston Street </p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Please RSVP to ehanna@casselberry.org.  </p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Use SunRail or LYMMO Lime Route to get there! Creative Village has limited on-street parking; use the “ParkMobile” app to pay.</p>','2020-01-14','2020-02-06','https://www.facebook.com/events/749679802194869/','Heather Croney','(321) 946-9752','heather.croney@knights.ucf.edu','Heather Croney, President of Urban Knights','Publish',224),(3068,'Congratulations USPS Employee of the Month, Det. Melissa Guadagnino','usps-employee-of-the-month-december-2019-det-melissa-guadagnino','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for December 2019 – Detective 1st Class, Melissa Guadagnino. Her nominators, Sergeant James Mangan and Sergeant Pablo Vargas, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>“Detective Guadagnino’s dedication and commitment (along with solid detective work) is evident in every case she works. She constantly volunteers for the toughest cases, the hardest assignments and works tirelessly to keep our community safe. </em></p>\n<p><em>          “Detective Guadagnino has served the UCFPD Community for six years and has truly made the community a safe place to live, learn, and work. Without her, UCF would not be as successful in offering high-quality education, student development or research. She assists students to further their civic responsibility by putting a criminal in the criminal justice process. She has shown an unwavering commitment to UCF’s mission, vision and values.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Detective Guadagnino receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, his name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. He is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf</a></p>','2020-01-17','2020-01-24','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3074,'#UCFinSpace Men\'s Basketball Game Set For Feb. 9','ucfinspace-mens-basketball-game-set-for-feb-9','<p><span>The first #UCFinSpace Men\'s Basketball game is set for Feb. 9 vs. Tulsa at Addition Financial Arena. The Knights will wear custom-made Nike uniforms featuring UCF\'s first unofficial mascot, the Citronaut, and canaveral blue to represent the sky and ocean off Cape Canaveral, Florida.</span><br><br><span>#UCFinSpace merchandise in on sale now at </span><a href=\"https://ucf.shoptruespirit.com/shop/ucf-athletics-t/home\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ShopUCFKnights.com</a><span> and at the Barnes and Noble on East Plaza Drive.</span></p>\n<p><span><a href=\"https://www1.ticketmaster.com/ucf-knights-mens-basketball-vs-tulsa-golden-hurricane-mens-basketball/event/2200574FD9F0B309?brand=ucf&amp;utm_source=Website&amp;utm_medium=SIDEARM&amp;utm_content=1920MBBSchedulePage&amp;utm_campaign=1920MBBTulsa\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Buy tickets through UCF Athletics</a> for the game.</span></p>','2020-02-06','2020-02-10','https://ucfknights.com/news/2020/1/22/-m-basketball-ucfinspace-mens-basketball-game-set-for-feb-9.aspx','UCF Athletics','(407) 823-3213','acesarano@athletics.ucf.edu','UCF Athletics','Publish',165),(3075,'Autodesk Educational Workshops','autodesk-educational-workshops','<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong>Wednesday, February 12</strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">3039 Technology Parkway Orlando, FL</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">Partnership Building 3, Room 233</span><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">Introduction to Autodesk Fusion 360</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">9 a.m. - noon</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">In this hands-on workshop you’ll learn how to start modeling and collaborating in Fusion 360. Fusion 360 is the world’s first cloud-based 3D CAD, CAM, and CAE platform. It brings teams together for collaborative product development, allowing them to work virtually anywhere, with anyone. Fusion 360 is compatible with Macs and PCs.</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\"> </span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">Introduction to Generative Design</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">1 p.m. - 4 p.m.</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">In this hands-on workshop, you’ll learn how to use Generative Design functionality in Fusion 360 to harnesses the computational power of the cloud to explore numerous design options. You can use Generative Design to solve complex engineering problems, such as:</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">            • Consolidating parts by reducing the overall number of parts and components</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">            • Reducing the weight of parts and components by using the least amount of material to make the part as effective as possible</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">            • Increasing performance by designing stronger parts and components</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"> </p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">What to Bring:</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">1. Laptop with Fusion 360 installed and activated (instructions will be given after sign up)</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">2. A mouse and power supply for laptop</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\"> </span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">REGISTRATION REQUIRED!</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">LIMITED SPACE!</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\"> </span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">These are free educational workshops courtesy of Autodesk. Contact Jessica Compton to sign up or if you have any questions.</span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><span style=\"font-weight: inherit;\">jcompton@ist.ucf.edu</span></p>','2020-02-03','2020-02-13',NULL,'Jessica Compton','(407) 882-0297','jcompton@ist.ucf.edu','School of Modeling Simulation and Training','Publish',247),(3076,'Leadership Week 2020','leadership-week-2020-1','<p>Leadership Week — a series of events that highlight leadership, service and social change —<strong> </strong>is coordinated by the LEAD Scholars Academy and supported by the UCF Student Government Association and numerous offices and departments throughout the university. Students, faculty, and staff are invited to attend all events, which range from lectures, programs, and workshops intended to educate the campus community.</p>\n<p>This year, we are celebrating the 20th anniversary of Leadership Week, marking two decades of quality knowledge, student growth and strengthening the community during <strong>February 17-22</strong>. This year\'s theme is centered around People, Purpose, &amp; Passion: The Pathway to Success. </p>\n<p>Please see our website (<a href=\"https://na01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Flsa.sdes.ucf.edu%2Fleadershipweek%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7CGermayne.Graham%40ucf.edu%7C9c6e87311445425fc21b08d68c79d767%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C636850853843431317&amp;sdata=9gH9S5FZHk%2FYDIN7HF1BZr88AiUibhdmttPc8zVRrp4%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://lsa.sdes.ucf.edu/leadershipweek/</a>) for more details, information on our keynote speakers, and our calendar. If you have any questions, please contact Germayne Graham <a href=\"mailto:Germayne.Graham@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">Germayne.Graham@ucf.edu</a> or Leah Freeman  <a href=\"mailto:leahfreeman@Knights.ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">leahfreeman@Knights.ucf.edu</a>.</p>','2020-02-10','2020-02-22','https://lsa.sdes.ucf.edu/leadershipweek/','Germayne Graham','(407) 823-2223','germayne.graham@ucf.edu','Germayne Graham','Publish',41),(3080,'USPS Staff Council Spring Scholarships Available','usps-staff-council-spring-scholarships-available','<p>The USPS Staff Council is now accepting applications for the Spring 2020 Scholarship awards.  Apply now at the Staff Council web site, (<a href=\"http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/</a>) or on the USPSP Staff Council Facebook page.  There are two awards available, the USPS Staff Council Employee Scholarship and the Barnes &amp; Noble Campus Book Award.  Dependents of USPS Staff may apply for the Campus Bookstore Award.  Applications must be submitted by 11:59 p.m. February 20th, 2020.  You may apply for one or both of the awards if you wish.   The only restrictions are: you must be a member of the USPS for a minimum of one year, and if you have won an award you must wait one year before applying for that particular award again.  Apply now and avoid the rush!</p>','2020-02-05','2017-02-20','http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/','Jamie Lamoreaux','(407) 882-0191','lamoreaj@ucf.edu','Jamie LaMoreaux','Pending',54),(3084,'USPS Staff Council Spring Scholarships Available','usps-staff-council-spring-scholarships-available-1-2-3-4','<p><span>The USPS Staff Council is now accepting applications for the Spring 2020 Scholarship awards.  Apply now at the Staff Council web site, (</span><a href=\"http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/</a><span>) or on the Council Facebook page. There are two awards available: the USPS Staff Council Employee Scholarship and the Barnes &amp; Noble Campus Book awards. </span></p>\n<p><span> Dependents of USPS Staff may apply for the campus bookstore award. Applications must be submitted by 11:59 p.m. February 20, 2020. You may apply for one or both of the awards. The only restrictions are you must be a member of the USPS for a minimum of one year, and if you have won an award you must wait one year before applying for that particular award again.</span></p>','2020-02-06','2020-02-21','http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/','Jamie Lamoreaux','(407) 882-0191','lamoreaj@ucf.edu','Jamie LaMoreaux','Publish',54),(3087,'USPS Employee of the Month - November 2019 Abner Ramos','usps-employee-of-the-month-november-2019-abner-ramos','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for November 2019: Abner Ramos. Abner is the Facilities Scheduler in the UCF College of Medicine. He has worked at UCF since July 2015. His nominators, Daniel Topping and Jennifer Mark, had this to say about him:</p>\n<p><em>          “Abner has been a cornerstone of operations and safety for the College of Medicine. He is courteous to everyone – employees, students, and most importantly, the visitors and guests. He stands out as a calm presence and makes an excellent first impression for the college. </em></p>\n<p><em>          He has personally helped UCF and the College of Medicine to be a major presence in the community through his integrity and dedication.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Mr. Ramos receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, his name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. He is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf</a></p>','2020-02-07','2020-02-17','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3088,'Wednesday is Knugget Knight at UCF Women\'s Basketball','wednesday-is-knugget-knight-at-ucf-womens-basketball','<p><span>Everyone\'s favorite mini horse, Knugget, will be hosting his own special night at the UCF women\'s basketball team\'s War on I4 matchup against rival USF on Wednesday night. </span></p>\n<p><span>Knugget will be at Addition Financial Arena on Feb. 19 to greet fans and 1,000 Knugget b</span><span>obbleheads will be available on a first-come, first-served basis</span><span>.</span><span> Doors open at 5 p.m. and tipoff against the Bulls is slated for 6 p.m.</span><span></span></p>','2020-02-17','2020-02-19','https://ucfknights.com/sports/womens-basketball/schedule','UCF Athletics','(407) 823-3213','cwalsh@athletics.ucf.edu','UCF Athletics','Publish',165),(3091,'Can Government Accountants Save the World? An International Scholar Presentation','can-government-accountants-save-the-world-an-international-scholar-presentation-w-dr-fred-mear','<p><span>Join the UCF Center for Public and Nonprofit Management for a special presentation from international scholar, Dr. Fred Mear! Mear is qualified as a public sector accountant (CIPFA) &amp; private sector accountant (FCCA) and will be discussing his research on what elements of the PFM system impact corruption perception. Over the last 30 years, Mear has worked as an academic with over 30 countries, including Sub Saharan African and Transition Economies. </span><br><br><span>As part of the aid effectiveness agenda, comparable information is available on over 100 developing countries and the relationships between different aspects of PFM systems and corruption perception. This research has identified some interesting conclusions on what elements of a PFM system impact a country\'s overall corruption and brings out some surprising results.</span></p>\n<p><span>The discussion will be held on February 26, 2020 from 1:30 - 3:00pm in the Dr. Phillips Academic Commons, room 455 at UCF Downtown. </span></p>','2020-02-19','2020-02-27','https://ccie.ucf.edu/cpnm/','Justin Miller','(407) 823-3794','justin.miller@ucf.edu','UCF Center for Public and Nonprofit Management','Publish',155),(3093,'Abner Ramos is USPS Employee of the Month (November 2019)','usps-employee-of-the-month-november-2019-abner-ramos-1','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for November 2019: Abner Ramos. Ramos is the facilities scheduler in the UCF College of Medicine. He has worked at UCF since July 2015. His nominators, Dr. Daniel Topping and Jennifer Mark, had this to say about him:</p>\n<p><em>          “Abner has been a cornerstone of operations and safety for the College of Medicine. He is courteous to everyone – employees, students, and most importantly, the visitors and guests. He stands out as a calm presence and makes an excellent first impression for the college. </em></p>\n<p><em>          He has personally helped UCF and the College of Medicine to be a major presence in the community through his integrity and dedication.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Ramos receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, his name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. He is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf</a></p>','2020-02-20','2020-02-27','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3094,'Ida Cerezo is USPS Employee of the Month (January 2020)','usps-employee-of-the-month-january-2020-ida-cerezo','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for January 2020 – Ida Cerezo. Cerezo is the administrative assistant in SDES – Recreation and Wellness Center. She has worked for UCF since July 2004. Her nominators, Michelle Fitzgerald and Sarah Hunt, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>          “Ida demonstrates commitment to UCF’s mission and goals daily by her excellent customer service to the community, students and staff. She works with integrity and passion and makes the Recreation and Wellness Center a great place to work and visit.</em></p>\n<p><em>Ida models a supportive community as she embraces and values a diverse range of people at RWC. She contacts with many student employees and consistently shows high performance in how well she interacts with them. She is dedicated to ensuring students have a positive experience at UCF.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Cerezo receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf</a></p>','2020-02-20','2020-02-27','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process-2019-20.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3095,'Stephania Hayes is USPS Employee of the Month (February 2020)','usps-employee-of-the-month-february-2020-stephania-hayes','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for February 2020 – Stephania Hayes</p>\n<p>Stephania Hayes is the administrative assistant in the College of Engineering and Computer Sciences. She has worked at UCF since 2012. Her nominators, Nina Leonard and Kim Small, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>          “Stephania’s consistency, regardless of the situation, is what prompted this nomination. Our office recently went through major staff changes; however, she has remained consistent in ensuring the front desk is staffed and available to address student’s concerns. She exhibits great integrity, teamwork, and consistency in her position.</em></p>\n<p><em>          Stephania, as the first point of contact in our office, helps our mission by welcoming students to our office and to our college. Providing a high-quality student development is about UCF’s mission. Stephania has implemented a training program for our assistants geared toward professional development enabling many of our assistants to obtain internships with companies.” </em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Ms. Hayes receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>','2020-02-26','2020-03-06','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Debbie Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3098,'Upcoming UCF 4th Annual Health Fair','upcoming-ucf-4th-annual-health-fair','<p><span>When: Tuesday, March 17, 2020 </span><span>10 a.m.</span><span> </span><span>to 2:30 p.m.<br>Where: Key West Ballroom</span></p>\n<p><span>Join us at the 4th Annual UCF Health Fair!</span><br><span>Includes FREE health screenings, health educations, food, giveaways, and more! Event open to all</span></p>','2020-03-05','2020-03-17','https://www.facebook.com/events/128937145190867/?active_tab=about','Fatima Bawaney','(321) 609-1202','maps.vpoperations@gmail.com','Multicultural Association of Pre Health Students','Pending',69),(3099,'Provide your Feedback: UCF Equity, Inclusion, and Diversity Climate Survey','ucf-equity-inclusion-and-diversity-climate-survey','<p>The Office of Diversity and Inclusion in partnership with <span>Campus </span><span>Climate</span><span> </span><span>Survey</span><span>s, LLC is excited to announce that the Viewfinder Campus </span><span>Climate</span><span> </span><span>Survey for UCF. You will receive an email from Campus Climate Surveys, LLC on Feb 24 asking for your participation in the survey and will receive reminder emails every few days if you have not taken the survey.eminder</span></p>\n<p><span>Participation is voluntary and the survey is intended to help UCF leadership and the Office of Diversity and Inclusion to <strong></strong></span>better understand UCF’s diversity, equity, and inclusion climate.</p>\n<p>Please take a moment to complete the survey and lend your voice to this effort. </p>','2020-03-05','2020-03-15',NULL,'Kent Butler','(407) 823-6479','diverse@ucf.edu','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','Publish',138),(3101,'Apply for UCF Alumni Scholarships','ucf-alumni-scholarships-open-1','<p><strong>UCF Alumni\'s scholarship applications are open until midnight on March 29, 2020.</strong></p>\n<p>Each year UCF Alumni Engagement and Annual Giving awards scholarships to UCF students demonstrating strong academic ability and significant extracurricular and community involvement. UCF Alumni Engagement and Annual Giving is pleased to again offer more than a dozen scholarship opportunities for the 2020-2021 academic year.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Applications are now available on A2O: Access to Opportunities (<a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.academicworks.com%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7CLiz.Irizarry%40ucf.edu%7C8bcd41f128cf442d649008d7c4f929d1%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637194447041110490&amp;sdata=XgoNT7IYRbkA5KlOoOS3ojRHR%2BUV8js6hwOSJUxcEtg%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucf.academicworks.com</a>). You are encouraged to apply for as many scholarships for which you are eligible.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>How to apply through A2O: </strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Read all scholarship criteria online at <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucfalumni.com%2Fget-involved%2Fstudents%2Fscholarships&amp;data=02%7C01%7CLiz.Irizarry%40ucf.edu%7C8bcd41f128cf442d649008d7c4f929d1%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637194447041120486&amp;sdata=sYD%2FAENRo9AvJRYMrkpZR5xBUErjSgMqMxjClChJ57c%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucfalumni.com/get-involved/students/scholarships</a> to determine which you may be eligible for.</li>\n<li>Log in to A2O: Access to Opportunities (<a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.academicworks.com%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7CLiz.Irizarry%40ucf.edu%7C8bcd41f128cf442d649008d7c4f929d1%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637194447041130479&amp;sdata=Cib7DvNWT937XYEH4gmw8ygi2PRfQqZOfynCtbAA3Xo%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucf.academicworks.com</a>).</li>\n<li>Complete the general application if this is your first time logging in.</li>\n<li>Browse available scholarships &gt; click “Opportunities” and select “Ours” then search for the specific scholarship you are looking for.</li>\n<li>Complete and submit application(s) and all required supporting documents.</li>\n</ol>\n<p> </p>\n<p>*No paper applications will be accepted. Scholarship applications are only available online through the A2O portal. You will only see scholarships for which you meet the basic eligibility requirements.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>IMPORTANT! Please read each scholarship application carefully to make sure you meet ALL of the specific criteria required for each scholarship before applying. Criteria used to determine eligibility includes, but is not limited to: GPA, class standing, academic program and campus involvement. If you do not see a particular scholarship, you do not meet one or more of the basic eligibility requirements (refer to our FAQs at <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucfalumni.com%2Fget-involved%2Fstudents%2Fscholarships&amp;data=02%7C01%7CLiz.Irizarry%40ucf.edu%7C8bcd41f128cf442d649008d7c4f929d1%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637194447041140478&amp;sdata=bj7g9jo7blpU%2BYQlRXWR1D%2BAKqXzTRne6ArJylLz0Es%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucfalumni.com/get-involved/students/scholarships</a>).</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Scholarships Available:</strong></p>\n<p>- <strong>Charles N. &amp; Frances Millican Scholarship: </strong>Senior serving in a leadership role</p>\n<p>- <strong>Jack &amp; Monica Thorsen Veteran Scholarship: </strong>Any class standing, served in the U.S. Military</p>\n<p>- <strong>Phoenix Scholarship: </strong>Non-traditional student, junior class standing</p>\n<p>- <strong>St. Onge Family Leadership Endowed Scholarship: </strong>Undergrad, sophomore or junior class standing serving in a leadership role</p>\n<p>- <strong>UCF Alumni Fellows Leadership Scholarship:</strong> Any class standing</p>\n<p>- <strong>UCF Alumni Legacy Scholarship: </strong>Undergrad, any class standing, parent/grandparent/legal guardian are UCF graduates</p>\n<p>- <strong>Amy G. Buchman, \'95, Memorial Endowed Scholarship:</strong> Any class standing, permanent resident of Tampa Bay area.</p>\n<p>- <strong>College of Business Administration Alumni Chapter Scholarship:</strong> Junior, senior or graduate student class standing enrolled in the College of Business Administration</p>\n<p>- <strong>Debbie K. Phillis Space Coast UCF Alumni Chapter Endowed Scholarship: </strong>Any class standing, permanent resident of Brevard County in Florida</p>\n<p>- <strong>Dr. William K. Grasty Memorial Scholarship:</strong> Undergrad, junior or senior in the Nicholson School of Communication</p>\n<p>- <strong>Lee A. Dumas Memorial Endowed Scholarship:</strong> Any class standing, permanent resident of Volusia/Flagler counties in Florida</p>\n<p>- <strong>UCF Regional Alumni Chapter/Club Scholarships:</strong></p>\n<p>+<u>Jacksonville UCF Alumni Club Scholarship:</u> Any class standing, permanent resident of Duval, Clay, St. Johns or Nassau counties in Florida</p>\n<p>+<u>Southeast Florida Knights Scholarship:</u> Any class standing, permanent resident of Dade or Broward counties in Florida, preference to those who are incoming freshman</p>\n<p>+<u>Tampa Bay Knights Legacy Scholarship:</u> Any class standing, permanent resident of the Tampa Bay Area, preference to those whose parent/grandparent/legal guardian are UCF graduates</p>\n<p>+<u>Chicago UCF Alumni Chapter Scholarship:</u> Any class standing, preference given to a UCF student from the state of Illinois. </p>\n<p><strong>The deadline to apply has been is midnight Sunday, March 29, 2020. Late, incomplete or paper applications will not be considered.</strong></p>\n<p> Questions? Email scholarships@ucfalumni.com or call 407-823-2586</p>','2020-03-12','2020-03-28','https://ucfalumni.com/get-involved/students/scholarships','Carolina Silva','(407) 823-2274','carolina.silva@ucf.edu','Office of Advancement, UCF Alumni Engagement and Annual Giving','Publish',44),(3104,'UCF Classes Moving Online Until March 27: Students Asked Not to Return to Campus','ucf-classes-moving-online-until-march-27-students-asked-not-to-return-to-campus','<p>The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) continues to rapidly evolve. While no cases have been reported at the university, <strong>UCF will move to remote instruction effective</strong> <strong>Monday, March 16</strong>, to minimize health and safety risks to the UCF community, especially as students and faculty prepare to return from Spring Break. <span><strong>Remote instruction will continue for at least two weeks. </strong></span>Fourteen days is the period in which secondary transmission to others is thought to be highest, and UCF advises against any additional travel during this time.</p>\n<p><strong>Because courses are being moved online, students should not to come back to campus for the next two weeks. </strong>Students should stay at or return to their permanent residences. Residence halls will remain open for residents who do not have an alternative place to stay, and certain campus services may not be available.</p>\n<p><span>All UCF campuses will remain open for employees, who are expected to continue working. Student employees should contact their supervisors for guidance.</span></p>\n<p><span>For the latest updates and FAQs, visit </span><a href=\"https://ucf.edu/safety/coronavirus\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucf.edu/safety/coronavirus</a></p>\n<p>Additional information is also available at <a href=\"../../news/coronavirus-awareness-and-guidance/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucf.edu/news/coronavirus-awareness-and-guidance</a></p>','2020-03-16','2020-03-27',NULL,'UCF Communications',NULL,'Today@ucf.edu','UCF Communications','Publish',166),(3107,'2020 Florida TaxWatch Productivity Awards - Nominations Now Open!','2020-florida-taxwatch-productivity-awards-nominations-now-open','<p>Since 1989, the Florida TaxWatch Productivity Awards program has publicly recognized and rewarded state employees and teams whose work significantly and measurably increases productivity and promotes innovation to improve the delivery of state services and save money for Florida taxpayers and businesses. Over the 30-year program, more than 16,000 nominations have been submitted, totaling $10 billion in cost savings, cost avoidances, and added value to the lives of Florida’s residents and visitors.</p>\n<p>Any employee of the state of Florida can nominate themself, a colleague, or a team of employees that meet the nomination criteria. Nominations should reflect an innovative or outstanding idea or practice that has led or will lead to taxpayer saving, improved service delivery, or overall taxpayer value. (Note: In-unit faculty are not eligible.)</p>\n<p>Whether through developing a creative new process, improving the quality and speed of our interactions with the public, or showing great initiative in tackling a problem to help our constituents, UCF has many initiatives that would qualify for these awards.</p>\n<p>To nominate yourself, a colleague, or a team, visit the Florida TaxWatch website: <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ftpa.floridataxwatch.org%2FInstructions&amp;data=02%7C01%7CLee.Williams%40ucf.edu%7Ceca8fe89180c43764b4a08d7c76269cf%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637197097798216407&amp;sdata=%2BVsKbbTEbk%2BBqGRAPmkKT4IryHq379Li0TTfACnipAM%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://tpa.floridataxwatch.org/Instructions</a><span>. <strong>The nomination window closes May 1.</strong></span></p>','2020-03-16','2020-05-01','https://tpa.floridataxwatch.org','HR Learning & Organizational Effectiveness','(407) 823-0440','HRLearning@ucf.edu','Lee Williams','Publish',24),(3108,'Sick Leave Pool Open Enrollment','sick-leave-pool-open-enrollment-1-2-3','<p>The UCF Sick Leave Pool open enrollment is March 1-31, 2020. To be eligible for membership, applicants must be employed with UCF continuously for at least one year and have accrued 64 hours of sick leave as of March 2020. New members are required to donate 16 hours of their sick leave; part-time employees will donate an amount proportionate to their FTE. Membership reply letters will be sent to new applicants by early April 2020.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Please note that if you are a current member of the Sick Leave Pool, you do not need to rejoin during open enrollment. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Interested faculty and staff should send <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/SLPApplication.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">applications</a> to the Human Resources Leave Administration section at <a href=\"mailto:loaandworkcomp@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">loaandworkcomp@ucf.edu</a></p>','2020-03-19','2020-03-31','http://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/leave-and-general-attendance-information/sick-leave-pools','HR Leave Administration','(407) 823-0540','loaandworkcomp@ucf.edu','UCF Human Resources','Publish',62),(3109,'UCF\'s Mindfulness Mondays on Instagram','new-ucfs-mindfulness-mondays-on-instagram','<p>Give your brain a breather. Beginning Monday, April 6, UCF will start its Mindfulness Monday series on Instagram Live.</p>\n<p>Every Monday at noon, a representative from UCF Counseling and Psychological Services (CAPS) will lead a live meditation session through <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">@ucf.edu</a> on Instagram. The practice will last 10-20 minutes. </p>\n<p></p>','2020-04-01','2020-05-20','https://www.instagram.com/ucf.edu/','@ucf.edu',NULL,'today@ucf.edu','UCF','Publish',165),(3110,'Marching Knight Drumline, Colorguard, Dance, and Majorette Auditions','marching-knight-drumline-colorguard-dance-and-majorette-auditions','<p>The UCF Marching Knights is proud to announcements auditions for the 2020 drumline, colorguard, dance, and majorette teams. Video auditions will be accepted through Saturday, May 16, 2020. To be considered for one of these amazing teams within the Marching Knights, please visit <a href=\"http://www.ucfbands.com\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.ucfbands.com</a> or contact Dr. Tremon Kizer, director of the Marching Knights for details.</p>\n<p><span>The UCF Marching Knights are the largest and most visible student organization at the University of Central Florida. They are known for their high-energy performances, unique and contemporary drill designs, and musical selections including genres such as Jazz, Pop, Classical, Soundtracks, and more. The 375+ members experience the thrill of performing for tens of thousands of fans each year at UCF Football games, high school exhibitions, local parades, and bowl and championship games. With a commitment to excellence in performance, both on and off the field, the Marching Knights truly are “The Pride of Central Florida.”</span></p>','2020-04-08','2020-05-16','http://www.ucfbands.com','Tremon Kizer','(407) 823-2212','tkizer@ucf.edu','UCF Marching Knights, Dr. Tremon Kizer- Director','Publish',75),(3112,'Online Info Session: Research Administration Graduate Programs','online-info-session-research-administration-graduate-programs-1-2','<p>Are you a research administration professional looking to take the next steps in your career? Have you considered a graduate degree in research administration? UCF offers a graduate degree and graduate certificate in research administration. The fully online program focuses on cutting-edge research administration techniques and emphasizes a curriculum that can be designed to suit your specific needs. Learn more at the next online info session. </p>\n<p><a href=\"https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/May1420\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Registration</a><span> </span>is required. </p>','2020-04-21','2020-05-15','https://ccie.ucf.edu/public-administration/research-administration/','Angela White-Jones','(407) 823-5786','angela.white-jones@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3113,'UCF Health Expands Telehealth Services For New, Established Patients','ucf-health-expands-telehealth-services-for-new-established-patients','<p>UCF Health, the <a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&amp;rls=en&amp;q=ucf+e+College+of+Medicine&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;oe=UTF-8\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">College of Medicine</a> physician practice, is extending its telehealth services, adding more specialties to the platform and offering care via computer or phone to new and established patients.</p>\n<p>The expansion comes as healthcare providers nationwide respond to the challenges of the COVID-19 pandemic and social distancing orders from local and state governments.</p>\n<p>UCF Health uses a HIPAA-compliant Zoom system where patients talk to their provider without having to visit the clinic. Telehealth provides effective, secure and safe non-contact visits for a variety of conditions, such as follow-up visits, skin ailments and ongoing management of diseases like diabetes.</p>\n<p><span>New </span><span>patients can use telehealth to establish their care at UCF Health and then follow-up with in-person or further telehealth services. Established patients can use telehealth for visits needed for prescription refills or for ongoing care for chronic conditions.</span></p>\n<p>UCF Health accepts most major insurance plans and provides primary and specialty care at two locations – on University Boulevard just blocks from the UCF main campus and in Lake Nona’s Medical City. All physicians are faculty at the UCF College of Medicine. </p>\n<p> <em>Please visit <a href=\"https://med.ucf.edu/news/ucf-health-expands-telehealth-services-for-new-established-patients/ucfhealth.com\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucfhealth.com</a> for information on the UCF Health specialties using telehealth care, FAQs and how to set up a Zoom appointment. Those interested in scheduling a telehealth visit should call 407-266-DOCS (3627).</em></p>','2020-04-21','2020-07-31','https://ucfhealth.com','UCF Health','(407) 266-3627','N/A','UCF Health','Publish',166),(3114,'Virtual Career Resources for UCF Students','virtual-career-resources-for-ucf-students','<p>As we continue to remain focused on social distancing and student success – retention, graduation and career readiness – Career Services is excited to share some resources recently added to the <a href=\"https://career.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Career Services website</a> to assist students looking for work in the current environment. </p>\n<ol>\n<li>A live feed of remote job opportunities for employers who are currently hiring on the <a href=\"https://career.ucf.edu/stayconnected/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Stay Connected with Us </strong>webpage</a>.</li>\n<li>A <a href=\"https://career.ucf.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/11/2020/04/Career-Toolbox-for-COVID-19_UCFCareerServices2020.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Career Toolkit during COVID-19</a>.</li>\n<li>An updated list of <a href=\"https://learn.joinhandshake.com/students/hiring-on-handshake-500/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">500 companies hiring students</a> through UCF Handshake. More than 50,000 UCF students and alumni are already registered on the UCF Handshake account. </li>\n</ol>\n<p>New students, or those currently looking for part-time and full-time employment, should access Handshake if they wish to search jobs, schedule a virtual one-on-one session with a career counselor, or attend one of the many virtual events career services will be hosting now through the summer.</p>\n<p>Students who need assistance or have questions can contact Career Services at <a href=\"mailto:career@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">career@ucf.edu</a>.</p>\n<p> </p>','2020-04-21','2020-06-01','https://career.ucf.edu/stayconnected/','Career Services','(407) 823-2361','career@ucf.edu','Career Services','Publish',165),(3115,'Drive-through COVID-19 Testing in Lake Nona Begins April 29','drive-through-covid-19-testing-in-lake-nona-begins-april-29','<p>Starting Wednesday, April 29, a COVID-19 drive-through testing site will open in Lake Nona through a partnership between UCF\'s College of Medicine, Aventus Health and Tavistock.</p>\n<p>The testing is by appointment only for people across the community. Patients must have a test order from a physician. Testing is covered by insurance. Those without insurance can get a free test through federal assistance.</p>\n<p>Appointments will be available from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Friday in the parking lot behind UCF Lake Nona Cancer Center, located at 6400 Sanger Road, Orlando, FL 32827. Appointments may end before 5 p.m. if the 250 daily appointments are filled earlier.</p>\n<p>Public health officials stay more widespread testing is key in getting our community, state and nation back to “normal.” Screening those who show symptoms allows us to identify and treat those who are ill, identify those they came in contact with and tell them they must isolate to stop further spread.</p>\n<p>COVID-19 symptoms include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fever</li>\n<li>Cough</li>\n<li>Shortness of breath or difficulty breathing</li>\n<li>Chills</li>\n<li>Repeated shaking with chills</li>\n<li>Muscle pain</li>\n<li>Headache</li>\n<li>Sore throat</li>\n<li>New loss of taste or smell</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you wish to be tested, follow these steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>If you have an order for a test from your healthcare provider:<span> </span></strong>Call Aventus Health directly to schedule a testing appointment: 407-986-0133.</li>\n<li><strong>If you are a patient at UCF Health — the College of Medicine’s physician practice — or are a UCF employee:<span> </span></strong>Contact UCF Health to obtain an order for a test by calling:<span> </span><a target=\"_blank\">407-266-3627</a></li>\n<li><strong>If you do not have a provider or need to speak to a physician about getting a test:<span> </span></strong>Get in touch with Aventus Health directly by calling:<span> </span><a target=\"_blank\">855-282-4860</a><span> </span>or 407-986-0133.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After the patient has been screened by a provider, Aventus will reach out to complete all necessary paperwork, including insurance coverage and schedule an appointment for testing. Upon arrival during a scheduled time, individuals will drive through and receive the testing with a swab designated specifically for them. Following the 10-minute test, they’ll receive results in 24 to 48 hours.</p>\n<p>The College of Medicine site is the second UCF drive-through testing location. <a href=\"../../news/covid-19-testing-site-to-open-at-ucf-monday-in-partnership-with-aventus-biolabs/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">COVID-19 testing continues on the main campus in Garage A</a>.</p>\n<p>For more information, please visit<span> </span><a href=\"https://aventushealth.com/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">AventusHealth.com</a></p>','2020-04-29','2020-07-31',NULL,'UCF Health','(407) 266-3627','N/A','UCF Health','Publish',166),(3116,'Get Involved with #GivingTuesdayNow on May 5','get-involved-with-givingtuesdaynow-on-may-5','<p>#GivingTuesdayNow is a day to celebrate the creative ways humans around the world have been helping each other during the pandemic, as well as to rally support for frontline workers, organizations, and individuals who are impacted by COVID-19.</p>\n<p>Ways to participate in UCF\'s #GivingTuesdayNow:</p>\n<p>-Sign up to be a volunteer<br>-Make a gift<br>-Attend a virtual event<br>-Write a note of appreciation to a Knight Nurse<br><br>For more information about this national movement, visit <a href=\"https://ucfalumni.com/givingtuesdaynow\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucfalumni.com/givingtuesdaynow</a>. </p>','2020-05-04','2020-05-06','https://ucfalumni.com/givingtuesdaynow','UCF Alumni','(407) 823-2586','knights@ucfalumni.com','UCF Alumni','Publish',165),(3117,'Ways to Help During Nurses Week','ways-to-help-during-nurses-week','<p>May 6-12 marks a special National Nurses’ Week, held during the World Health Organization’s Year of the Nurse in honor of Florence Nightingale’s 200th birthday.</p>\n<p>Now, more than ever, it is important to show our support for these healthcare heroes.</p>\n<p>Here are a few ideas:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sponsor a meal:</strong> Order food from a restaurant to be delivered to nurses hard at work at a hospital in Central Florida. Adopt a unit you’re connected to or one at <a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Hospital-Contact-Information-Nurses-Week_-final.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">our local hospital partners</a>.<br><br></li>\n<li><strong>Send a card</strong>: A handwritten note is a thoughtful way to show you care. Have kids? Print a <a href=\"https://ucfalumni.com/UCF-coloring-sheets.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">UCF coloring sheet</a> to add some flare to a homemade card! Send to a nurse or unit you’re connected with or to <a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Hospital-Contact-Information-Nurses-Week_-final.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">one of our partners</a>.<br><br></li>\n<li><strong>Honor a nurse</strong>: <a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/thank-a-nurse-nurses-week-2020/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Share your story</a> honoring a nurse who has made a difference in your life as part of our Thank A Nurse campaign. You can also <a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/thankanurse\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">make a gift in their honor</a> to support student nurses negatively impacted by COVID-19.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thank you in advance for joining us in honoring these healthcare heroes and taking a quick moment to brighten a nurse’s day.</p>','2020-05-06','2020-05-12','https://nursing.ucf.edu/thank-a-nurse-nurses-week-2020/','Christina Gonzalez','(407) 823-2422','c.gonzalez@ucf.edu','Christina Gonzalez','Publish',256),(3118,'ONLINE Comprehensive Project Management Certificate Program Starts in June','online-comprehensive-project-management-certificate-program-project-management-professional-pmp-starts-in-june','<p><strong>Keep yourself future-focused by getting PMP-certified. </strong></p>\n<p>UCF’s <a href=\"https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program/Comprehensive-Project-Management-Certificate-Project-Management-Professional-PMP\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Comprehensive Project Management Certificate &amp; PMP®/CAPM® Exam Preparation program</a> aligns with the <em>PMBOK® Guide – Sixth Edition</em> and combines expert instruction with The CertWise® Learning System for PMP® Exam Preparation training materials.  It also meets PMI’s 35 contact hour PMP Exam requirement.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>This program is designed to prepare CAPM/PMP students who seek to test for the <a href=\"https://www.pmi.org/certifications/types/project-management-pmp/exam-prep/changes\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">current</a> PMP/CAPM exam (December 31, 2020).</li>\n<li>Learn the entire <em>PMBOK</em>®<em> Guide – Sixth Edition</em> with our experienced and <a href=\"https://media.ce.ucf.edu/CE/Assets/program/954/Files/InstructorBios2019.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">certified PMP instructors</a>.</li>\n<li>Study the three domains tested on the PMP exam, including updated exam domains: <em>People, Process, Business Environment</em> and updated predictive (50%), agile and hybrid (50%) approaches.</li>\n<li>Prepare for class and the exam with The CertWise Learning System for PMP® Exam Preparation, included in tuition. This interactive study program includes printed and online study materials, online quizzes, flashcards, PMP practice exam, and more. You will have access to the online study tools for an entire year.</li>\n<li>Discuss topics and network with peers from a variety of industries.</li>\n<li>Stay on track to complete your PMP studies with our structured learning environment.</li>\n<li>Meet the 35-hour project management education prerequisite.</li>\n<li>Earn up to 40 CEUs/PDUs.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Classes fill quickly. Don’t miss out!</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Live Online Instruction (access from anywhere!)<br> </strong>Thursday evenings, June 18, 2020 – September 3, 2020<strong><br> </strong>5:30 – 9:30pm<br> <br> Course fee is <strong>$2,495</strong> which includes course instruction, textbooks, materials and Continuing Education Units (CEUs). </p>\n<p>Discounted registration fee available for UCF Alumni, Staff, Faculty and Students of <strong>$2,395</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program/Comprehensive-Project-Management-Certificate-Project-Management-Professional-PMP\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>REGISTER NOW</strong></a></p>','2020-06-18','2020-09-03','https://www.ce.ucf.edu/Program/Comprehensive-Project-Management-Certificate-Project-Management-Professional-PMP','Lisa Ruscigno','(407) 882-0337','Lisa.Ruscigno@ucf.edu','Lisa Ruscigno','Publish',30),(3119,'2020 Florida TaxWatch Productivity Awards - Nominations Deadline Extended!','2020-florida-taxwatch-productivity-awards-nominations-deadline-extended','<p>Since 1989, the Florida TaxWatch Productivity Awards program has publicly recognized and rewarded state employees and teams whose work significantly and measurably increases productivity and promotes innovation to improve the delivery of state services and save money for Florida taxpayers and businesses. Over the 30-year program, more than 16,000 nominations have been submitted, totaling $10 billion in cost savings, cost avoidances, and added value to the lives of Florida’s residents and visitors.</p>\n<p>Any employee of the state of Florida can nominate themself, a colleague, or a team of employees that meet the nomination criteria. Nominations should reflect an innovative or outstanding idea or practice that has led or will lead to taxpayer saving, improved service delivery, or overall taxpayer value. (Note: In-unit faculty are not eligible.)</p>\n<p>Whether through developing a creative new process, improving the quality and speed of our interactions with the public, or showing great initiative in tackling a problem to help our constituents, UCF has many initiatives that would qualify for these awards.</p>\n<p>To nominate yourself, a colleague, or a team, visit the Florida TaxWatch website: <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ftpa.floridataxwatch.org%2FInstructions&amp;data=02%7C01%7CLee.Williams%40ucf.edu%7Ceca8fe89180c43764b4a08d7c76269cf%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637197097798216407&amp;sdata=%2BVsKbbTEbk%2BBqGRAPmkKT4IryHq379Li0TTfACnipAM%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://tpa.floridataxwatch.org/Instructions</a>. <strong>The nomination window has been extended to July 17.</strong></p>','2020-05-06','2020-07-18','https://tpa.floridataxwatch.org','HR Learning & Organizational Effectiveness','(407) 823-0440','HRLearning@ucf.edu','Lee Williams','Publish',24),(3120,'Online Info Session: Urban & Regional Planning Graduate Program','online-open-house-urban-regional-planning-graduate-program','<p>Join program director, Dr. Luis Santiago, for a virtual conversation on the Master of Urban &amp; Regional Planning program. Urban and regional planning is a growing career field, particularly in areas similar to Central Florida, that are rapidly growing as new businesses and residents continue relocate to the area. The program offers courses in the evening to accommodate the schedules of working professionals. </p>\n<p>In the session, we\'ll discuss the course curriculum, tuition, application and career opportunities in the field. </p>\n<p>For more information on the Master of Urban &amp; Regional Planning program, please join us for the <a href=\"https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/URP520\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">virtual information session</a>. </p>','2020-05-11','2020-05-14','https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/URP520','Luis Santiago','(407) 823-2604','luis.santiago2@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3122,'UCF Sports Medicine Looking for Student Volunteers for Football Season','ucf-sports-medicine-looking-for-student-volunteers-for-football-season','<p><span>The UCF Athletics Sports Medicine department is looking for volunteers to asssit, starting Aug. 1, with the upcoming football season. UCF students interested in pursuing a career in sports medicine/athletic training can apply to gain valuable experience with an NCAA Division I football team. We\'re seeking students preferably available in the mornings during Fall 2020 for practices, with additional opportunities potentially available throughout the fall and spring semesters. </span></p>\n<p><span>Send your resume and fall class schedule to Associate Athletic Trainer Ed Woodley at ewoodley@athletics.ucf.edu. Students who have prior experience will be to be considered first. Resumes will be accepted throughout the summer.</span></p>','2020-05-26','2020-11-01','https://ucfknights.com/sports/2019/7/18/sports-medicine.aspx','Edmeston Woodley','(407) 823-0585','ewoodley@athletics.ucf,edu','Ed Woodley','Publish',204),(3123,'Congratulations USPS Employee of the Month, Linda Rutsyamuka','usps-employe-of-the-month-march-linda-rutsyamuka','<p> Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for March 2020 – Linda Rutsyamuka</p>\n<p>Linda is the International Insurance Specialist in Health Service Center of the Academic Health Sciences Center.  Her nominators, Kimberly Thrash and Donovan Williams, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>         “In addition to Linda’s daily responsibilities she has undertaken several key tasks which are outside of her current purview, which significantly positively impacted the organization.  Linda clocked over 100+ hours assisting the Business Office with revenue cycle management, processing over 716 payments totaling over $319,746, ensuring revenue from payers based on the services provided were posted in a timely manner.  </em></p>\n<p><em> </em><em>         Linda does an outstanding job as the International Insurance department lead, she recently instituted an online submission process for International students, reducing the barriers they were experiencing when submitting required documentation.  Linda embodies one of UCF’s key goals ‘Providing International focus to our curricula and research programs.’  Her direct and proactive support of international students positively impacts how international students view the University upon arrival.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Ms. Rutsyamuka receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>','2020-05-15','2020-05-25','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3130,'Associate Professor Kenyatta Rivers\' Lasting Impact on Students, Profession','associate-professor-kenyatta-rivers-leaves-a-lasting-impact-on-students-and-profession','<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">Kenyatta Rivers, a </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">retired</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> faculty member in the School of Communication Sciences and Disorders, believed in leading by example. He taught students how to </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">improve </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">the </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">communication skills of</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">children with </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">speech and </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">language disorders and people of all ages with traumatic brain injury. He </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">did this</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> not only through class </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">instruction and </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">assignments, but also </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">by demonstrating how to lead through</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> service and education.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Rivers </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">was passionate</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> about </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">guiding under-represented students to the profession he loved so much.</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">He was active with the McNair Scholars </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">P</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">rogram at UCF</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">, which</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> prepares students from low-income, first-generation and traditionally underrepresented groups for do</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">ctoral programs;</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">and the </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">National Black Speech-Language-Hearing Association</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">.</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> He held many leadership positions over the </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">years</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> and contributed </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">vastly</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">to</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> the </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Florida Association of Speech-Language Pathologists and Audiologists.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">Rivers </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">also</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> served as a formal and informal mentor to a wide range of students</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">and colleagues</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">in Communication Sciences and Disorders and beyond. </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">You could literally hear the impact of his relationships. It was a trademark of Rivers to shout a greeting across campus to bring a smile to the faces of colleagues and students.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">When Rivers</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> retired last year, his colleagues established a scholarship in his honor</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> to </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">encourage</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> students to lead as he did</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">—</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> with </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">humi</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">li</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">ty,</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> advocacy and a sense of humor</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"201341983\":0,\"335559739\":160,\"335559740\":259}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Recently, Rivers </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">passed away. His legacy will continue</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> through </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">the many students and colleagues he mentored throughout the years</span> <span data-contrast=\"auto\">and through his </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">work</span> <span data-contrast=\"auto\">as </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">an</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">ordained minister</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"201341983\":0,\"335559739\":160,\"335559740\":259}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">The</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> first </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">recipient</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> of the</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> Dr</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">. </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">Kenyatta Rivers Memorial Scholarship </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">is</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">Ayanna Frederick, a</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">n</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">undergraduate student in CSD who </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">shares Rivers’ commitment to mentoring. Frederick says she has</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> benefited from </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">the wisdom and support of </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">mentors throughout her life</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> and wants to pay it forward. </span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">She</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> belongs to Crown to Crown, a UCF organization that mentors young girls in the community. </span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">“We strive to establish a safe space, friendship, support and insight from our personal experiences,” Frederick </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">said</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">. “</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">Overall,</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> our goal is to </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">empower</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> our mentees</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">and </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">cultivate</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">their sense of </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">self-worth</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">.”</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'>F</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">rederick said she is humbled to be chosen as the first recipient of the memorial </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">scholarship and</span> <span data-contrast=\"none\">is grateful to continue Rivers’ </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">mission of service through education and mentorship.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">“I believe it is my responsibility to instill the importance of self-love, confidence and a great work ethic in the generations who will lo</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">ok up to me and to those who follow in my footsteps</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">,</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">”</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> Frederick </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">said.</span> <span data-ccp-props=\'{\"134233117\":true,\"134233118\":true,\"201341983\":0,\"335559740\":240}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Through this memorial scholarship, UCF Communication Sciences and Disorders students will carry on Rivers’ commitment to faith, community and service to others.</span></p>\n<p><strong>Donate to the Dr. Rivers Memorial Scholarship:</strong></p>\n<p>To honor Dr. Rivers and his legacy, Maurice LaMar Pearson (’93) and Ileana Pearson (’97), UCF alumni and life-long friends of Dr. Rivers, have generously issued a matching challenge to encourage others to give to his newly established memorial scholarship fund.? The Pearsons will match donations to the Dr. Kenyatta Rivers Memorial Scholarship fund up to $5,000. ??This means that any gift made will now have double the impact. The Rivers family and the Pearson family will receive notification that a gift has been made in your name to honor Dr. Kenyatta Rivers.</p>\n<p>Donate Online:<span> </span><a data-wpel-link=\"external\" href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/kenyatta\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.ucffoundation.org/kenyatta</a><br>At the bottom of the form,?please fill in the tribute information to reflect “In Memory of Dr. Kenyatta Rivers.”</p>\n<p>Also, we are collecting photos and statements to share on the Rivers’ Memorial Scholarship webpage. You can view and submit those online:<span> </span><a data-wpel-link=\"internal\" href=\"https://healthprofessions.ucf.edu/give/kenyatta/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://healthprofessions.ucf.edu/give/kenyatta/</a></p>','2020-05-18','2020-05-30','https://healthprofessions.ucf.edu/news/associate-professor-kenyatta-rivers-leaves-a-lasting-impact-on-students-and-profession/','Megan Pabian','(407) 823-0345','megan.pabian@ucf.edu','UCF College of Health Professions and Sciences','Publish',5),(3131,'CAN YOU PLEASE REMOVE THIS URL? https://www.ucf.edu/announcements/shrm-cpshrm-scp-courses/','can-you-please-remove-this-url-httpswwwucfeduannouncementsshrm-cpshrm-scp-courses','<p>The information is out of date.</p>','2020-05-26','2020-05-26','https://www.ucf.edu/announcements/shrm-cpshrm-scp-courses/','Lisa Ruscigno','(407) 882-0337','lisa.ruscigno@ucf.edu','Lisa Ruscigno','Pending',30),(3132,'CPNM Accepting Applications for Summer Capacity Building Seminars','cpnm-accepting-applications-for-summer-capacity-building-seminars-1','<p>If your nonprofit agency has a health and human services mission and is located in, and serving residents of, Ora<span>nge County, Florida, you may be eligible to participate in a valuable capacity building opportunity.</span></p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida Center for Public and Nonprofit Management (CPNM) has partnered with Orange County Citizens’ Commission for Children (OCCCC) to provide 15 hours of capacity building training. Fifteen agencies will be accepted for the online training program (July 14 - August 6, 2020) focused on grant writing, organization governance, financial management, and strategic planning and program evaluation. One-on-one technical assistance will be provided virtually by UCF graduate students for a total of 20 hours per participating agency. The training program, free of charge to participants, is funded entirely by OCCCC. Please note that agencies will receive training and technical assistance, but no financial assistance.</p>\n<p>Preference will be given to 501(C)(3) not-for-profit organizations with a health and human service mission that are both located and provide services in Orange County, and have been in operation for a minimum of one (1) year. Additional eligibility criteria are listed on the application website.</p>\n<p>To apply for the program and to get more information:</p>\n<p>Go to<span> <a href=\"https://ccie.ucf.edu/cpnm/capacity-building/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ccie.ucf.edu/cpnm/capacity-building/</a></span><span> </span>or contact Mrs. Silvana Bastante, Project Coordinator, at CPNM@ucf.edu. Application is due by June 30, 2020. Early application is encouraged. Selection notification will occur by close of business on July 7, 2020.</p>','2020-06-01','2020-07-01','https://ccie.ucf.edu/cpnm/capacity-building/','Silvana Bastante','(407) 823-2604','cpnm@ucf.edu','UCF Center for Public and Nonprofit Management','Publish',155),(3133,'Nominations Open for the 2020 Gabor A&P Excellence Award','nominations-open-for-the-2020-gabor-ap-excellence-award','<p><strong>Nominations are now open for UCF\'s annual Gabor Administrative and Professional (A&amp;P) Excellence Award. </strong></p>\n<p>Sponsored by The Gabor Agency, the award was established to recognize, appreciate, and celebrate the outstanding job performance of a selected A&amp;P employee. The chosen candidate will be announced at the Knight Star Awards (date and format to be determined based on campus operations) and will receive a check for $2,500.</p>\n<p>All nominations must be received in Human Resources by <strong>5:00 p.m. on Friday, July 17, 2020</strong>.</p>\n<p>Eligibility criteria and additional information about the award: <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/</a></p>\n<p>Nomination form: <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/2020-Gabor-Nom-Form.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/2020-Gabor-Nom-Form.pdf</a> (best viewed in Internet Explorer)</p>\n<p>If you have questions, or for more information, please contact the Human Resources Learning &amp; Organizational Effectiveness team at 407-823-0440 or email <a href=\"mailto:HRLearning@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">HRLearning@ucf.edu</a>.</p>','2020-06-01','2020-07-17','https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/','HR Learning & Organizational Effectiveness','(407) 823-0440','HRLearning@ucf.edu','Lee Williams','Publish',24),(3134,'Virtual Forum for Students Scheduled for Thursday','virtual-forum-for-students-scheduled-for-thursday','<p><span>Join Vice President for Student Development and Enrollment Services Maribeth Ehasz and Student Government President, Sabrina LaRosa for a virtual forum for students on Thursday, June 4th 2:30pm-4pm. </span></p>\n<p><span>This is an opportunity for you to share your voice and learn more about the work the university is doing to prepare for the Fall 2020 semester.  Your ideas and questions about returning to campus are important for us to hear.</span></p>\n<p><span>You may join on Zoom at: <a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/j/94923102773?pwd=dUNaMmk1citWcWFzeExCNG9xUG5udz09&amp;status=success\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.zoom.us/j/94923102773?pwd=dUNaMmk1citWcWFzeExCNG9xUG5udz09&amp;status</a> (Meeting ID: 949 2310 2773 Password: 041890)</span></p>\n<p><span>The meeting also can be viewed on the UCF YouTube channel at <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JfPTfmYYDzA&amp;feature=youtu.be\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://youtu.be/JfPTfmYYDzA</a>  and on Facebook at <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/events/873693503129296/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Original URL:https://www.facebook.com/events/873693503129296/Click to follow link.\">https://www.facebook.com/events/873693503129296/</a>.</span></p>','2020-06-04','2020-06-05','https://events.ucf.edu/event/1762179/student-virtual-forum/','Maribeth Ehasz','(407) 823-2000','today@ucf.edu','UCF','Publish',165),(3135,'Report Ethical Concerns through UCF IntegrityLine','report-ethical-concerns-through-ucf-integrityline','<p>UCF has been receiving complaints alleging bias and unfair treatment and takes every report seriously. If any student, current or former, believes they may have experienced abusive or discriminatory behavior by any faculty or staff member, we want to know about it.</p>\n<p>Concerns can be reported to UCF’s IntegrityLine, which also takes anonymous complaints, at <a href=\"http://www.ucfintegrityline.com/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.ucfintegrityline.com/\">www.ucfintegrityline.com</a> or 855-877-6049.</p>','2020-06-07','2020-06-30','https://compliance.ucf.edu/compliance-helpline/','UCF','(855) 877-6049','complianceandethics@ucf.edu','UCF','Publish',165),(3136,'Congratulations USPS Employee of the Month (April): Arlene Flores','usps-employee-of-the-month-april-arlene-flores','<p> Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for April 2020 – Arlene Flores</p>\n<p>Arlene is the Administrative Assistant in the School of Performing Arts. Her nominators, Michael Wainstein and Thomas Harrison, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>         “For over 20 years, Arlene has been giving of her time and energy to UCF.  She is a strong supporter of the faculty and other staff and daily lives the values of integrity and excellence.  The school has made many changes over the past two years and Arlene has been central in managing those changes and working with faculty to make the changes easier. </em></p>\n<p><em>         She has many assets but her most remarkable trait is the way she presents an optimistic and positive face to students and faculty.  Nothing fazes her.  She is consistently sets a positive and upbeat tone which is infections.  “ </em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Ms. Flores receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>','2020-06-16','2020-06-26','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Deborah Frankenbach','(407) 823-2777','deborah.frankenbach@ucf.edu','Deborah Frankenbach','Publish',23),(3137,'A Virtual Educational Town Hall: Reopening Florida\'s K-12 Schools, Universities and Colleges','a-virtual-educational-town-hall-reopening-floridas-k-12-schools-universities-and-colleges','<p>On June 19 from 6 to 7:30 p.m. the Florida Legislative Black Caucus will host a virtual town hall to discuss reopening Florida\'s K-12 schools, universties and colleges. The event will be available for streaming via Zoom (ID # 824 4943 6886), Facebook (@FLBLKCAUCUS). You can also participate by calling 321-626-6799/PW: 397932. </p>\n<p>The following educational <span>leaders will provide information on the path to reopening: </span></p>\n<p><span>Marshall Criser III State University System chancellor</span></p>\n<p><span>Kathy Hedba, Florida College System chancellor</span></p>\n<p><span>Jacob Oliva, K-12 Public Schools chancellor</span></p>\n<p><span>Larry Robinson, Florida A&amp;M University president</span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Barbara Jenkins \'83 \'86MEd \'96EeD</strong>, Orange County Public Schools superintendent</span></p>','2020-06-17','2020-06-20',NULL,'The Florida Black Caucus',NULL,'TFLBC@Earthlink.net','UCF Communications and Marketing','Publish',166),(3138,'Call For Art: Hidden Artists Virtual Exhibit','call-for-art-hidden-artists-virtual-exhibit','<p>Hidden Artists is a group of UCF faculty and staff who make art outside their daily jobs. Every year the group exhibits their artwork at the UCF John C. Hitt Library Main Campus. For 2020, Hidden Artists Exhibit will be virtual.</p>\n<p>Participants must be <strong>current or former UCF faculty or staff employees</strong>.</p>\n<p>Artwork can be 2D or 3D. Drawing, painting, photography, mixed media, sculpture, digital art, digital photography will be accepted. Work should be created in 2020. No explicit work.</p>\n<p>Maximum of 4 artwork per artist.</p>\n<p><em>Artwork must be digitally photographed to be included in the virtual exhibit.</em> </p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Deadline: July 31, 2020</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>For more information on how to submit artwork:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://hiddenartistsucf.exposure.co/2020-call-for-art-by-ucf-faculty-and-staff\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hiddenartistsucf.exposure.co/2020-call-for-art-by-ucf-faculty-and-staff</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Check out the virtual gallery space to see past exhibits: <a href=\"http://hiddenartistsucf.exposure.co/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">hiddenartistsucf.exposure.co</a></p>\n<p></p>','2020-07-01','2020-07-31','https://hiddenartistsucf.exposure.co/2020-call-for-art-by-ucf-faculty-and-staff','Christopher Saclolo','(407) 823-0703','christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu','Christopher Saclolo','Publish',198),(3140,'A Special ‘Thank You’ to UCF’s Faculty and Staff for a Heroic Response to COVID-19','a-special-thank-you-to-ucfs-faculty-and-staff-for-a-heroic-response-to-covid-19','<p>UCF\'s faculty and staff recently received a big \"thank you\" from a key UCF Board of Trustees committee in recognition of their unprecedented efforts to quickly <span>convert all spring courses to online instruction due to the COVID-19 pandemic.</span></p>\n<p>UCF Trustee Ken Bradley, chair of the UCF BOT\'s Educational Programs Committee, proposed the proclamation that his committee supported to applaud faculty and staff for extraordinary work to keep UCF moving forward during the most difficult of professional and personal circumstances.</p>\n<p>“Our Board of Trustees Educational Programs Committee realizes the Herculean efforts our faculty and staff have undertaken to continue providing quality education in light of the pandemic,” Bradley said. “Our Board members simply want to say ‘thank you’ with this proclamation. We understand this has been a very challenging time.  But we greatly appreciate the UCF team who have kept education and learning as our #1 priority.  Thank you.”</p>\n<p>Here’s the proclamation approved unanimously on June 17 by Bradley and committee colleagues and trustees Joe Harrington, Caryl McAlpin and Sabrina La Rosa.</p>\n<p><strong>A Proclamation Honoring UCF’s Faculty and Staff for Their Valiant Response to the Extraordinary Challenges from COVID-19</strong></p>\n<p><strong>WHEREAS,</strong><span> </span>the University of Central Florida is a vibrant and diverse community of more than 83,000 students, faculty and staff; a leading talent producer nationally among public universities; a vital force for lifting lives and livelihoods in Central Florida; and a game changer in making the world a better place through teaching, research, and service;</p>\n<p><strong>WHEREAS,</strong><span> </span>great universities and communities are built upon great faculties and the staff that support their essential efforts to advance student success, innovation, and the cultivation and dissemination of new knowledge for global impact;</p>\n<p><strong>WHEREAS,</strong><span> </span>the COVID-19 pandemic presented unprecedented professional and personal challenges for UCF faculty and staff in the middle of spring semester 2020 and required an immediate shift of all courses to online instruction amid severe stressors, including personal health and safety, family care, food and household supplies, and much more;</p>\n<p><strong>WHEREAS,</strong><span> </span>UCF is a national leader in online learning and the Division of Digital Learning performed magnificently in short order to transition faculty and students to an all-remote learning environment of outstanding quality;</p>\n<p><strong>WHEREAS,</strong><span> </span>UCF further distinguished itself as a pacesetter in higher education for creative, innovative and successful approaches to online learning in navigating well the most extraordinary and difficult of pandemic times; and</p>\n<p><strong>WHEREAS,</strong><span> </span>the remarkable efforts of UCF’s faculty and staff assured that teaching, learning, and service at the state’s largest university by enrollment would charge on at the highest levels possible for the benefit of the deserving students, communities, and employers we serve;</p>\n<p><strong>THEREFORE,<span> </span></strong>the UCF Board of Trustees’ Educational Programs Committee hereby proudly applauds and commends the university’s faculty and staff for their dedication, professionalism, resiliency, and creativity in continuing to move our university forward to an even greater future of impact for Central Florida, the Sunshine State, and the world. You have our deepest appreciation. Thank you.</p>','2020-07-02','2020-07-09','https://provost.ucf.edu/news/community-engagement/a-special-thank-you-to-ucfs-faculty-and-staff-for-a-heroic-response-to-covid-19/','Gwen Ransom','(407) 823-3549','gwenr@ucf.edu','Joe Adams','Publish',264),(3141,'UCF Libraries Awards 2020 June S. Stillman Memorial Endowed Scholarship','ucf-libraries-awards-2020-june-s-stillman-memorial-endowed-scholarship','<p>The University of Central Florida Libraries is proud to announce that Holly Rogers is the 2020–21 recipient of the June S. Stillman Memorial Endowed Scholarship.<span> </span></p>\n<p>Rogers is a third-year student in the Doctorate Physical Therapy program at UCF. She began working as a student assistant in the Acquisitions and Collection Services Department in the John C. Hitt Library in August 2015. She was part of the team that assembled and stored data in support of the Automatic Retrieval Center (ARC). Other library responsibilities include web development testing, microfilm pH testing, and data input.<span> </span></p>\n<p>Rogers academic career includes Dean’s List as well as President’s List for Eastern Florida State College. Her volunteer experience includes Mission Trips to Belize including organizing a summer camp for children of the Belmopan community as well as constructing a playground. She also volunteers for <em>GoBabyGo </em>which consists of community builds of cars for special needs children.<span> </span></p>\n<p>This is the 22<span>nd </span>awarding of the Stillman scholarship, which is given to a student or staff member of the UCF Libraries. June S. Stillman was one of the first two librarians hired when UCF (then Florida Technological University) opened in 1968. Her impact on students can be seen from a 25<span>th </span>anniversary survey of the first graduating class, a majority of whom listed her as a key figure from their student days. Stillman received her second master’s degree in English Literature from UCF while working as the Head of Reference Services at the Library. She retired in 1996 and tragically passed away in 1998. Her friends and family established the June S. Stillman Memorial Endowed Scholarship in her honor. She is remembered as a consummate professional, the epitome of gentility and compassion, and a proponent of lifelong learning.<span> </span></p>','2020-07-08','2020-07-31',NULL,'UCF Libraries','(407) 823-2564','infolit@ucf.edu','UCF Communications','Publish',166),(3142,'USPS Employee of the Month (May): Jessica Torres','usps-employee-of-the-month-may-jessica-torres','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for May 2020 – Jessica Torres</p>\n<p>Jessica is the Senior Information Specialist at the UCF Foundation. Her nominators, Kelly Travis and Alison Kubala, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>          “ Jessica’s work speaks for itself. The fact that when asked I received support forms not just from her peers in our department but from the other departments that she works with in our division speaks volumes. </em></p>\n<p><em>Jessica has continually shown her dedication to being not only a UCF employee, but a UCF Knight. Even more rare than Jessica’s days off, are the times she does not know the answer to a question. With more than 10 years with the Foundation, she is a wealth of knowledge. She has seen us through and learned the ins-and-outs of not one but two conversions of our database systems. Through everything, Jessica maintains a high level of performance while keeping positive.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Ms. Torres receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>','2020-07-10','2020-07-24','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','Theresa.Scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3143,'Lead Forward: Virtual Nonprofit Conference','lead-forward-virtual-nonprofit-conference','<p><strong>Leading Forward: Acting on Our Values in a Changing World</strong></p>\n<p><span>The 19th Annual Nonprofit Community Partners Conference will be held on <strong>Friday, September 25, 2020</strong>. This year’s topic is \"Leading Forward: Acting on Our Values in a Changing World.\"</span></p>\n<p><span>This year\'s conference focuses on building relationships and finding solutions to challenges exacerbated by the COVID-19 pandemic and provides a platform to discuss building social equity and justice into our communities through our nonprofit missions and the partnerships we make to achieve progress. Join us for a day of engaging sessions discussing topics such as </span>social media and communicating in a complex social environment, cultivating diversity, sustainability goals, and identifying disparities in access to services. The keynote address will be delivered by Dr. Thomas Bryer, a professor of public administration and the program director for the Office of Downtown Community-Engaged Scholarship. </p>\n<p><span>The conference is hosted by the UCF School of Public Administration\'s Nonprofit Management Advisory Board, the Office of Downtown Community-Engaged Scholarship at UCF Downtown, and the Center for Public and Nonprofit Management. Sponsorship opportunities are still available. Please email <a href=\"mailto:justin.miller@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">justin.miller@ucf.edu</a> for more information. All proceeds support student scholarship. Whether you join us for a few sessions or a full day, we look forward to this opportunity to share insight, develop solutions, and create relationships that can have a dynamic impact on your nonprofit mission. </span></p>','2020-07-14','2020-09-24','https://www.eventbrite.com/e/19th-annual-nonprofit-community-partners-conference-registration-112685023940','Justin Miller','(407) 823-3794','justin.miller@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3144,'USPS Employee of the Month (June): Shannon Cajigas','usps-employee-of-the-month-june-shannon-cajigas','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for June 2020 – Shannon Cajigas</p>\n<p>Shannon is the administrative assistant in the sociology department. Her nominators, Bridgett Burk and Chelsea Belanger, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>          “Shannon is the glue that holds the Sociology Department together. She is always willing and eager to assist faculty, students, and staff with any task. She organizes all our events, handles our payroll, travel, inventory, the Foundation budget, record keeping, student worker schedules, department funding and more – all with a smile on her face and a desire to keep everything running smoothly. </em></p>\n<p><em>Ms. Cajigas’ work ethic is always efficient and high-quality. We can always count on her to produce excellent quality of work and service to the students, staff, and faculty that enter her office. We, as a department, are so grateful for Ms. Cajigas and the years she has committed to UCF and the Sociology department. She truly deserves to be recognized for this award and be reminded of how valued she is.“</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Ms. Cajigas receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>','2020-07-20','2020-07-31','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3145,'Complete Your COVID Self-Checker','complete-your-covid-self-checker','<p>As a UCF employee, you must conduct symptom monitoring every day before coming to campus through the COVID Self-Checker on the UCF Mobile app or online. It’s also a good tool to help monitor your health daily.</p>\n<p>It’s quick, easy and confidential. Just download the app and fill out your self-check. You’ll receive your results and next steps within seconds. Follow these tips if you have questions or need help:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>English:</strong> <a href=\"../../../../coronavirus/document/covid-self-checker-instructions-for-employees/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ucf.edu/coronavirus/document/covid-self-checker-instructions-for-employees/</a></li>\n<li><strong>Spanish:</strong> <a href=\"../../../../coronavirus/document/covid-self-checker-instructions-for-employees-spanish-version/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ucf.edu/coronavirus/document/covid-self-checker-instructions-for-employees-spanish-version/</a></li>\n<li>You can also access the COVID Self-Checker online at: <a href=\"https://ucf.service-now.com/self_checker\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.service-now.com/self_checker</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The UCF Mobile app is your way to stay connected. Get the latest updates, ways to armor up and other helpful resources. Let’s do our part in keeping the community safe, Knights.</p>\n<p><strong>Download the app today:</strong> <a href=\"https://ucfmobile.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucfmobile.ucf.edu/</a></p>','2020-07-27','2020-08-31',NULL,'COVID-19 Questions',NULL,'covid19questions@ucf.edu','Communications and Marketing','Publish',138),(3146,'ODI Legacy Summer Symposium','odi-legacy-summer-symposium','<p><span>The Office of Diversity and Inclusion invites students, faculty and staff to the 2020 LEGACY SUMMER SYMPOSIUM — a virtual leadership and mentorship development bootcamp for </span><span>the first-generation, under-represented and minority college students and the entire campus community.</span><br><span> </span><br><span>There will be a virtual discussion with seven faculty and staff members that will cover improving diversity and inclusion on campus and enhancing global perspectives. The sessions will be centered around the following disruptive frontiers:</span><br><span> </span><br><span>· Expunging the narrow-minded atomistic thinking </span><br><span>· Strategic identification of problems and deepening how to visualize the big picture</span><br><span>· Holistic thinking and creatively designing a better future to enrich learning and living</span><br><span>· Connecting the right dots that redesign and reinvent transformational excellence</span><br><span> </span><br><span>Date: Tuesday, July 28, 2020</span><br><span>Time: Noon until 3 p.m.</span><br><span>Register here: </span><a href=\"http://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_6mU8zzCvjoCJgLr\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_6mU8zzCvjoCJgLr</a></p>','2020-07-21','2020-07-28','https://events.ucf.edu/manager/event/416915/','Victor Nkwocha','(321) 202-3242','victor.nkwocha@ucf.edu','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','Publish',165),(3147,'USPS Employee of the Month (July): Joanna Hoyt','usps-employee-of-the-month-july-joanna-hoyt','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for July 2020: Joanna Hoyt.</p>\n<p>Joanna Hoyt is the Office Support Assistant for Interdisciplinary Studies in the College of Undergraduate Studies. Her nominators, Mr. Wayne Bowen and Mr. Pete Wallace, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>“For most students, Joanna is the face of Interdisciplinary Studies, providing them with thoughtful, compassionate, and efficient customer service at all times, in support of their academic goals. More than just a staff member at reception, she leads or supports innovation and enhancements across the entire program.</em></p>\n<p><em>Sometimes individuals make a grand gesture beyond the norm but Joanna’s contributions are daily, meaningful, and consistently in support of student success. Joanna invests the time and effort in staying up-to-date on curricular and policy changes. She leverages her knowledge of available university resources to connect students with academic and support services without prompting because she genuinely cares about student success in college and beyond. “ </em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Joanna receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Annual Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>','2020-08-03','2020-08-21','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3148,'Call for Alumni Authors','call-for-alumni-authors','<p>The UCF Alumni team would <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">like to hear from our alumni authors. Whether you’ve published a novel or a collection of poetry or short stories, let us know by filling out this form: <a href=\"https://ucfalumni.com/callforauthors\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucfalumni.com/callforauthors</a></span></p>','2020-07-27','2021-07-27','https://ucfalumni.com/callforauthors','UCF Alumni',NULL,'knights@ucfalumni.com','UCF Alumni','Publish',268),(3149,'Collective Bargaining Session - PBA','collective-bargaining-session-pba-1-2-3','<p><span>A collective bargaining session is scheduled between the Board of Trustees and the Police Benevolent Association (PBA) for August 6th at 2:00p.m.</span></p>','2020-08-04','2020-08-06','https://ucf.zoom.us/j/96666460918','Maureen Binder','(407) 823-0425','maureen.binder@ucf.edu','Brittny Bannister','Pending',205),(3150,'WUCF to Celebrate PBS’ 50th Anniversary with Virtual 5K Fun Run','wucf-to-celebrate-pbs-50th-anniversary-with-virtual-5k-fun-run','<p>WUCF, Central Florida’s PBS station, announced today a virtual fun run in celebration of PBS’ 50th<span> </span>anniversary. The virtual event will be held on Sunday, Oct. 11, 2020. Participants are encouraged to run or walk down memory lane dressed as their favorite PBS character and pay tribute to some PBS icons such as Mister Rogers, Julia Child, Bob Ross and Daniel Tiger, while celebrating kindness throughout their neighborhoods.<span> </span></p>\n<p>All registered participants will receive a WUCF race T-shirt and finisher medal as well as virtual activities leading up to race day including race playlists, kindness bingo, and a digital toolkit featuring race signage to build excitement for their own race day on the time, day and location of their choosing.</p>\n<p>“This milestone offers an opportunity for Central Florida, and the country, to celebrate the extraordinary contributions of PBS and WUCF, including the beloved programs, people and characters that are deeply woven into our culture,” said Dr. Phil Hoffman, WUCF TV &amp; FM executive director. “Community support is essential to our future and events like this help preserve our mission to serve as a beacon of thoughtful media and important storytelling.”</p>\n<p>More than 40 percent of WUCF\'s annual operating budget comes from the generous support of viewers and listeners. Annual funding for WUCF is made up of a remarkable public-private partnership combining university, state, and federal support with sponsorship from corporations and foundations, and also gifts from individuals. WUCF is grateful for the thousands of individuals and families from Central Florida who support WUCF each year - enabling us to provide Central Florida with quality programming you won\'t find anywhere else.</p>\n<p>For more information or to sign up visit<span> </span><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wucf.org%2Ffunrun&amp;data=02%7C01%7CJenna.Lee%40ucf.edu%7C5254002f84cd4b752b6e08d838a0c41c%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637321610424430216&amp;sdata=f2iFnsyj0pNSxxNsrsnK9v8riW3TWjcPg%2F8I5pTh4SM%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">wucf.org/funrun</a>.<span> </span></p>','2020-08-06','2020-10-01','http://wucf.org/funrun','WUCF','(407) 823-5796','andrea.dennis@wucf.org','WUCF','Publish',165),(3151,'Hidden Artists Virtual Exhibit','hidden-artists-virtual-exhibit','<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Every year a group of UCF faculty and staff</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">who enjoy creating art on their own time </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">called </span><em><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Hidden Artists</span></em><span data-contrast=\"auto\">,</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">come together to exhibit</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> their work at the John C. Hitt Library. It’s no surprise that 2020 has been eventual so far. </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Because of </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">the pandemic</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">, the Hidden Artists Exhibit is </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">online</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> this year. While the group was lo</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">oking forward to a physical exhibit at the </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">main campus </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">library, Hidden Artists had to adapt to the changing climate and decided to show </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">the</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">ir </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">incredible artwork made during the first half of 2020</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">through </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">a virtual gallery space</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">. </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Some of the artwork was created in</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">response to the pandemic, while </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">other</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">s</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> chose to explore their artistic </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">practice</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">.</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> </span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"201341983\":0,\"335559739\":160,\"335559740\":259}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">This year</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">’s </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">p</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">articipating</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> faculty and staff come from a wide </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">range of </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">sectors </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">across the university</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">, </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">such as UCF Connect, </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Division of Student Learning and Academic Success, </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">and </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">UCF L</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">ibraries</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">. </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Hidden Artists Virtual Exhibit </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">features the art from Maribel Amaro-Garcia, Judy Bragg Pardo, Gina Clifton, Christine Dassow, Claudia Davidson, Rachel Edford, Megan Haught, Rebecca Hawk, Jacqui Johnson, Nazim Muradov, Brian Pate, Matt Ricke, Chris Saclolo, Audra Skukauskaite, and Aaron Smith.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"201341983\":0,\"335559739\":160,\"335559740\":259}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">For </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">the next </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Hidden Artists</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> Exhibit</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">, the 2021 exhibit will be on display at the new UCF Libraries’ Special Collections &amp; University Archives</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> Gallery, a </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">brand-new</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> gallery space </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">which is </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">part of the </span><a href=\"../../news/a-sneak-peek-inside-the-john-c-hitt-library-renovation/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><span data-contrast=\"none\">21</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">st</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">Century </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">Library </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">Project</span></a><span data-contrast=\"auto\">.</span><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"201341983\":0,\"335559739\":160,\"335559740\":259}\'> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">To view Hidden Artists Virtual </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Exhibit</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\"> go to: </span><a href=\"http://hiddenartistsucf.com/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><span data-contrast=\"none\">hiddenartistsucf.com</span></a><span data-ccp-props=\'{\"201341983\":0,\"335559739\":160,\"335559740\":259}\'> </span></p>','2020-08-06','2020-08-31','http://hiddenartistsucf.com','Christopher Saclolo',NULL,'christopher.saclolo@ucf.edu','Christopher Saclolo','Publish',198),(3154,'College of Engineering and Computer Science Recognized for Advising Excellence','college-of-engineering-and-computer-science-recognized-for-advising-excellence-1-2','<p>When you first meet Nina Leonard, her passion for helping students succeed shines through. It\'s no wonder that she was selected as the recipient of the Pegasus Advisor Award. This annual recognition honors an advisor who champions student success. CECS Advising Director Kim Small nominated Leonard. </p>\n<p>Leonard is an advisor in the College of Engineering and Computer Science (CECS) and works with the college\'s students, faculty, and staff. She coordinates orientation and open houses, manages the BS-MS Program, oversees the scholarship process, and leads efforts to integrate the Pegasus Path into the academic planning process for engineering and computer science majors. In the past, she managed the CECS Academic Alert and CECS Academic Probation programs.</p>\n<p>\"Nina strives for excellence in her advising responsibilities,\" said Small. \"She is a true asset to our college and UCF. Our college is fortunate to have Nina as part of our team.\"</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>What\'s your favorite part of your job?</strong></p>\n<p>On my gosh, it\'s working with students! I remember a first-time college student who had a lot of accelerated credits. She was nervous about starting college. I was a little worried about her beginning upper-level courses during her first semester. We met each semester to talk about her classes and plan to graduation. She ended up staying at UCF to pursue a master\'s degree. It was fulfilling to see how her confidence increased and watch her academic career unfold. When she graduated, she brought me a card to thank me. Advising this student is a highlight of my career.</p>\n<p><strong>What\'s a typical day like as an advisor? </strong></p>\n<p>Every day is different. It always includes guiding CECS students to develop a plan for their future and make sure they stay on track. I love that I see a student\'s entire degree progression I help students to understand the university’s policies and degree requirements. I assist students with schedule planning, course selection, and navigating the many resources UCF has to offer. I link them with resources to increase academic success &amp; employability after graduation. </p>\n<p><strong>Sometimes, students have difficulties completing degree requirements. How do advisors help them get back on track? </strong></p>\n<p>It begins with building relationships with students. Advising goes beyond selecting classes. It\'s making sure that they know about available resources, such as the Pegasus Path and the Student Academic Resource Center. You also have to be willing to have those tough conversations. </p>\n<p>I led the CECS Early Alert Program that identifies students who are struggling and are at risk of extending their time to graduation or, in the worst case, leaving UCF. We work with the student to determine if the course load or the major is not right. Or, it might be time to refer them to the Student Academic Resource Center for tutoring or to the Knights Major Exploration and Transition Center to meet with an advisor who can help them select a degree program that aligns with their talents and future plans.</p>\n<p><strong>What advice would you give to advisors?</strong></p>\n<p>Some days can be hard, especially when you\'re having tough conversations with students. We need to give ourselves grace and make sure to recharge. It will make us better advisors. We need to show students that we\'re invested in their success. At the same time, let them know that they own their education.</p>\n<p><strong>What do you do in your spare time?</strong></p>\n<p>Spend time with my family. My husband Cameron is an Academic Advisor for the Rosen College of Hospitality Management at UCF. We have a three-year-old son and a daughter who\'s two. It\'s been interesting during the pandemic. I love watching them come up with new games and participate in hobbies that I like, such as Sudoku. I sometimes wonder what colleges they\'ll attend, what careers they\'ll choose, and hope they\'ll meet an advisor who will help them achieve their dreams. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>','2020-08-05','2020-08-15','https://www.cecs.ucf.edu/news/','CECS','(407) 823-2156','barbara.smith@ucf.edu','CECS','Publish',165),(3155,'UCF Physician Assumes New Role as Faculty in UCF-HCA Healthcare Endocrinology Fellowship','ucf-physician-assumes-new-role-as-faculty-in-ucf-hca-healthcare-endocrinology-fellowship','<p>As a young physician, Mustafa Kinaan helped build UCF’s new residency and fellowship programs. After five years of training, he’s staying in Greater Orlando to “care for the new family I love.”</p>\n<p>This month, Dr. Kinaan joins Premier Endocrinology in Kissimmee and St. Cloud also begins work at Osceola Regional Medical Center as a faculty member in the UCF-HCA Healthcare endocrinology fellowship. There, he will train doctors on the best ways to care for patients with conditions like diabetes, thyroid and pituitary gland diseases. It’s fitting for a physician who often told fellow residents that his goal in life was to cure diabetes.</p>\n<p>“Endocrinology is all about personalized care,” he said. “Diabetes is more than just giving your patient a pill. It’s working with patients to change their lifestyle – what they eat, their activity level. You spend more time with your patients and make deeper connections with them for life.”</p>\n<p>Dr. Kinaan graduated from Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar and did clerkship rotations and research at Cornell University in New York. There, he fell in love with endocrinology because it combined his passions for basic science and patient care. In 2014, UCF selected him as a resident for its inaugural residency program in internal medicine that was a partnership between the College of Medicine, the Orlando VA Medical Center and Osceola Regional. That residency has since grown to 28 graduate medical education programs training almost 500 physicians across Florida.</p>\n<p>After three years of caring for veterans and residents of Osceola County, one of Florida’s most diverse and fastest growing counties, Dr. Kinaan was selected as one of the program’s first chief residents. His responsibility – lead residents at one of the nation’s largest VA hospitals. “I have always had a passion for medical education,” he said. “I always learn better when I teach. Being chief was a fruitful opportunity to also learn about leadership, administration and to translate that into patient care for our nation’s veterans.” From there, he entered UCF’s endocrinology fellowship, a partnership between the medical school, HCA and the VA.</p>\n<p>Dr. Suzanne Quinn-Martinez leads that fellowship. “When I met Dr. Kinaan as an internal medicine resident, we didn’t have an Endocrinology Fellowship yet,” she said. “He was such a great candidate, we just had to build a fellowship around him and he never disappointed. We couldn’t let him leave to train anywhere else. We couldn’t be happier that he is staying in Osceola County. What an asset to the neighborhood and the medical community. “</p>\n<p>Doctors cannot care for patients immediately after they graduate from medical school. They must go first through residency training – three to seven years depending on the specialty. After residency, many go into fellowships for even more specialized training. Premier Endocrinology has been a strong clinical partner in training UCF-HCA residents and fellows.  Dr. Theresa Fynn, one of the owners of the practice, said Osceola County has an epidemic of Type 2 diabetes – in part because of the county’s large number of Hispanic residents, who are at high risk for the disease. She said the recent influx of residents from hurricane-ravaged Puerto Rico has added to the community’s need for more endocrinologists. “When Dr. Kinaan was a fellow in our clinic, the patients loved him and kept asking when he was coming back. When we interviewed him he kept saying, ‘I want to be here and help this community.’”</p>\n<p>Dr. Abdo Asmar, UCF’s vice chair of internal medicine who leads the Greater Orlando Internal Medicine residency program, said the College of Medicine and HCA are focused on recruiting, training and retaining outstanding physicians so that graduates of the residency and fellowship programs remain in the community to care for residents.</p>\n<p>“This is why we started these programs,” Dr. Asmar said. “To bring more outstanding physicians to our community. “I couldn’t be happier. Whatever he does, Mustafa isn’t a sprinter, he’s a marathon runner. He is committed to building rapport and establishing long-term relationships with his patients. That’s what he loves.”</p>','2020-08-09','2020-08-19','https://med.ucf.edu/news/physician-staying-in-osceola-to-care-for-the-new-family-i-love/','Wendy Sarubbi','(407) 226-1418','wendy.sarubbi@ucf.edu','College of Medicine','Publish',165),(3156,'UCF Center Partners with Orlando-based United Abolitionists to Combat Human Trafficking','ucf-center-partners-with-orlando-based-united-abolitionists-to-combat-human-trafficking','<p>The Center for Public and Nonprofit Management (CPNM) and the Orlando nonprofit, United Abolitionists, are collaborating to pursue research, develop policy-related solutions, and educate and train students and community leaders on the problem of human trafficking. The U.S. National Human Trafficking Hotline reported a nearly 25% increase in reported cases from 2017 to 2018 with thousands more cases still unreported.</p>\n<p>“Human trafficking is a significant challenge that the CPNM can be at the forefront of in terms of finding innovative public sector solutions. We serve as a liaison between the School of Public Administration faculty, who are uniquely positioned to engage in traditional or interdisciplinary research on human trafficking, and partners in the community. This collaboration offers opportunity to leverage our faculty expertise and build new knowledge in human trafficking research, while gaining insight from community leaders and practitioners. The CPNM is excited to be a part of this effort to bridge academia and practice, save lives and build a better world,” says Deborah A. Carroll, associate professor and director of the CPNM.</p>\n<p>The partnership also provides opportunities to educate and train students on the implications and signs of human trafficking and engages them in the policy development process for human rights issues. Maritza Concha, Ph.D., lecturer within the School of Public Administration, adds “This partnership will bring opportunities for our undergraduate and graduate students to explore research opportunities in human trafficking.”</p>\n<p>In just one month, the CPNM and United Abolitionists have submitted a research proposal to the National Science Foundation, collaborated on the production of a research paper to be submitted to a leading peer-reviewed journal and designed a survey to capture the effect COVID-19 is having on anti-trafficking and victim service organization operations around the world.</p>\n<p>“With its focus on research in public policy and administration as well as its goal of bridging academia, government and the nonprofit community, the CPNM is a key enabler to building understanding in the public, using research to help develop more informed policies and helping nonprofits and other nongovernmental organizations be more effective in their missions,” explains Tomas J. Lares, founder and president of the United Abolitionists, Inc.</p>\n<p>As a result of this partnership, the 13th<span> </span>Annual Human Trafficking Conference, scheduled for January 27-29, 2021, will include academic research panels as well as discussions on technology used to combat trafficking, youth educational outreach events and interdisciplinary dialogues that engage international nongovernmental organizations and nonprofits, academics, and government professionals in law, security, public health, tourism, agriculture and public policy.</p>\n<p>“Human trafficking is and continues to be a wicked problem in our society,” explains Abdul-Akeem Sadiq, Ph.D., associate professor and program director for UCF’s graduate programs in public administration and public policy. “It will take a concerted and collaborative effort to fight it.”</p>','2020-08-13','2020-08-29','https://ccie.ucf.edu/2020/07/30/the-cpnm-partners-with-orlando-based-united-abolitionists-to-combat-human-trafficking/','Justin Miller','(407) 823-3794','justin.miller@ucf.edu','UCF Center for Public & Nonprofit Management','Publish',155),(3158,'Participate in Virtual Campus Climate Conversations','participate-in-virtual-campus-climate-conversations-1','<p>With the release of our Campus Climate Survey results, we will be hosting a series of Campus Climate Conversations beginning to share the findings and hear your stories.</p>\n<p>Earlier this year, we asked faculty, staff and students a series of important questions about how welcome and supported they feel at UCF to help inform how we can build a more inclusive community together. Your responses were powerful, and I appreciate everyone who took the time to share your thoughts and experiences through our Campus Climate Survey. I encourage you to look through the <a href=\"https://diversity.ucf.edu/campus-climate-survey/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">survey results posted on the Office of Diversity and Inclusion’s website</a> to see if they match your own experiences and consider where and how we must be better. These surveys were administered in February and March, clearly capturing the voices of a small population of our campus. Much has changed since then. The pandemic has ravaged the globe, and thousands have joined forces to march against racism, brutality and bigotry. Like the cries for greater equality ringing across the country, our climate survey also found discrepancies in how different groups perceive they are treated at UCF, concerns that their contributions are not being recognized and a lack of transparency. These findings are similar to what I saw while working on <a href=\"https://facultyexcellence.ucf.edu/inclusive-excellence/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">inclusive excellence</a> for Faculty Excellence and <a href=\"https://facultyexcellence.ucf.edu/document/odi-focus-group-report-2019/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">hosting faculty focus groups</a> last year on the same topic, as well as the results of <a href=\"https://facultyexcellence.ucf.edu/coache/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">our last COACHE survey among faculty</a>. Many of us have spoken out about the discrimination we have suffered in our lives as we continue to encourage our friends, family and colleagues to <a href=\"../../news/now-is-our-time-to-be-actively-anti-racist/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">be actively anti-racist</a> in their words and actions. We carry these experiences with us everywhere we go, in the workplace, our interactions with others and how we share our values.</p>\n<p><strong>Join Our Conversations</strong> <br>I will be hosting a series of Campus Climate Conversations, starting next week, so we can discuss these survey results together and elevate more voices who either did not participate in the survey or have additional experiences they would like to share. We want and need to hear from you. These conversations will help inform the university’s action plan for equity, inclusion and diversity, which <a href=\"../../news/we-must-do-better-at-ucf/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">President Cartwright announced earlier this summer</a>. The plan will involve more training and campus support, more inclusive search committee practices and hiring efforts, and more resources dedicated to make sure we deliver on these promises. These virtual conversations will take place on the following days:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://events.ucf.edu/event/1784265/staff-campus-climate-conversation/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">A conversation with staff</a> from 10:30 a.m. to noon, Tuesday, Aug. 18</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://events.ucf.edu/event/1784453/faculty-campus-climate-conversation/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">A conversation with faculty</a> from 10:30 a.m. to noon, Wednesday, Aug. 19</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://events.ucf.edu/event/1784495/student-campus-climate-conversation/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">A conversation with students</a> from 3:30 to 5 p.m., Tuesday, Sept. 1</li>\n</ul>\n<p>— <span>S. Kent Butler, Ph.D.<br></span>Interim Chief Equity, Inclusion and Diversity Officer</p>','2020-08-16','2020-09-02','https://events.ucf.edu/','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','(407) 823-6479','diverse@ucf.edu','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','Publish',165),(3159,'Sick Leave Pool Open Enrollment','sick-leave-pool-open-enrollment-1-2-3-4','<p>The UCF Sick Leave Pool open enrollment is September 1-30, 2020. To be eligible for membership, applicants must be employed with UCF continuously for at least one year and have accrued 64 hours of sick leave as of September 2020. New members are required to donate 16 hours of their sick leave; part-time employees will donate an amount proportionate to their FTE. Membership reply letters will be sent to new applicants by early October 2020. </p>\n<p>Please note that if you are a current member of the Sick Leave Pool, you do not need to rejoin during open enrollment. The link listed below includes details on how to verify your current membership status and the <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/SLPApplication.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">application</a> to submit.</p>\n<p>Interested faculty and staff should send applications to the Human Resources Leave Administration section at <a href=\"mailto:loaandworkcomp@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">loaandworkcomp@ucf.edu</a>.</p>','2020-09-01','2020-09-30','http://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/leave-and-general-attendance-information/sick-leave-pools','Todd Coon','(407) 823-0540','loaandworkcomp@ucf.edu','Ben Anderson, UCF Human Resources','Publish',62),(3161,'USPS Employee of the Month (August):  Janet Feliciano','usps-employee-of-the-month-august-janet-feliciano','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for August 2020: Janet Feliciano.</p>\n<p>Janet Feliciano is the Administrative Assistant-Key Services for Housing &amp; Residence Life. Her nominators, Mr. Richard Berwanger and Ms. Kaila Kowalski, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>“Janet is one of those people who will inevitably go above and beyond every single day because that is just part of her nature. Janet will discover an issue or see a need and will never hesitate to jump in and do what she can to remedy the situation. When she works on a task, she thinks through every angle to ensure she is being proactive and limiting the room for error. This is especially important as Janet serves as the Manager of the Key System for approximately 12,000 residetial students and fifteen residential communities including our statellite properties such as Rosen and UnionWest.</em></p>\n<p><em>Janet has innate ability to connect to others, especially those she works around, in a way that always makes you feel welcomed, valued, and appreciated. I can’t say how many times the personnel in our shop have come to her with something, work or non-work related and walked away with a arenewed vison, a different understanding, a voice within themselves they never had, or a resolution that is clear, precise and positive. A lot of us become exhausted from doing our daily work and fulfilling our obligations, but not in this case. She is tireless, she has that piece, but also on the other end an internal strength from just always giving of herself.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Janet receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, her name in lights on the UCF campus marquee, and an introduction to the Board of Trustees. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Annual Awards Program.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>','2020-08-19','2020-09-04','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3162,'Hack@UCF Meetings go Virtual for Fall 2020','hackucf-meetings-go-virtual-for-fall-2020','<p>If you\'re interested in cybersecurity, come and learn with us.  We offer workshops that teach various security topics from the ground up.  Our competitive teams, such as our three-time national champion CCDC Team, participate in many security competitions.  Many of our competitions have gone Virtual this semester and are open to all interested club members.  Visit <a href=\"https://hackucf.org/blog\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hackucf.org</a> for more information on the club and sign-up for the club mailing list/newsletter.  Join URL: <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.zoom.us%2Fj%2F99668568780%3Fpwd%3DTHFUWHY2NS9DaUxPelozMDFwdVFPUT09&amp;data=02%7C01%7CThomas.Nedorost%40ucf.edu%7Ca8164ae83a2544d40be808d848614a4c%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637338930256328448&amp;sdata=ak4m%2B9q%2BkzgwUEVeBifvUJWZ5mBf%2FoUcu4YipvXmS%2Fc%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.zoom.us/j/99668568780?pwd=THFUWHY2NS9DaUxPelozMDFwdVFPUT09</a> every Friday starting at 5:30 pm.  We look forward to seeing you on ZOOM!</p>\n<p></p>','2020-08-25','2020-12-04','https://hackucf.org','Ryan Carnovsky','(856) 689-2334','rcarnovsky@hackucf.org','Collegiate Cyber Defense Club (aka Hack@UCF)','Publish',144),(3165,'Collective Bargaining Session - PBA','collective-bargaining-session-pba-1-2-3-4-5','<p><span>A collective bargaining session is scheduled between the Board of Trustees and the Police Benevolent Association (PBA) for August 28th at 2:00p.m.</span></p>','2020-08-27','2020-08-29','https://ucf.zoom.us/j/99854620479','Maureen Binder','(407) 823-0425','maureen.binder@ucf.edu','Brittny Bannister','Pending',205),(3166,'Applications open for 2021 Pabst Steinmetz Foundation Arts & Wellness Innovation Awards','2021-pabst-steinmetz-foundation-arts-wellness-innovation-awards','<p>Community organizations and UCF faculty/staff are invited to apply for the <strong>Pabst Steinmetz Foundation Arts &amp; Wellness Innovation Awards</strong> starting August 28. Two <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.us15.list-manage.com%2Ftrack%2Fclick%3Fu%3D64c14de756df35dc8187a403b%26id%3D7133d37ad9%26e%3Ddc252ff114&amp;data=02%7C01%7CVictoria.Weston%40ucf.edu%7C8dbebacc0b9c45a3087e08d84b80080f%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637342360541481041&amp;sdata=C0LDSVUAwbnly1MI5W%2F7G74DnxjTHg2%2FA7Qx4cgkD6I%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">$25,000 awards</a> are given to selected interdisciplinary disciplinary teams focused on the area of arts and wellness. Applicants must involve at least one community partner; the UCF College of Arts and Humanities and at least one other college, unit or center at the University of Central Florida in each submission; and all programs, initiatives or projects must contain an evaluation framework, quantitative or qualitative. Learn more and apply <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.us15.list-manage.com%2Ftrack%2Fclick%3Fu%3D64c14de756df35dc8187a403b%26id%3D3c0ed9dbc0%26e%3Ddc252ff114&amp;data=02%7C01%7CVictoria.Weston%40ucf.edu%7C8dbebacc0b9c45a3087e08d84b80080f%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637342360541481041&amp;sdata=yQwnO1aUSj4jGzU1BXg8ziqXHmkYvgPwZDogaMxfOLY%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> before November 20.</p>','2020-08-28','2020-11-20','https://www.cah.ucf.edu/research/arts-wellness-innovation-awards/','Heather Gibson',NULL,'heather.gibson@ucf.edu','UCF College of Arts and Humanities','Publish',10),(3167,'2021 O-Team Applications Open Now!','2020-o-team-applications-open-now','<p>First Year Experience is searching for dedicated, passionate student leaders to serve as Orientation Leaders on the 2021 O-Team!</p>\n<p>Orientation Leaders will welcome new students and families to the UCF community this upcoming summer. We encourage any undergraduate students to apply for this position! Applications are due October 11th at 11:59pm. The O-Team application can be found <a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_cGtJ7VNjH1HRaUl\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>! We encourage all applicants to attend an interest session for more information related to O-Team requirements, dates and position details.</p>\n<p>Interest Session Dates:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><em>Wednesday, September 9, 11am-12pm, In Person, TA 130</em></span></li>\n<li><span><em>Tuesday, September 15, 5pm-6pm, Virtual session </em></span><span></span></li>\n<li><span><em>Friday, September 25, 2pm-3pm, Virtual session</em></span></li>\n<li><span><em>Wednesday, September 30, 9am-10am, In-Person, TA 130</em></span></li>\n<li><span><em>Friday, October 2, 10am-11am, Virtual session </em></span></li>\n<li><span><em>Tuesday, October 6, 4:30pm-5:30pm, Virtual session </em></span><span></span></li>\n<li><span> </span><span><em>Friday, October 9, 4pm-5pm, In Person session</em></span><span>, TA 130</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<p>To register for information sessions and for more information regarding application details, please visit <a href=\"https://orientation.ucf.edu/about/oteam/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://orientation.ucf.edu/about/oteam/</a>.  </p>\n<p>If you have any additional questions, please reach out to <a href=\"mailto:oteam@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">oteam@ucf.edu</a>!</p>','2020-09-08','2020-10-11','https://orientation.ucf.edu/about/oteam/','Hannah','(407) 431-4077','hannah.ward@ucf.edu','First Year Experience','Publish',269),(3168,'Learn from UCF Experts During Healthcare Simulation Week (Sept. 14-19)','learn-from-ucf-experts-during-healthcare-simulation-week-2020','<p><strong><em>Telehealth, virtual reality, and using simulation to address healthcare disparities are among the topics being discussed at events this week hosted by the UCF College of Nursing.</em></strong></p>\n<p>To increase awareness of the importance of simulation in healthcare, UCF College of Nursing is joining the Society for Simulation in Healthcare and an international community of simulation centers for the fourth annual Healthcare Simulation Week.</p>\n<p>“Healthcare simulation continues to grow at an extraordinary rate,” said Bob Armstrong, president of the society. “An increasing number of professionals in the healthcare industry are waking up to simulation’s ability to help individuals and organizations improve patient care, which is so great to witness. We want to celebrate both that increased role and all healthcare simulation professionals this week.”</p>\n<p>UCF College of Nursing is a leader in healthcare simulation education. Currently, 10 percent of college faculty are<span> </span><a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/contact/faculty-staff/?people_group=simulation\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">certified healthcare simulation educators</a><span> </span>– three have earned advanced certification and are among the world’s leading experts in the field. The college is home to the<span> </span><a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/news/ucf-earns-international-accreditation-in-healthcare-simulation-education/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">internationally accredited Simulation, Technology, Innovation and Modeling (STIM) Center</a><span> </span>and Florida’s first – and one of only a few nationwide –<span> </span><a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/admissions/sim/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">healthcare simulation graduate programs</a>.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Healthcare Simulation Week Events</strong></p>\n<p>For the week of September 14 – 20, 2020, UCF College of Nursing and the UCF student-led<span> </span><a href=\"https://knightconnect.campuslabs.com/engage/organization/simsation\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Simsations-4-LIFE organization</a><span> </span>are hosting a series of virtual events. All events are open to the public, but advance registration is required.</p>\n<p><strong>Monday, Sept. 14 | Telehealth and Simulation Lunch and Learn</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>11:30 – 12:00 p.m.: Grab your lunch and participate in an engaging talk about the latest in healthcare simulation. </li>\n<li>12:00 – 12:30 p.m.: Certified telehealth educator<span> </span><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fnursing.ucf.edu%2Fpeople%2Fdawn-eckhoff%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7Ccarolyn%40ucf.edu%7Cbed92896c8ef407bd11e08d85574aa5b%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637353306846276492&amp;sdata=r5UUeP0IKNWHbGoO5EU2ApKDC9Zz6rsxifszxgc4FzQ%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Dawn Eckhoff ’18PhD</a><span> </span>will share her research in the field.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJErdOqrrTIqE9BlFzvYoZ-1RAoXoPoRK7lI\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">REGISTER</a><span></span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Tuesday, Sept. 15 | Become a Volunteer Patient “Actor” in UCF’s Accredited STIM Center</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>3:00 – 4:30 p.m.: Interested in volunteering as a remote “patient” or “actor” in simulations to train nursing students? No previous experience necessary. Learn more at the semi-annual Embedded Participant Volunteer online training event. Volunteers must be 18 years or older.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJUldOqgqT0rHdwdCgE9LiHTrHuo8UfNsZYR\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">REGISTER</a><span></span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Wednesday, Sept. 16 | Virtual Simulation and Other Research Lunch and Learn</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>11:30 – 12:00 p.m.: Grab your lunch and participate in an engaging discussion about STIM research at UCF. </li>\n<li>12:00 – 12:30 p.m.: <a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/news/wmfe-heres-how-hands-on-nursing-education-went-online-during-the-pandemic/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Valorie MacKenna ’20PhD</a>, director of simulation-based education at the University of Connecticut School of Nursing and recent graduate of the <a href=\"https://nursing.ucf.edu/academics/graduate-certificates/online-hcsim/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">healthcare simulation certificate</a> program, will share the findings from her research with virtual simulation and self-reflection.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJYrceytqTIsEtGEtTPYLbA7VBTW9g6HKHNA\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">REGISTER</a><span></span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Thursday, Sept. 17 | Augmented and Virtual Reality Lecture</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>4:00 – 5:00 p.m.: Virtual reality pioneer<span> </span><a href=\"https://www.cs.ucf.edu/person/carolina-cruz-neira/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Dr. Carolina Cruz-Neira</a><span> </span>from the UCF Department of Computer Science will share her expertise in the field of augmented and virtual reality.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJYlf-iurjMiHNXg7u8gx9fuvYud_d4S0QCM\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">REGISTER</a><span></span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Friday, Sept. 18 | Addressing Healthcare Disparities with Simulation-based Education and Simsations-4-LIFE Lunch and Learn</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>11:30 – 12:00 p.m.: Simsations-4-LIFE will share their plans for the academic year. </li>\n<li>12:00 – 12:30 p.m.: UCF student researchers will share their research and work to address healthcare disparities with simulation-based education.  </li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJMscOivpjIuHNYsafZv5fiZFkpl7opCmDJJ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">REGISTER</a><span></span></p>\n<p> </p>','2020-09-14','2020-09-18','https://nursing.ucf.edu/news/learn-from-ucf-experts-during-healthcare-simulation-week-2020/','Desiree Diaz',NULL,'desiree.diaz@ucf.edu','UCF College of Nursing','Publish',57),(3171,'Virtual Session: Explore UCF\'s Research Administration Programs','explore-ucfs-research-administration-programs-1','<p><span>Are you a research administration professional looking to take the next steps in your career? Have you considered a graduate degree in research administration? UCF offers a graduate degree and graduate certificate in research administration. The fully online program focuses on cutting-edge research administration techniques and emphasizes a curriculum that can be designed to suit your specific needs. Learn more at the next online info session on September 17 from <strong>12-12:30pm</strong>. <br><br></span><a href=\"https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/mra917\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Registration</a><span> is required. </span></p>','2020-09-15','2020-09-18','https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/mra917','Angela White-Jones','(407) 823-2604','angela.white-jones@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3173,'Virtual Session: Explore a Career in Urban & Regional Planning','explore-a-career-in-urban-regional-planning-1','<p>Join program director, Dr. Luis Santiago, for a virtual conversation on the Master of Urban &amp; Regional Planning program. Urban and regional planning, is a rapidly growing field, particularly in areas similar to Central Florida, as new businesses and residents continue relocate to the area. The program offers courses in the evening to accommodate the schedules of working professionals. </p>\n<p>In the session, we\'ll discuss the course curriculum, tuition, application and career opportunities in the field. Join us on<strong> October 5</strong> from <strong>1:00 - 1:30pm</strong>. </p>\n<p>For more information on the Master of Urban &amp; Regional Planning program, please join us for the<span> <a href=\"https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/urb105\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">virtual information session</a>. </span> </p>','2020-09-19','2020-10-06','https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/urb105','Luis Santiago','(407) 823-2604','luis.santiago2@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3174,'Virtual Session: Start a Career in Public Policy','start-a-career-in-public-policy','<p>Do you have an interest in policy as it relates to local, state or federal government; health; transportation; and more? Want to learn more about UCF\'s<span> </span><strong>new</strong><span> </span>Master of Public Policy based in downtown Orlando? Then you don\'t want to miss this! </p>\n<p>Learn about the program curriculum, application requirements and employment opportunities related to public policy in this 30-minute session on <strong>September 29</strong> from <strong>12:00 - 12:30pm</strong>. </p>\n<p><a href=\"https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/mpp929\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register</a><span> </span><strong>now</strong><span> </span>to secure your spot! </p>','2020-09-16','2020-09-30','https://applynow.graduate.ucf.edu/register/mpp929','Edlira Dursun','(407) 823-2604','edlira.dursun@ucf.edu','UCF School of Public Administration','Publish',155),(3179,'USPS Staff Employee Scholarship Award and Barnes & Noble Bookstore Award','usps-staff-employee-scholarship-award-and-barnes-and-noble-bookstore-award-1-2-3-4','<p>The USPS Staff Council is now accepting applications for the Fall 2020 Scholarship awards.  Apply now at the Staff Council web site, (<a href=\"http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/</a>) or on the Council Facebook page.  There are two awards available.  Dependents of USPS staff may apply for the Campus Bookstore Scholarship.  Applications must be submitted by 11:59 p.m. September 30, 2020.  You may apply for one or both of the awards if you wish.   The only restrictions are you must be a member of the USPS for a minimum of one year, and if you have won an award you must wait one year before applying for that particular award again.  Apply now and avoid the rush!</p>','2020-09-18','2020-09-30','http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/','Jamie LaMoreaux','(407) 882-0191','lamoreaj@ucf.edu','USPS Staff Council','Publish',54),(3183,'LIGHT UP UCF 2020 Update','light-up-ucf-2020-update','<p>We regret to inform our Orlando community that due to ongoing public health and safety concerns and uncertainties surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic, the tough decision has been made to not hold Light Up UCF this year. The safety and well-being of our guests, employees, partners, and vendors remain our number one priority as we navigate through these times.</p>\n<p>Light Up UCF wishes everyone a safe and healthy holiday season this year.</p>','2020-09-17','2020-12-31',NULL,'ALLISON DOBIN',NULL,'Allison.Dobin@spectraxp.com','UCF Communications','Publish',166),(3194,'National Hazing Prevention and Awareness Week','national-hazing-prevention-and-awareness-week','<p>National Hazing Prevention and Awareness Week takes place during the third week of September. UCF sponsors various events, workshops and educational sessions to help students understand the impact of hazing, including the short-term and long-term consequences associated with participation in these activities. All events this year will be virtual. </p>\n<p>The week includes a discussion sponsored by <a href=\"http://HazingPrevention.org\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">HazingPrevention.org</a> featuring parents who have suffered the loss of their children to hazing incidents.  On Monday we will host two workshops on anti-hazing laws in the state of Florida.  David Bianchi, author of Andrew’s Law recently signed by Gov. DeSantis, will discuss how the new law affects parents, students, staff and advisors.  On Tuesday, UCF Band Director Tremon Kizer will facilitate a session on how we can change the culture of hazing by developing healthy traditions.  On Wednesday, Office of Student Conduct staff members Xavier Shannon and Heather Cohen will share information about the organizational and group conduct process.  Additionally, there will be online contests and prizes and the opportunity to sign the pledge against hazing.</p>\n<p>View the full calendar of events here: <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fantihazing.sdes.ucf.edu%2Fnational-hazing-prevention-week%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7CAdrianne.Demetry%40ucf.edu%7C397f2c13495340f3202f08d85beb21dd%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637360412723704646&amp;sdata=cgnL%2BnkxBhR4pUzwt5sF8c7Q97DON3tsE4QlwUf2Yd8%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://antihazing.sdes.ucf.edu/national-hazing-prevention-week/</a></p>','2020-09-21','2020-09-25','https://antihazing.sdes.ucf.edu/national-hazing-prevention-week/','Germayne Graham','(407) 823-2223','anti-hazing@ucf.edu','Adrianne Demetry','Publish',271),(3195,'Enter to be Featured on Bounce House Live during UCF Football Games','enter-to-be-featured-on-bounce-house-live-during-ucf-football-games','<p><span>UCF Athletics introduces Bounce House Live, a new initiative for the 2020 home football season that gives fans an opportunity to be a part of the game from the comfort of their living room.</span><br><span> </span><br><span>Fans can enter to win by filling out </span><a href=\"https://ucfknights.com/sb_output.aspx?form=2119\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">THIS FORM</a><span>. The deadline to sign up for the home opener is Wednesday, Sept. 30, by 5 p.m.</span><br><span> </span><br><span>Winners will be featured throughout the game on the video board in the Bounce House with live look-ins at celebrations, field goal distractions, crowd prompts, contests, trivia and more.</span><br><span> </span><br><span>The first Bounce House Live will take place during UCF\'s home opener on Saturday, Oct. 3 against Tulsa. The game vs. the Golden Hurricane is scheduled for 7:30 p.m.</span></p>','2020-09-24','2020-09-30','https://ucfknights.com/sb_output.aspx?form=2119','UCF Athletics','(407) 823-1000','knights@ucfathletics.com','UCF Athletics','Publish',165),(3196,'USPS Employee of the Month - September 2020 Judy Rechsteiner','usps-employee-of-the-month-september-2020-judy-rechsteiner','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for September 2020: Judy Rechsteiner.</p>\n<p>Judy Rechsteiner is the Admissions Specialist II in the College of Nursing. Her nominators, Jessica Simmons and Lucas Noboa, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>“<span>Judy brings consistency and dependability to the College that positively impacts student success, clinical placement, and clinical partnerships. She is committed to lifelong learning in leadership, diversity, and technology. Without Judy, students would not be able to successfully complete their clinical requirements. Judy plays a key role in the College of Nursing</span></em><span><em>.</em></span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span><em>I think Judy’s most outstanding attribute to our College and the University is her unwavering commitment to our students. Clinical experiences are a large portion of a Nursing students’ education and Judy works very hard behind-the-scenes to make this all possible. In many cases, she stands as an advocate on behalf of the student without them even knowing.”</em></span></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Judy receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, and a goody bag. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>','2020-09-30','2020-10-16','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione',NULL,'theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3197,'Save on Game Day Gear!','save-on-game-day-gear','<p>Celebrate your school spirit and support your UCF Knights! Check out a few different ways to buy your game day gear below.</p>\n<p>To kick off the first home game, receive 25% off Nike gear from 9/28/20 to 10/2/20 at one of the three Barnes &amp; Noble partnered locations. Visit the UCF Bookstore in the John T. Washington Center, the Barnes &amp; Noble Knights Plaza location, or online at <a href=\"https://ucf.bncollege.com/shop/ucf/home\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.bncollege.com/shop/ucf/home</a>.</p>\n<p>The UCF Athletics site also gives you access to merchandise deals. Please visit them at <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fshop.ucfknights.com%2F%3F_s%3Dbm-top_nav%26utm_source%3Ducf%26utm_medium%3Dreferral&amp;data=02%7C01%7CSue.Gonzalez%40ucf.edu%7Cd99d104584844f58223e08d85fe49ef4%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637364782812673472&amp;sdata=Ee8bTnbjNA3BSTpEuyGSv%2FwOx6myuw2MaQVUhB1P2OU%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://shop.ucfknights.com/?_s=bm-top_nav&amp;utm_source=ucf&amp;utm_medium=referral</a>.</p>\n<p><em>*25% off Nike apparel promotion does not apply to this site. </em></p>','2020-09-28','2020-10-03','https://ucf.bncollege.com/shop/ucf/home','Sue Gonzalez','(407) 823-3539','Sue.Gonzalez@ucf.edu','Administrative Affairs','Publish',273),(3198,'Omicron Delta Kappa applications','omicron-delta-kappa-applications-1','<p>The Omicron Delta Kappa Society is the national leadership honor society for college students, faculty, staff, administrators, and alumni that recognizes and encourages superior scholarship, leadership, and exemplary character.</p>\n<p>The student and faculty members of Omicron Delta Kappa work closely together to foster leadership abilities within its members. The organization is also dedicated to a variety of projects that benefit the university and the surrounding community.</p>\n<p><strong>Requirements for induction into the</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Central Florida Circle of ODK:</strong></p>\n<p>Class standing: Sophomore (at least 30 credits), Junior, Senior, or Graduate Level</p>\n<p>Minimum GPA: 3.2 for undergraduates, 3.5 for graduate students</p>\n<p>Initiation fee of $95-includes lifetime membership and pin (graduation cords may be purchased for an additional $25) . If accepted your dues will be due by 11/5/20 at 12:00 PM. Induction will be held on Thursday, November 19 at 5:30pm via Zoom (link will be sent out once dues are paid)</p>\n<p>Demonstrated leadership in at least two of the five areas:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Scholarship</li>\n<li>Athletics</li>\n<li>Campus/Community Service, Social/Religious Activities, and Campus Government</li>\n<li>Journalism, Speech and the Mass Media</li>\n<li>Creative and Performing Arts</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>How to Apply:</strong></p>\n<p>Visit our website at <u><a href=\"https://membership.odk.org/audience/prospective_members/membership_application_form\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://membership.odk.org/audience/prospective_members/membership_application_form</a></u> to complete the online application</p>\n<p>Questions may be directed to Dr. Stacey Malaret, Faculty Secretary for ODK, in the LEAD Scholars Academy Office, Ferrell Commons 165</p>\n<p><strong>Online application deadline is </strong><strong>10/27/20</strong></p>','2020-09-29','2020-10-27','https://membership.odk.org/audience/prospective_members/membership_application_form','Stacey Malaret','(407) 595-2221','malaret@ucf.edu','Stacey Malaret','Publish',8),(3199,'2020 UCF Virtual Majors Fair this Wednesday','2020-ucf-virtual-majors-fair','<p>On October 7 from 11 a.m. - 2 p.m., the Knights Major Exploration and Transition Center, the 2020 UCF Virtual Majors Fair is a fully online experience that connects current UCF students directly to academic colleges to learn more about the majors and minors offered at the university.Students will have an opportunity to speak with college advisors, faculty members and staff from across campus. This event is an excellent opportunity for students to explore majors in one centralized location and learn about available campus resources to help them successfully navigate the major exploration process. All students are invited to attend this event to gather more information on the many academic areas of study offered by UCF.</p>\n<p>To participate in event, students must register via <a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/2020-ucf-virtual-majors-fair-registration-120243368151\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Eventbrite</a>. Students will receive a link to participate online following registration.</p>\n<p>Visit the <a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/2020-ucf-virtual-majors-fair-registration-120243368151\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">2020 UCF Virtual Majors Fair webpage</a> to learn more. </p>','2020-10-04','2020-10-08','https://academicsuccess.ucf.edu/kmetc/','Knights Major Exploration and Transition Center','(407) 823-3165','kmetcoutreach@ucf.edu','Student Learning and Academic Success','Publish',275),(3200,'Thriving Versus Surviving: Building Resilience in Turbulent Times [Free CE Lecture]','thriving-versus-surviving-building-resilience-in-turbulent-times','<p><strong></strong><span><strong>Stressed during uncertain times?</strong> If you, your staff or your colleagues are feeling particularly spent, it is probably because the level of emotional exhaustion in healthcare workers was already at an all-time-high before COVID-19, with one out of three people already meeting the criteria for burnout. In this enlightening and entertaining module, we will provide some perspective, hope, and simple strategies to try during tense times.</span> </p>\n<p>Join the UCF College of Nursing virtually on Oct. 27 from 2-4 p.m. for its 10th annual Orlando Health Nursing Lecture during the Year of the Nurse <strong>featuring guest speaker Bryan Sexton, Ph.D.</strong>, director of Duke Center for Healthcare Safety and Quality and associate professor of psychiatry at Duke University School of Medicine.</p>\n<p><strong>Learning Objectives: </strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span>To succinctly identify and explain how increases in stress at the societal and nursing unit levels impact care quality and self-care in general. Measure unit level norms that enhance vs. hinder work-life balance.</span></li>\n<li><span>To recognize the factors that contribute to burnout, understand the psychology behind how it develops, and the theory behind evidence-based approaches to reduce it.</span></li>\n<li><span>To practice the evidence-based skills, strategies, and positive psychology tools provided in resilience webinars.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p><br><strong>Attendees who are nurses can earn 2.0 contact hours. </strong></p>\n<p><strong><span><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ft.e2ma.net%2Fclick%2Fsbp7md%2Fwylnw6gb%2Fsvsbgg&amp;data=02%7C01%7Ccarolyn%40ucf.edu%7C90796a08cabe445270f008d85b19d5da%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637359513828006285&amp;sdata=0Lz8ST0Z1eTHJacIW7hiVusjroWT3vvpRDrX7Hy2fAQ%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Advanced registration</a> is required to participate via Zoom Webinar. </span></strong></p>','2020-10-12','2020-10-27','https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_9hW8tqnASmORJl1l5yKbtQ','Lisa Goldblatt',NULL,'nursingevents@ucf.edu','UCF College of Nursing','Publish',57),(3201,'Lecture Series: Hispanics in Central Florida: Key to Region’s Economic Growth','college-of-undergraduate-students-lecture-series-hispanics-in-central-florida-key-to-regions-economic-growth','<p><span>Join the College of Undergraduate Studies, Univision, UniMás Orlando and 98.1FM on Friday at noon to discuss the important role that Hispanics play in Central Florida. Humberto Hormaza, senior vice president and general manager of Orlando Univision, UniMás, and 98.1 FM will discuss how Hispanics will shape the future of the region. A panel of Univision professionals will share their career journeys.</span></p>\n<p><span>Register for this at: <a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_R_-liRweQjGv0n32V-OhgQ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_R_-liRweQjGv0n32V-OhgQ</a></span></p>','2020-10-08','2020-10-09','http://CUGSComm@ucf.edu','Barbara Smith','(407) 823-3197','CUGSComm@ucf.edu','College of Undergraduate Studies','Publish',275),(3204,'Eminent Scholars Lecture Series: Justice for All?','eminent-scholars-lecture-series-justice-for-all','<p><span>The UCF Center for Public and Nonprofit Management invites you to an intimate, virtual conversation with Dr. Mary E. Guy on <strong>November 18, 2020 </strong>from 11am-12pm EST. <br><br>Entitled \"Justice for All? Public Administration\'s Role in Advancing Social Equity,\" the talk examines the levers that public service professionals have at their disposal to advance social justice and serves as the topic for the Fall 2020 Eminent Scholars Lecture Series.</span><br><br><span>Guy\'s discussion will consider the roles civil institutions and the public service sector play that go beyond pursuing fairness through equality of administrative access and protecting procedural due process to create a community where equity is the norm. </span><br><br><span>It\'s a timely discussion as we approach a highly contentious election, confront a global crisis, contend with economic instability and navigate social unrest. The challenge of governance extends beyond policies, procedures, and laws. It requires that each community’s social architecture advance equity rather than hinder it. Public service’s many facets offer opportunities to do just that.</span><br><br>Register <a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/fall-2020-eminent-scholar-lecture-series-featuring-dr-mary-guy-phd-tickets-123387287699\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. </p>','2020-10-09','2020-11-18','https://www.eventbrite.com/e/fall-2020-eminent-scholar-lecture-series-featuring-dr-mary-guy-phd-tickets-123387287699','Justin Miller','(407) 823-3794','cpnm@ucf.edu','UCF Center for Public and Nonprofit Management','Publish',155),(3205,'Tune in for Matters of Diversity with Dr. B','new-series-matters-of-diversity-with-dr-b-launches-oct-21','<p>The Office of Diversity and Inclusion has created a Diversity Dialogues Series designed to highlight equity issues as they relate to the University of Central Florida community. The episodes will be broadcast live via Zoom and <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCKZwSu_zPMXx7NdKFW4683A\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">YouTube</a> on Wednesdays from 3–4 p.m. and Fridays from 1–2 p.m. weekly. The Wednesday show will have fireside chats with UCF administrators, faculty, staff and community stakeholders. The Friday show is designed to specifically engage with UCF students providing them with a platform to share their views.</p>','2020-10-14','2020-11-30','https://m.youtube.com/channel/UCKZwSu_zPMXx7NdKFW4683A','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','(407) 823-6479','diverse@ucf.edu','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','Publish',165),(3206,'ChargeOn Virtual Panel: UCF Alumnae Leading the Charge','chargeon-virtual-panel-ucf-alumnae-leading-the-charge','<p><em>ChargeOn</em> Virtual Panel: UCF Alumnae Leading the Charge<br> <em>Wednesday, Oct. 21 from 11:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. </em></p>\n<p><span>Join us as we chat with an inspiring group of alumnae from a variety of industries at our <strong><a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/ChargeOnPanel\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ChargeOn Virtual Panel: UCF Alumnae Leading the Charge</a> </strong></span></p>\n<p><span>We’ll learn how UCF has played a in role in their lives, how they have overcome obstacles and what advice they have for the future. UCF Alumni is proud to feature the following alumnae:</span></p>\n<p><strong>Emcee:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Maritza Martinez ’00 ’05MA ’11MBA</strong></span><span>, associate vice president for the Division of Government and Community Relations and director for the Office of Community Relations and Economic Development at UCF</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span><strong>Panelists:</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span><strong>Phyllis Klock HC’14</strong></span><span>, retired president and chief operating officer of CompBenefits Corporation</span></li>\n<li><span><strong>Ruth Colombe ’12</strong></span><span>, portfolio marketing manager at The Coca-Cola Company</span></li>\n<li><span><strong>Jonell Radabaugh ’15</strong></span><span>, associate project manager for Walt Disney World\'s Facility Asset Management</span></li>\n<li><span><strong>Reverend Marcietta ‘Marcie’ Washington ’83</strong></span><span>, retired NASA engineer, ordained minister and cancer survivor</span></li>\n<li><strong>Ybeth Bruzual \'05</strong>, two-time Emmy award winning journalist and News 13 anchor</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong></strong></p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/ChargeOnPanel\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register Here!</a></strong></p>','2020-10-12','2020-10-21','https://ucfalumni.com/events/homecoming','Laura Heiselman','(407) 823-1498','laura.heiselman@ucf.edu','Laura Heiselman, UCF Alumni','Publish',277),(3207,'Share the Knight with the Cartwrights','share-the-knight-with-the-cartwrights','<p><span>Please be our guest for a very special evening as we celebrate the future of UCF. </span> <span>You\'re invited to join UCF Alumni as we get to know the University of Central Florida\'s sixth President, <a data-name=\"Dr. Alexander Cartwright\" data-type=\"url\" href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ft.e2ma.net%2Fclick%2F3xgrns%2Ffjxnk1k%2Frgf5fq&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cashley.marley%40ucf.edu%7C7a25646f509a47cb2af908d86edff689%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637381255480132827&amp;sdata=vwJohXLOWkHHHIrRWfEKmZhPfBypa3rQ3HS%2FzE9oJEg%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Dr. Alexander Cartwright</a> and First Lady, Melinda Cartwright. You won’t want to miss this intimate conversation led by UCF Foundation Board member</span><span> </span><span><a data-name=\"Dr. Gideon J. Lewis \'00\" data-type=\"url\" href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ft.e2ma.net%2Fclick%2F3xgrns%2Ffjxnk1k%2F78f5fq&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cashley.marley%40ucf.edu%7C7a25646f509a47cb2af908d86edff689%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637381255480132827&amp;sdata=cvSD76gmP8sC16jw0t7KF3z7WMJ7EXoshw1wx2xsDSo%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Gideon J. Lewis \'00</a>, a UCF alumnus, renowned physician, surgeon, educator and entrepreneur.</span> <span>It’s an exciting time for UCF, and we want to share it with you.</span> <span>Please register in advance and submit a question that may be answered during this special live session. We look forward to seeing you virtually on Nov. 4. </span></p>\n<p><span>Register at: <a href=\"http://www.ucffoundation.org/STKEast\" rel=\"nofollow\">www.ucffoundation.org/STKEast</a></span></p>','2020-10-21','2020-11-05','https://www.ucffoundation.org/STKEast','Ashley Marley','(407) 823-1978','ashley.marley@knights.ucf.edu','UCF Alumni','Publish',276),(3208,'Lunch in Pompeii: How Metal Shaped Pompeii and the Roman Empire','lunch-in-pompeii-how-metal-shaped-pompeii-and-the-roman-empire','<p><strong>Wednesday, October 28 </strong></p>\n<p><strong>noon - 1 p.m. EST</strong></p>\n<p><strong>virtual Zoom event</strong></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Join us for lunch in Pompeii! Faculty from the UCF Anthropology and Chemistry Departments, and educators from Orlando Science Center, will help us walk back in time and explore artifacts from </span><a href=\"https://www.osc.org/pompeii/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em></a><span> and how they relate to the modern world. The artifacts discussed in these talks will be on display in </span><em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em><span> traveling exhibit at Orlando Science Center, October 26 – January 24.</span></p>\n<p><span>Zoom virtual talks: 30 minute talk and then moderated Q&amp;A.</span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span><a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_4JhSjEiGLgvUOpL\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Click Here to RSVP</strong></a></span></p>\n<p><span><strong></strong></span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Speaker: Joseph “Seppi” Lehner, Ph.D.</strong><br></span>Australian Research Council Discovery Early Career Research Award Fellow<br>Department of Archaeology<br>The University of Sydney</p>\n<p>Courtesy Assistant Professor<br>Department of Anthropology<br>University of Central Florida</p>\n<p><strong></strong></p>\n<p><strong></strong></p>\n<p>Learn more about the talk <a href=\"https://sciences.ucf.edu/lunch-in-pompeii/how-metal-shaped-pompeii/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p>','2020-10-15','2020-10-28','https://sciences.ucf.edu/lunch-in-pompeii/how-metal-shaped-pompeii/','UCF College of Sciences','(407) 823-0446','COSMarketing@ucf.edu','UCF College of Sciences','Publish',278),(3209,'John Lewis: Good Trouble Virtual Cinema','john-lewis-good-trouble-virtual-cinema','<p><a data-link=\"https://watch.eventive.org/johnlewis/play/5f6ccbfed129750062b1750d\" href=\"https://watch.eventive.org/johnlewis/play/5f6ccbfed129750062b1750d\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">John Lewis: Good Trouble</a><span> </span>tells the story of Congressman John Lewis, an American hero who spent his life fighting for voting rights and racial justice. As he put it, making ‘good trouble’. As we continue to fight for racial equity, we invite you to join us in this special screening of the virtual cinema documentary, John Lewis: Good Trouble, directed by Dawn Porter, to celebrate UCF Diversity. While watching John Lewis: Good Trouble at home, $5 from every ticket purchase will go directly to<span> </span><a data-link=\"https://sja.sdes.ucf.edu/\" href=\"https://sja.sdes.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Social Justice and Advocacy</a><span> </span>activities and programs designed to increase diversity education and inclusion on campus.</p>\n<p>All registrants will be entered in a pool where three winners will be randomly selected to win the John Lewis Memoir “Walking with the Wind: A Memoir of the Movement,” which will also be highlighted in a UCF Alumni Book Club discussion!</p>\n<p><strong>Supporting Diversity at UCF</strong><br>Your personal philanthropy serves a vital role in UCF\'s diversity initiatives. Please consider a one-time or monthly recurring<span> </span><a data-link=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/dei\" href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/dei\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">gift to support</a><span> </span>important enrichment programs designed to improve equity and inclusion within the UCF community.</p>\n<p></p>','2020-10-19','2020-10-23','https://watch.eventive.org/johnlewis/play/5f6ccbfed129750062b1750d','Ashley Marley','(407) 823-1978','ashley.marley@ucf.edu','UCF Alumni','Publish',276),(3210,'Benefits Open Enrollment','benefits-open-enrollment-1-2-3-4-5-6','<p>The state\'s annual open enrollment period for eligible employees to change insurance benefits options begins on Monday, Oct. 19 at 8 a.m. and ends Friday, Nov. 6 at 6 p.m. EST.</p>\n<p>This year, information will be delivered through webinars, recordings, and supporting provider materials through Friday, Oct. 30. There will be no in-person Benefits Fair this year.</p>\n<p>Please visit<span> </span><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fhr.ucf.edu%2Fopen-enrollment&amp;data=02%7C01%7Ckeven%40ucf.edu%7Ca35ee3c4cd9c400190d408d86ac73dce%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637376751257588519&amp;sdata=oiABOg3EMgTgoPh%2BEP7BhI5pTZGbcmNM8V629Pz%2B7RE%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/open-enrollment</a><span> </span>for details and updates.</p>\n<p>Questions can be directed to<span> </span><a href=\"mailto:benefits@ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">benefits@ucf.edu</a><span> </span>or 407-823-2771.</p>','2020-10-19','2020-11-06','https://hr.ucf.edu/open-enrollment','UCF HR Benefits','(407) 823-2771','benefits@ucf.edu','UCF HR Benefits','Publish',262),(3211,'Celebrate National Cyber Security Awareness Month: PegaSec Cyber Security Expo, Weekly Webinars and Phishing Derby','celebrate-national-cyber-security-awareness-month-pegasec-cyber-security-expo-weekly-webinars-and-phishing-derby','<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PegaSec Cyber Security Expo</strong></span><span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"> </span><br></span><span>On Friday, Oct. 30, InfoSec will be hosting the annual PegaSec Cyber Security Expo to conclude National Cyber Security Awareness Month. Attend this virtual event to:</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>·         </span><span>Learn how criminals can defeat your multi-factor authentication, and what you can do to stop them.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>·         </span><span>Hear about the FBI cyber threat landscape and see current and emerging trends.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>·         </span><span>See the technology that can threaten the encryption currently used to protect your information.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>·         </span><span>Avoid becoming a fraud victim by learning from an FBI special agent what steps you can take.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>·         </span><span>Get a behind-the-scenes look into cybersecurity from industry experts.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>Due to security considerations, <strong>some sessions will not be recorded — so reserve your space now</strong>. To view the full agenda and register for sessions, please visit </span><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Finfosec.ucf.edu%2Fpegasec&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C6f64b4c18e9f4fcbd67808d8743e29e8%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637387157620460752%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=iw2m2QripCWB3j0HeM8HW3Xx57aUScYv5vvKwRBb6yM%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><span><strong>https://infosec.ucf.edu/pegasec</strong></span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Weekly Themed Webinars</strong></span><span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"> </span><br></span><span>Throughout October, InfoSec will be hosting <a href=\"https://infosec.ucf.edu/ncsam.\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">weekly webinars </a>to share information security tips. Each webinar will focus on that week’s theme during NCSAM.  For those who can’t attend at the scheduled time, the webinars will be recorded and made <a href=\"https://infosec.ucf.edu/ncsam.\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">available on the website</a>, <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Finfosec.ucf.edu%2Fncsam&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C6f64b4c18e9f4fcbd67808d8743e29e8%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637387157620460752%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=hi9Q8gR0d1Yfi8wNEcmNyFO5fQ4kU06BP0xI8NTx3wE%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>https://infosec.ucf.edu/ncsam</strong></a>.</span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Week 1 – If You Connect It, Protect It</strong>: Smart home devices, security cameras, and anything else that’s connected to the Internet creates a risk to your privacy and device security.  Learn about steps you can take to reduce your risk from all those Internet-connected devices you may have.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Week 2 – Securing Devices at Home and Work</strong>: How many are reading this from their homes?  The current pandemic has shifted how we work, learn, and shop.  We’ll discuss what can be done to protect your devices and online accounts both in your personal and professional lives.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Week 3 – Securing Internet-Connected Devices in Healthcare</strong>: Having a virtual visit with your doctor is convenient, but also carries risk to your data and privacy.  We’ll talk about what we can do to protect our health information.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Week 4 – The Future of Connected Devices</strong>: As technology evolves, so do the threats. We’ll peer into our crystal balls and try to imagine how future technology will impact our online experiences, and what risks we may need to face.</span><span> </span> </p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Phishing Derby</strong></span><span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"> </span><br></span><span>As part of National Cyber Security Awareness Month, researchers and the InfoSec team at UCF are conducting a competition where participants test their ability to identify a wide variety of phishing emails. Those who have signed up will receive several simulated phishing emails throughout October.  Successfully spotting and reporting these phishing messages will increase the reward the participants receive. </span></p>\n<p><span>During a session at PegaSec on Friday, Oct. 30 the results of the research study will be reviewed. Join the session to learn more about phishing, how you can spot phishing attacks and see if you can guess which messages hooked the most participants.</span></p>\n<p><strong>Reserve your spot in the session now: <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.zoom.us%2Fmeeting%2Fregister%2FtJIpdeygqD0pGdKyrKktk5lvfGijz_9RDB-r&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C6f64b4c18e9f4fcbd67808d8743e29e8%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637387157620470749%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=m47n2jDE048WU9WcJgvO7fNLGER%2FIOPkYoFELMaRISc%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Original URL:\nhttps://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJIpdeygqD0pGdKyrKktk5lvfGijz_9RDB-r\n\nClick to follow link.\">https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJIpdeygqD0pGdKyrKktk5lvfGijz_9RDB-r</a>  </strong></p>','2020-10-01','2020-10-31','https://infosec.ucf.edu/pegasec','Michael Constantino','(407) 823-3979','michael.constantino@ucf.edu','UCF Communications','Publish',166),(3212,'Knight Vision Kick-Off Open Forum with UCF Leadership','knight-vision-erp-kick-off-open-forum','<p>UCF is kicking off <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fknightvision.it.ucf.edu%2F&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C0cc86b4540b34687cb5508d876056e0d%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637389112980836696%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=I35YIdojWXaZwdIXTCcRmljbXaTsKDDWvZUYfUIr5%2FM%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Knight Vision</a>, a multi-year project to transform the way we operate in serving our students, faculty, and staff by increasing the effectiveness and efficiency of our administrative processes. Knight Vision will replace PeopleSoft financial, human resources and student information systems with Workday, a modern, <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ferp.it.ucf.edu%2F&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C0cc86b4540b34687cb5508d876056e0d%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637389112980846692%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=jJkoyL9eV22I5NnZ2ARpIriHHpCCx9okZBIyD1%2FdaCY%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">cloud-based enterprise resource planning (ERP) platform</a>. It will also update many of our business processes to match leading practices that have been proven effective at other institutions of higher learning.</p>\n<p>To learn more about this critical initiative, the entire campus community is invited to attend the Knight Vision Kickoff Open Forum on Tuesday, November 3 at 11 a.m. President Cartwright and Interim Provost Michael Johnson will participate as the Knight Vision project team shares information about what the UCF community can expect over the next few years, followed by a question and answer session.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>Join virtually via Zoom:</strong> <br><a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.zoom.us%2Fj%2F93037038855%3Fpwd%3DNEQybG1ZeUpsYnJPS2h6aGFDdkprQT09&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C0cc86b4540b34687cb5508d876056e0d%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637389112980856692%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=JI%2FUKQDwFROdxkyjyvXQ8gb4xSK%2BEiHp4RgaJHgx8Hw%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.zoom.us/j/93037038855?pwd=NEQybG1ZeUpsYnJPS2h6aGFDdkprQT09</a><br>Passcode: 947729</p>\n<p><strong>Or iPhone one-tap :</strong><br>US: +13017158592,,93037038855# or +13126266799,,93037038855#</p>\n<p><br><strong>Or Telephone:</strong><br>Dial(for higher quality, dial a number based on your current location):<br>US: +1 301 715 8592 or +1 312 626 6799 or +1 929 205 6099 or +1 253 215 8782 or +1 346 248 7799 or +1 669 900 6833<br>Webinar ID: 930 3703 8855</p>\n<p><br><strong>International numbers available:</strong> <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fucf.zoom.us%2Fu%2FayfhrZAsk&amp;data=04%7C01%7CNicole.Dudenhoefer%40ucf.edu%7C0cc86b4540b34687cb5508d876056e0d%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637389112980856692%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=T0BsPIViI8HVY4gVo1LClFLlXM6UY%2BmcfpmaRJS7rs4%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.zoom.us/u/ayfhrZAsk</a></p>\n<p><strong>Stream the open forum on Youtube: </strong><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dUor8477xsA\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dUor8477xsA</a></p>\n<p>*Please note <span> YouTube viewers will be unable to submit questions to panelists during the event. To submit questions, please attend via Zoom.</span></p>','2020-10-22','2020-11-03','https://knightvision.it.ucf.edu','Thomas Diaz',NULL,'thomas.diaz@ucf.edu','UCF Communications','Publish',166),(3213,'Symposium: Life and Death in Pompeii','symposium-life-and-death-in-pompeii','<p><strong></strong><strong></strong>Engage in a lively presentation and discussion about life and death in Pompeii. Historians of art, archaeology, and classical languages and literature, will present their research as it relates to Pompeii. UCF Associate Professor of Art History, Ilenia Colón Mendoza<span>, </span><span>Ph.D.,</span> will moderate the symposium and Q&amp;A discussion that will follow each presentation. <span>Learn more about the symposium </span><a href=\"https://arts.cah.ucf.edu/symposium-pompeii/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a></p>\n<p>Presentations will include:<br><br><strong><em>Greek and Roman Myths in the Houses of Pompeii and the Bay of Naples</em></strong><br><span>With Robert Vander Poppen, Ph.D., Rollins College</span><br><br><strong><em>Public Entertainment in Pompeii</em></strong><br><span>With Edward Dandrow, Ph.D., University of Central Florida</span><br><br><em><strong>Pompeii: Cultural Heritage and Preservation</strong></em><br><span>With Margaret Ann Zaho, Ph.D., University of Central Florida<br></span><br>This symposium is in partnership with the Orlando Science Center, Orange County Arts and Cultural Affairs and their tourism partners to support the blockbuster exhibit <em><a href=\"https://www.osc.org/pompeii/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Pompeii: The Immortal City</a>, </em>on view from<em> </em><span>October 26, 2020 – January 24, 2021.</span></p>\n<p><strong>Date: Nov. 6, Noon to 1:30 p.m. ET<br></strong><br><strong><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_CvgL2VnGRcKcIiuTHfwr2g\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Click Here to Register</a></strong></p>','2020-10-27','2020-11-06','https://arts.cah.ucf.edu/symposium-pompeii/','Hannah Estes',NULL,'hannah.estes@ucf.edu','UCF College of Arts and Humanities','Publish',200),(3214,'2020 Faculty Exhibition at UCF Art Gallery','2020-faculty-exhibition','<p>The UCF Art Gallery is proud to present a dynamic exhibition of artworks by the faculty of the<span> </span><a href=\"https://svad.cah.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">UCF School of Visual Arts and Design</a>. These professional artists have received both national and international recognition for their engaging and thought-provoking works. The exhibition showcases a wide range of traditional and contemporary media and processes including ceramics, drawing, digital art, mixed media, painting, photography, printmaking, sculpture, and textiles.</p>\n<p><strong>Faculty include:</strong><span> </span>Hadi Abbas, Chuck Abraham, Jason Burrell, Byron Clercx, Larry Cooper, Victor Davila, Brooks Dierdorff, Scott F. Hall, Kevin Haran, Robert Hoekstra, Tommy James, Matthew Johnson, Joo Kim, Amer Kobaslija, Keith Kovach, Theresa Lucey, Justin Nolan, Carla Poindexter, Robert Reedy, Robert Rivers, Debi Starr, Ashley Taylor, Keri Watson, M. Laine Wyatt, and Margaret Zaho.<br><em><br></em><strong>Exhibition Dates: Oct. 15 - Nov. 5, 2020<br><br>Gallery Hours: </strong><em><strong><br></strong></em><strong>Monday - Thursday:<span> </span></strong><span>10 a.m. - 5 p.m.</span><strong><br>Friday:<span> </span></strong><span>10 a.m. - 4:30 p.m.</span><em><strong><br><br></strong></em><strong>Virtual Gallery:<span> <a href=\"https://artshumanitiesucf.exposure.co/2020facultyexhibit\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Click Here</a></span></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Special Programs and Events</strong><br>A series of artist talks and two art history presentations will be online this year.<span> </span><a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/2020-annual-faculty-exhibition/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">More information.<br></a></p>\n<p>More Information can be found here:<strong><span> <a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/</a></span></strong></p>\n<p><em><strong>This exhibition is free and open to the public. Free parking is available in Garage F next to the Addition Financial Arena. $5 parking lot H-4 or Garage I requires purchasing a visitor permit from a kiosk. Please note that visitors should park in green student spaces ONLY, as the $5 daily permit does not cover red and blue spaces.</strong></em></p>','2020-10-27','2020-11-05','https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/2020-faculty-exhibition/','UCF Art Gallery',NULL,'gallery@ucf.edu','UCF Art Gallery','Publish',200),(3215,'Mirage: Fall 2020 SVAD Biannual BFA Exhibition at UCF Art Gallery','mirage-fall-2020-svad-biannual-bfa-exhibition','<p>The SVAD Biannual BFA Exhibition provides the opportunity for undergraduate students majoring in book arts, ceramics, drawing, experimental animation, illustration, painting, photography, printmaking, and sculpture to share their research and artistic practice.</p>\n<p><strong>Exhibition Dates: </strong>November 9-23, 2020<strong><br><br>Gallery Hours: <em><br></em>Monday - Thursday:<span> </span></strong>10 a.m. - 5 p.m.<br><strong>Friday: </strong>10 a.m. - 4:30 p.m.<strong><br></strong></p>\n<p><em>Mirage<span> </span></em>includes work by sixteen artists: Kaitlyn Alborn, Alexander Alvarez, Kenny Castellanos, Sofia Del Real, James Dumay, Alexis Faulkner, Cameron Felt, Laurel Felt, Kevin Flores, Logan Hernandez, Sara Kerner, Sarah Luciano, Mär Martinez, Bernard Postell, Tiddles and Samantha Wiggins<br><br><em>Virtual gallery link coming soon!</em><br><br>Our physical gallery space is now open! plan your visit:<span> </span><a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/?fbclid=IwAR1HofKu1M-rmvtntFPwPceKTIa9AV_AtD8DlQ69TPJg3w8_fRMz4cwD6S0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/</a><br><br>This exhibition is free and open to the public. Free parking is available in Garage F next to the Addition Financial Arena. $5 parking lot H-4 or Garage I requires purchasing a visitor permit from a kiosk. Please note that visitors should park in green student spaces ONLY, as the $5 daily permit does not cover red and blue spaces.</p>','2020-11-09','2020-11-23','https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/mirage-bfa-2020/','UCF Art Gallery',NULL,'gallery@ucf.edu','UCF Art Gallery','Publish',200),(3216,'Clinton Global Initiative University Applications Open','clinton-global-initiative-university-applications-open','<p>Are you a student leader who wants to make the world a better place through positive social change? If so please consider applying for the 2021 Clinton Global Initiative University program (CGIU)! Applications are now open for undergraduate and graduate college students who are tackling critical issues on their college campus, in their local community, or around the world. Selected students will be paired with a mentor and will provide opportunities to receive seed money towards your initiative and resources. <strong>Apply by January 15, 2021</strong> <strong>to be part of CGI U \'s global cohort</strong>: <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fclintonfoundation.us12.list-manage.com%2Ftrack%2Fclick%3Fu%3De809aa89bab0cd5855ca8ede9%26id%3De94b20ecd8%26e%3Dfffc6afbbd&amp;data=04%7C01%7Cstacey.malaret%40ucf.edu%7C77e8611fc3804dfcd3af08d8768b3625%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637389687571037844%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=U5aT97QrPPu9OYcUwX6aPBD9n3IXyg9VuXmTvDAEJlU%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>cgiu.org/apply</strong></a></p>\n<p><strong></strong>If you are a student interested in learning more about the CGI U yearlong program and application process, we invite you to attend one of the following Prospective Student Webinars, hosted by CGI U Outreach Associate Cassie Epstein.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Thursday, October 22 at 12:00pm ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZIqcOysqTsoHNBvQzn2reDFKWgvn3Zr89zN\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here<span> (link is external)</span></a></li>\n<li>Tuesday, November 3 at 10:00am ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZMpfuCvrDopHdFcMvXvtYKemh-ADG23g3XU\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here<span> (link is external)</span></a></li>\n<li>Monday, November 16 at 3:00pm ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZUkdeuhpjouG9H_Kl-OlekubHcGZQzDQ-MP\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here<span> (link is external)</span></a></li>\n<li>Thursday, December 3 at 4:00pm ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZwsc-ysqzktGt1_OShk56z4AVSC_ar1wWXW\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here<span> (link is external)</span></a></li>\n<li>Wednesday, December 16 at 11:00am ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZcscuirqDkjHNwKtA94sMR461r9jEyvJnDR\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here<span> (link is external)</span></a></li>\n<li>Friday, January 8 at 5:00pm ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZ0qf-qrqjsuH9Ebz5vcbVt1Od1c_nWC7fa9\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here<span> (link is external)</span></a></li>\n<li>Thursday, January 14 at 9:00am ET • <a href=\"https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZUode6vpjgqGN2c323VTL1jpafwFIsaEAJJ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here</a></li>\n</ul>','2020-10-27','2021-01-15','http://cgiu.org/apply','Stacey Malaret','(407) 823-6492','malaret@ucf.edu','Stacey Malaret','Publish',8),(3217,'USPS Employee of the Month (October): Gregg Nelson','usps-employee-of-the-month-october-gregg-nelson','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for October 2020: Gregg Nelson.</p>\n<p>Gregg Nelson is a law enforcement officer for the UCF Police Department. His nominators, Commander James Mangan and Commander Pablo Vargas, had this to say about him:</p>\n<p><em>“Officer Nelson saved a life of a stranger on August 21st, 2020, after being alerted by a witness that this person had been shot and possibly hit by a vehicle. Officer Nelson applied a tourniquet and clotting agent to control the bleeding until fire rescue could arrive on scene.</em></p>\n<p><em> </em><em>Officer Nelson was able to help save a life due to three reasons: 1. Even though he was on his way home, he was prepared with all his equipment and ready to go at a moment’s notice, 2. Officer Nelson had situational awareness to see someone flagging him down and his mind was ready for action, and 3. Officer Nelson cares about others and is always ready to help, no matter when or where that might occur.</em></p>\n<p><em> </em><em>By stopping to assist someone with a gunshot wound, Officer Nelson was showing a commitment to UCF\'s Mission/Creed of being a positive impact on our community. Citizens of our Orlando community saw a marked UCF Police car, a uniformed UCF Police Officer and most importantly, a UCF Knight helping someone in need. One of these witnesses even thanked Officer Nelson several times for stopping and not just driving away.”</em></p>\n<p><em> </em><span>As USPS Employee of the Month, Gregg receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, and a goody bag. He is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards.</span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit </span><a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><span>https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</span></a><span> </span><span> </span></p>\n<p><span> </span></p>','2020-10-30','2020-11-18','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3218,'Lunch in Pompeii: Dailies and Delicacies- Getting a Taste of Pompeii','lunch-in-pompeii-dailies-and-delicacies-getting-a-taste-of-pompeii','<p><strong>November 19, 2020<br>Noon - 1 p.m. EST<br>Zoom Virtual Event </strong></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Join us for lunch in Pompeii! Faculty from the UCF Anthropology and Chemistry Departments, and educators from Orlando Science Center, will help us walk back in time and explore artifacts from </span><a href=\"https://www.osc.org/pompeii/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em></a><span> and how they relate to the modern world. The artifacts discussed in these talks will be on display in </span><em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em><span> traveling exhibit at Orlando Science Center, October 26 – January 24.</span></p>\n<p><span>Zoom virtual talks: 30 minute talk and then moderated Q&amp;A.</span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span><strong><a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_4JhSjEiGLgvUOpL\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Click here to RSVP</a></strong></span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Speaker: Lana Williams, Ph.D.</strong><br>Associate Lecturer, UCF Department of Anthropology<br><br></span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Abstract</strong>: </span>Welcome to our<span> </span><em>gustatio</em>, a light lunch of starters! We will share a virtual tasting of daily fresh breads, herbed olives in oil, and drink a full-bodied raisin wine or posca, a cold, watered-down vinegar. Then, we will enjoy the delicacies of our table, cold boiled veal slices with a savory, peppery fish sauce and crispy, roasted and honey-glazed dormice. Sounds delicious! Or does it?</p>\n<p>Our modern system of tastes that seem so “naturally” preferable to us are very different from those of the past. The perfect meal of ancient Pompeii and the Roman World was one where all the tastes, and therefore all the virtues, would be simultaneously present. These tastes developed a model of cuisine based on the blending of a multitude of flavors and textures rather than being singular or distinct. This “structure of taste,” strongly correlated with the philosophy and worldview of those living in Pompeii, at times serves as a barrier for us in understanding a reality so different from our own.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>Speaker Biography: </strong>Dr. Lana Williams a bioarchaeologist specializing in research of human health and diet. She received her PhD in 2008 from University of Western Ontario and was awarded the Governor General’s Academic Gold Medal in 2009. She has been a member of the Dakhleh Oasis Project in Egypt since 2002, the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven project at Dayr al-Barsha in Egypt since 2006, and also works with various archaeological projects inEurope, the Near East, and Mesoamerica. The central goal of Dr. Williams’ research is to better understand the synergistic complexities among biological, social and physical environments in the past. She focuses particularly on isotopic and elemental analysis of hair, seasonality in fertility and disease, musculoskeletal biomechanics and patterns of activity, and placement of the dead in the physical and social landscapes.</p>\n<p>Dr. Williams’ research contributions have been published in journals such as the <em>American Journal of Physical Anthropology</em>, <em>International Journal of Osteoarchaeology</em>, <em>American Antiquity</em>, and <em>Practical Diabetes International.</em> She has published a book titled <em>Forensic Recovery of Human Remains: Archaeological Approaches, 2</em><em>nd</em><em> Edition</em> (with co-authors T. Dupras, J. Schultz, and S. Wheeler, CRC Press, 2011). Dr. Williams joined the faculty in2013 and teaches Life and Death in Ancient Egypt, Human Biological Diversity, Medical Anthropology, Nutritional Anthropology, History of Anthropological Thought, Forensic Archaeology Field Methods, and Seminar in Biological Anthropology.</p>','2020-11-19','2020-11-19','https://sciences.ucf.edu/lunch-in-pompeii/dailies-and-delicacies/','UCF College of Sciences','(407) 823-1997','COSMarketing@ucf.edu','UCF College of Sciences','Publish',278),(3219,'Celebrate International Education Week: Nov. 16-20','celebrate-international-education-week-nov-16-20','<p>UCF Global invites students, faculty, and staff to celebrate International Education Week (IEW), Nov.16-20. </p>\n<p>International Education Week is a joint initiative between the U.S. Departments of State and Education, recognizing the benefits of international education and exchange across campuses worldwide. A series of events will take place across campus highlighting international affairs, cultural diversity and the positive impact the international community has made on Central Florida.</p>\n<p>Although this year’s events will all be mostly virtual, one of the featured events is a discussion with <span> Kirk Johnson of the Smithsonian Institute, as</span> part of the Mandell Distinguished Lecture Series. He will be discussing the topic, “What the Past tells us about Climate Change.” Other event offerings include panels, info sessions, cooking and art demos, a movie in the park in partnership with the UCF Arboretum, and social media challenges.</p>\n<p>If your department or division is planning to host an event during IEW, <a href=\"https://global.ucf.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">UCF Global</a> will be promoting the week\'s events online at <a href=\"https://global.ucf.edu/iew\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://global.ucf.edu/iew</a> and through social media. We encourage everyone to use #UCFIEW20 and #GlobalKnights in your posts. Additionally, we would like to share your events through our channels. Please submit your event details online at: <a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_6xjMh3QTkV5o389\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_6xjMh3QTkV5o389</a></p>','2020-11-05','2020-11-20','https://global.ucf.edu','Mark Hartman','(407) 823-1230','Mark.Hartman@ucf.edu','UCF Global','Publish',166),(3220,'COS Alumni Virtual Panel, Life After Graduation: Succeeding in the Workplace','cos-alumni-virtual-panel-life-after-graduation-succeeding-in-the-workplace','<p><strong>Monday, November 9<br>6 - 7 pm EST<br>Zoom Virtual Event</strong></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Once you get that dream job or internship, how can you stand out and showcase your skills? The </span><a href=\"https://ucfalumni.com/sciences\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">College of Sciences alumni board</a><span> invites you to attend the third virtual alumni panel in the Life After Graduation series: Succeeding in the Workplace!</span></p>\n<p>Hear from College of Sciences alumni, who share their insights on how to build your network and showcase your skills and experiences when applying for your dream job or internship. Learn about what advice they received when starting their careers, their tips for acing your next interview, and more.</p>\n<p><em>Reserve your spot to attend by<span> </span><strong><a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/COSAlumniPanel3\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">registering here</a><span> </span></strong>and receive the Zoom link via email.<br>This event is free. Registration is required to receive the event webinar link.</em></p>\n<p><em></em></p>\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Alumni Panelists:</span></p>\n<p>-<span> </span><strong>Nick Grandchamps ’15,<span> </span></strong><span>Foreign Service Officer at the Department of State<br>- <strong>Janelle Coutts ’08 ’13PhD, </strong>Senior Chemical Analyst at NASA Kennedy Space Center<br>- <strong>Stephen Hanas ’15, </strong>Manager of Business Intelligence at Houghton Mifflin Harcourt<br>- <strong>Tristan Reynoso ’15, </strong>2nd year PhD Student at Louisiana State University, 2019 NSF-GRFP Recipient<br><br></span><span></span></p>\n<p><span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Panel Moderator: </span><br></span></p>\n<p><span>-<strong> Diana Rodriguez ’18, </strong>College of Sciences Alumna, Psychology BS</span></p>\n<p><em></em></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://sciences.ucf.edu/succeeding-in-the-workplace/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Click here for more information.</em></a></p>','2020-11-05','2020-11-10','https://sciences.ucf.edu/succeeding-in-the-workplace/','UCF College of Sciences','(407) 823-0120','sciences@ucfalumni.com','UCF College of Sciences Alumni Board','Publish',278),(3221,'Integrative Anthropology Annual Conference','integrative-anthropology-annual-conference','<p>- Friday, December 4<br>- 10 a.m. - 4 p.m. EST<br>- Virtual Event </p>\n<p><span>The Integrative Anthropological Sciences doctoral program at the University of Central Florida invites </span>you to<span> </span><span>the third annual Integrating Anthropology conference. This year\'s topic will be <strong>Transformations of the Body</strong>. This may be viewed from a literal standpoint looking at direct effects on the human body from:</span></p>\n<p><span>- modifications and rites-of-passage<br>- environmental change, diet and disease<br>- the fluidity of identity, gender and sexuality<br>- the physical effects of human frailty, mortality and mortuary treatments</span><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Alternatively, this may also refer to the figurative transformation of bodies, such as the ever-increasing body of multi-disciplinary anthropological research.<a href=\"https://www.integrativeanthropology.com/#h.djakozo4wzsg\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"></a>In keeping with the program’s thematic interests, we will present research implementing interdisciplinary approaches to contrast, compare, and showcase transformations of the body. To ensure the health and well-being of our participants and attendees, this year\'s conference will be held virtually.</span></p>\n<p><span><br><strong><a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/integrating-anthropology-conference-transforming-the-body-tickets-123205219127\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">REGISTER HERE</a></strong><br></span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><strong>Keynote Speaker: <br></strong><strong>Aaron Deter-Wolf,<span> </span></strong>Prehistoric Archaeologist for the State of Tennessee Division of Archaeology</p>\n<p><span>Aaron Deter-Wolf is a Prehistoric Archaeologist with the Tennessee Division of Archaeology in Nashville, where his work includes managing ancient Native American sites on State-owned lands and conducting archaeological excavations and research. In addition to his work in Tennessee, for the past decade Aaron has been a leading researcher in developing the archaeological study of tattooing. Those efforts include studies using contextual analysis and microscopic use-wear signatures to identify tattooing tools in archaeological collections, projects to systematically document tattoos on ancient preserved human remains, and experiments recreating and testing ancient and historic tattooing implements.</span></p>\n<p><span>In 2009, Aaron organized the first American academic symposium to examine ancient and early historic Native American tattooing, which culminated in the volume Drawing with Great Needles: Ancient Tattoo Traditions of North America. He has participated in international symposia on ancient body modification, authored multiple research publications on the archaeological identification of tattooing artifacts, and is co-editor of the volume Ancient Ink: The Archaeology of Tattooing, the first-ever book dedicated to the global archaeological study of tattooing. In recent years Aaron was part of research teams which identified a 2,000-year old cactus spine tattooing tool from southern Utah, and 5,000-year old turkey bone tattooing tools from Tennessee. He shares information about ancient and historic tattooing and body modification on the Instagram account @archaeologyink.</span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><strong>This event is free, but registration is required. Register by<span> </span><a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/integrating-anthropology-conference-transforming-the-body-tickets-123205219127\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">clicking here</a>.</strong></p>\n<p>For more information about this event, refer to their<span> </span><a href=\"https://www.integrativeanthropology.com/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>.</p>','2020-11-04','2020-12-04','https://www.integrativeanthropology.com/','Integrating Anthropology UCF',NULL,'IntegratingAnthropologyUCF@gmail.com','UCF College of Sciences','Publish',278),(3222,'UCF Alumni Book Club Presents Author Knight With David James Poissant','ucf-alumni-book-club-presents-author-knight-with-david-james-poissant','<p><strong>Thursday, November 19 | 7-8p.m.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Zoom</strong></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Join us for a chat with David James Poissant, author of the novel <em>Lake Life</em> (Simon &amp; Schuster, 2020), a <em>New York Times</em> Editors\' Choice selection, <em>Publishers Weekly</em> Summer Read, and a <em>Millions</em> Most Anticipated book of 2020. </span><br> <br> <span>Lillian Laitman \'93, a UCF College of Arts and Humanities alumna, author, and award-winning editor will lead the conversation. </span><br> <br> <span><strong>Attendees will be entered into a random giveaway to win a copy of David’s novel <em>Lake Life</em> or Lillian’s book <em>Suit Up! Empowered with Purpose</em>.</strong></span></p>\n<p><span><strong></strong></span></p>\n<p><strong>Register:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/alumnibookclub\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ucffoundation.org/alumnibookclub</a> </p>\n<p></p>','2020-11-12','2020-11-19',NULL,'UCF Alumni',NULL,'knights@ucfalumni.com','UCF Alumni','Publish',280),(3223,'Join Us for a Virtual Heart Walk Nov. 14','join-us-for-a-virtual-heart-walk-nov-14','<p>Lend your support to the American Heart Association Heart Walk by either sponsoring our team members or by walking yourself. As with many events, this year’s walk will be virtual — but heart disease is certainly very real. <br><br>Mary Lou Sole, dean of the College of Nursing, and Mike Morsberger, vice president for Advancement and CEO of the UCF Foundation, are co-chair\'s of this year\'s UCF team, and can use all the help they can muster. Join team UCF or support this worthwhile project by visiting <a href=\"http://ucffoundation.org/heartwalk\" rel=\"nofollow\">ucffoundation.org/heartwalk</a>. <br><br>Virtual Heart Walk<br>Nov. 14<br><span><a href=\"http://ucffoundation.org/heartwalk\" rel=\"nofollow\">ucffoundation.org/heartwalk</a></span></p>','2020-11-11','2020-11-14','http://ucffoundation.org/heartwalk','Mary Lou Sole',NULL,'foundation@ucf.edu','Laura Cole','Publish',35),(3225,'Giving Tuesday at UCF','giving-tuesday-at-ucf','<p><span>You’ve probably heard of Black Friday and Cyber Monday, and maybe even Small Business Saturday. Following the big shopping days, non-profits across the globe celebrate Giving Tuesday. On this day, they ask for their supporters to give back what they can to help sustain their good work.  </span><br> <br> <strong>On Tuesday, Dec. 1, UCF will celebrate Giving Tuesday with a special focus on supporting student success.</strong></p>\n<p><span>We’re asking Knights to consider donating to scholarships, student services or any program at UCF that they care about—whether it’s academics, research, emergency funds or even diversity initiatives. Through collective action, we will have the chance to transform lives through philanthropy. </span></p>\n<p>Take a minute to <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ft.e2ma.net%2Fclick%2Fnl8vqs%2F705roib%2Fnpfsnq&amp;data=04%7C01%7CKelsey.Moscater%40ucf.edu%7C6aec5340eeb64dd160a908d888081de7%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637408915722501936%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=I2A%2FjenKP%2FzIZhQcdCpmpSK8e%2FP9oHVtsojdpezdX0k%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">learn about Giving Tuesday</a> and how you can be a part of it: <a href=\"https://ucfalumni.com/givingtuesday\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucfalumni.com/givingtuesday</a></p>','2020-11-16','2020-12-01','https://ucfalumni.com/givingtuesday','Stephanie Odierno','(407) 882-0564','stephanie.odierno@ucf.edu','UCF Advancement','Publish',268),(3226,'Deadline Approaching for USPS Staff Employee Scholarship Award and B&N Bookstore Award','usps-staff-employee-scholarship-award-and-barnes-and-noble-bookstore-award','<p>The USPS Staff Council is now accepting applications for the <u>Spring 2021</u> Scholarship awards.  Apply now at the Staff Council web site, (<a href=\"http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/</a>) or on the council Facebook page. There are two awards available: The USPS Staff Council Employee Scholarship and the Barnes &amp; Noble Campus Book awards. </p>\n<p>Dependents of USPS staff may apply for the Campus Bookstore award. Applications must be submitted by 11:59 p.m. January 20, 2021. You may apply for one or both of the awards if you wish. The only restrictions are you must be a member of the USPS for a minimum of one year, and if you have won an award you must wait one year before applying for that particular award again. </p>\n<p>Apply now and avoid the rush!</p>','2020-12-09','2021-01-20','http://staffcouncil.admfin.ucf.edu/','Jamie LaMoreaux','(407) 882-0191','lamoreaj@ucf.edu','Jamie LaMoreaux','Publish',54),(3227,'2020 #UCFinSpace Uniform Auction is Live','2020-ucfinspace-uniform-auction-is-live','<p><span>The 2020 #UCFinSpace Helmet and Uniform Auction in live on <a href=\"http://UCFKnights.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">UCFKnights.com</a>. To bid on your set today, visit <a href=\"https://ucfknights.com/auctions/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">ucfknights.com/aucutions</a>.</span><span> The auction will end Tuesday, Dec. 15 at noon.</span></p>','2020-12-10','2020-12-14','https://ucfknights.com/auctions/','UCF Athletics','(407) 823-1000','jskiles@athletics.ucf.edu','UCF Athletics','Publish',165),(3228,'UCF Alumni Hosts Virtual Pep Rally for the Boca Raton Bowl!','ucf-alumni-hosts-virtual-pep-rally-for-the-boca-raton-bowl','<p>Bust out your black and gold gear for our first-ever virtual UCF pep rally! Although the bowl game may look a little different this year, UCF Alumni is still here to celebrate with you.</p>\n<p>Our <a data-type=\"url\" href=\"https://ucfalumni.com/bowlbound\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>UCF ChargeOn Virtual Pep Rally for the Boca Raton Bowl</strong></a> will feature all of your fan favorites including: UCF Vice President and Director of Athletics, Danny White, the UCF Spirit Team, Knightro, the UCF Marching Knights and some other surprise guests!<br> <br> This virtual experience is complimentary but <a data-name=\"registration is required\" data-type=\"url\" href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/ChargeOnBoca\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>registration is required</strong></a><strong>.</strong><strong><br> <br> </strong>All attendees will be entered into an \"opportunity to win\" drawing for some autographed memorabilia so you won\'t want to miss this! </p>','2020-12-11','2020-12-22','https://ucfalumni.com/bowlbound','Laura Heiselman','(407) 823-1498','laura.heiselman@ucf.edu','Laura Heiselman, UCF Alumni','Publish',277),(3229,'Students Encouraged to Apply to Odyssey Ambassadors','odyssey-ambassadors','<p><span>Office of Diversity and Inclusion\'s student advisory board that allows students to discuss and provide recommendations on diversity and inclusion topics and how to enrich the student-learning environment across UCF. Perspective students will meet to discuss their experiences as UCF students and discuss issues of concern of their peers. Odyssey Ambassadors will have opportunity to enhance their leadership competencies, explore various facets of diversity, exhibit knowledge of diversity and inclusion as ambassadors for ODI, and serve as mentors for the “UCF Young Knights Mentoring Program.” The students will also be trained to facilitate courageous conversations around equity, inclusion, and diversity.</span></p>','2020-12-18','2021-01-08','https://diversity.ucf.edu/students/odyssey-ambassadors/','Flore Septimus','(407) 823-6479','odysseyambassadors@ucf.edu','Office of Diversity and Inclusion','Publish',161),(3230,'Learning From Lasers: Uncovering Pompeii With Chemical Laser Analysis','learning-from-lasers-uncovering-pompeii-with-chemical-laser-analysis','<p><span>- Thursday, January 14, 2021<br></span><span>- Noon - 1 p.m. EST<br></span><span>- Zoom Virtual Event </span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span>Join us for lunch in Pompeii! Faculty from the UCF Anthropology and Chemistry Departments, and educators from Orlando Science Center, will help us walk back in time and explore artifacts from </span><a href=\"https://www.osc.org/pompeii/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em></a><span> and how they relate to the modern world. The artifacts discussed in these talks will be on display in </span><em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em><span> traveling exhibit at Orlando Science Center, October 26 – January 24.</span></p>\n<p><span>Zoom virtual talks: 30 minute talk and then moderated Q&amp;A.</span></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span></span><strong><a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_4JhSjEiGLgvUOpL\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">RSVP Here.</a></strong></p>\n<p><strong></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Speaker: Matthieu Baudelet, Ph.D., Associate Professor, UCF Department of Chemistry</strong></p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Abstract:</strong> </span><span>This talk will show how lasers are used in archaeology and art through research and artifacts from Pompeii and displayed in the <em>Pompeii: The Immortal City</em> traveling exhibit. Lasers are unique tools that can be used to provide information at so many levels when studying artifacts and archaeological sites. From mapping entire cities and buildings, to the chemical analysis of artifacts and art pieces, we will travel through the exciting world of chemical analysis with lasers. Lasers can unveil atomic and molecular compositions while keeping the items intact and provide us with a comprehensive view of their origin and manufacturing.</span></p>\n<p><span>We will discover chemical formulation of paints to better understand how they were created as well as the composition of everyday glassware. We will also travel through the recent uses of lasers for mapping Pompeii that allow us to be part of the city and unveil the knowledge of this civilization after all these years.</span></p>\n<p><strong>Speaker Biography: </strong>Dr. Matthieu BAUDELET is an associate professor specializing in chemical analysis for forensic research. He graduated with a <a href=\"http://M.Sc\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">M.Sc</a>. in \"Laser and Spectroscopy\" in the University of Lyon (France) and continued to complete his Ph.D. in the \'Laboratoire de Spectrométrie Ionique et Moléculaire\' (Lasim, Lyon) working on \"Laser-induced plasma and spectroscopic analysis\" under the direction of Pr. Jin YU in 2008. From 2008 to 2015, as a Senior Scientist and then Research Assistant Professor of Optics in the Laser &amp; Plasma Laboratory in the Townes Laser Institute at UCF, he was introducing and developing laser spectroscopy for atomic spectroscopy as well as electronic, vibrational and rotational molecular spectroscopy for studying fundamentals of plasmas, quantitative analysis and sensing in tabletop and integrated configuration as well as for stand-off detection. Now Faculty member of the Chemistry department in the National Center for Forensic Science at the University of Central Florida, his research focuses on the application of spectroscopic techniques for forensic analysis. He is focusing on evidence such as tire skid marks, pollen grains and anthropological remains. He also develops matrix-matched analytical standards of hard biomaterials for laser-ablation techniques. He is teaching spectroscopy and microscopy for forensic analysis at the undergraduate and graduate levels.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://sciences.ucf.edu/lunch-in-pompeii/learning-from-lasers/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Click Here for More Information</a></p>','2021-01-05','2021-01-14','https://sciences.ucf.edu/lunch-in-pompeii/learning-from-lasers/','UCF College of Sciences','(407) 823-0120','COSMarketing@ucf.edu','UCF College of Sciences','Publish',278),(3231,'Registration Open for AFAA Group Exercise Certification Course','afaa-group-exercise-certification-course','<p><span>The AFAA Group Exercise Certification Course is a 3 day workshop that consists of online lectures via Zoom. This course is great for anyone interested in becoming a certified group exercise instructor or wanting to learn more about exercise programming.</span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Course Information:</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>This course meets 3 days in a row: January 29th, 30th, and 31st. A course syllabus with detailed information will be provided. The course will meet beginning January 29th.</span></p>\n<p><span>January 29th: 4:30pm-6:30pm</span></p>\n<p><span>January 30th: 9am-3pm </span></p>\n<p><span>January 31st: 2pm-5pm </span></p>\n<p><span><strong>Price per student: $219</strong></span></p>\n<p><span>Materials include:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Access to online resources</span></li>\n<li><span>Textbook</span></li>\n<li><span>Practice exam</span></li>\n<li><span>GEX examination enrollment</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>AFAA</strong></p>\n<p>Athletics and Fitness Association of America (AFAA) certifications are well-recognized throughout the United States and the world as providing comprehensive knowledge. The AFAA- Group Exercise Certification teaches you how to successfully lead a group exercise class like Cardio Kickboxing, Total Body Strength, and more.</p>\n<p>Registration will be open from 1/8/2020 until 1/28/2021.<span> </span><a href=\"https://ucfrwc.org/Program/GetProducts?classification=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000026002\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register here. </a></p>\n<p>Please direct any questions about this course to Kyra.Dickie@ucf.edu</p>','2021-01-08','2021-01-28','https://ucfrwc.org/Program/GetProducts?classification=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000026002','Kyra Dickie','(407) 823-2408','kyra.dickie@ucf.edu','Stacey Embry','Publish',284),(3232,'Registration Open for National Academy of Sports Medicine Personal Training Course','nasm-personal-training-course','<p>The NASM Personal Training course is a five-week course that consists of online lectures via Zoom. This course is great for anyone interested in becoming a certified personal trainer or wanting to learn more about exercise programming.</p>\n<p><strong>Course Information</strong></p>\n<p>This course meets once a week for two hours. A course syllabus with detailed information will be provided.The course will meet on Thursdays beginning February 18th </p>\n<p><strong></strong><strong>Price per student: $499</strong></p>\n<p>Materials include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span>Access to online resources</span></li>\n<li>Textbook</li>\n<li>Practice exam</li>\n<li>CPT examination enrollment</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>NASM</strong><br><span>National Academy of Sports Medicine (NASM) certifications are well-recognized throughout the United States and the world as providing comprehensive knowledge. The NASM-CPT (Certified Personal Trainer) certification teaches you how to evaluate a client’s current fitness and build a program around them.</span></p>\n<p><span>Registration will be open from 2/1/2021 until 2/17/2021. Register <a href=\"https://ucfrwc.org/Program/GetProgramDetails?courseId=06130433-5878-4431-9c52-ffad2b76656b&amp;semesterId=7ff5a89d-3a20-4609-a315-cca04ecedf16\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://ucfrwc.org/Program/GetProducts?classification=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000026002\">here. </a></span></p>\n<p>Please direct any questions about this course to Kyra.Dickie@ucf.edu.</p>','2021-01-18','2021-02-17','https://ucfrwc.org/Program/GetProducts?classification=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000026002','Kyra Dickie','(407) 823-2408','kyra.dickie@ucf.edu','Stacey Embry','Publish',284),(3233,'WEBINAR-Career Transitions: How To Change Lanes','career-transitions-how-to-change-lanes','<p>Career Transitions: How To Change Lanes<span style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"> </span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong>Thursday, Jan. 28</strong><br><strong>Noon-1 p.m.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong>Webinar is free for all alumni and friends.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">UCF Alumna, <strong>Lynn Chisholm \'80</strong>, Director of Office of Internships and Career Readiness at the University of South Florida, will share tips and strategies on making a career change that works! Lynn will discuss how to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Edit your resume content for the position you want</li>\n<li>Develop and enhance your network on LinkedIn</li>\n<li>Identify and clarify your brand in today’s market</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">Whether you are a new graduate or seasoned professional needing to switch gears, join the conversation and start 2021 in the right direction!</p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">RSVP: <a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/HowToChangeLanes\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ucffoundation.org/HowToChangeLanes</a></p>','2021-01-28','2021-01-28','https://www.ucffoundation.org/HowToChangeLanes','Ashley Turner','(407) 823-6203','Ashleyc.Turner@ucf.edu','UCF Alumni Engagement','Publish',285),(3234,'Healing Art Exhibition VII - Virtual Reception','healing-art-exhibition-vii-reception','<p>Please join us for the seventh annual UCF Counseling &amp; Psychological Services (CAPS) collaboration with the School of Visual Arts and Design to showcase artworks by UCF students, faculty, staff and alumni. The UCF Healing Art Exhibition\'s mission is designed to create campus-wide awareness of the power between arts and healing, to increase inclusivity across campus, and to create an open exhibition space for creativity in a healing environment. We welcome you to honor our artists who have been transformed by the healing power of creativity to inspire others to do the same.<br><br><strong>Healing Arts Exhibition VII</strong><br>The Art of Being Visible: Expressions of Social Justice<br><br><strong>Wednesday, February 10 | 6-7 p.m. EST</strong><br>*Featuring Virtual Art Gallery and Awards*<br><br><strong>Zoom Registration Link:</strong><span> </span><a href=\"https://bit.ly/HealingArtVII?fbclid=IwAR1ev6Ko0Ukn2yI-IAb9CmsR-gEFNaZ1lV7U6SLR9If9K4bppSAIRk1U_a8\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">http://bit.ly/HealingArtVII</a><br><br>Hosted in association with UCF Counseling and Psychological Services, UCF School of Visual Arts and Design (SVAD), and Sam Flax of Orlando.</p>','2021-02-01','2021-02-11','https://ucf.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJErdeiqqDgtGtHO7gjQgmPLDa0vxlveqbKm','Caiti Bradbury',NULL,'Caitlin.Bradbury2@ucf.edu','UCF Counseling and Psychological Services (CAPS)','Publish',200),(3235,'Theatre UCF Returns to the Stage this Spring','theatre-ucf-returns-to-the-stage-this-spring','<p><span>This spring, Theatre UCF is back on stage for three outdoor performances including a hopeful musical revue, a colorful Commedia dell\'arte play and a family-friendly show about wanting to be anything but average.</span></p>\n<p><span>Up first, <strong><em>Song of Inspiration</em></strong> hopes to inspire audiences through a musical revue featuring classic show tune favorites and the latest Broadway hits. Performances include songs from <em>Anastasia</em>, <em>Annie Get Your Gun</em>, <em>West Side Story</em>, <em>Man of La Mancha</em>, <em>Godspell</em>, <em>Funny Girl</em> and more. The performance will take place in the Orlando Shakes Courtyard in a covered, outdoor setting with cozy cabaret tables physically-distanced for the health and safety of patrons and performers.</span></p>\n<p><span>Full of raucous energy typical of Commedia dell\'arte, Theatre UCF\'s production of <strong><em>Scaramouch in Naxos</em></strong> will take place in the courtyard of the UCF Performing Arts Center, resembling the original presentation of Commedia plays in the 17th century. The story involves a plot by the roguish clown Scaramouch to have a Greek god star in his latest play, while Silenus schemes to interfere with his theatrical ambitions as well as the would-be lovers, Ione and Sarmion.</span></p>\n<p><span>For one weekend only, the UCF Performing Arts Center Courtyard will host a family-friendly show produced by the MFA <em>Theatre for Young Audience</em> class called <strong><em>The Grumpiest Boy in the World</em></strong>. The play follows Zachary, a grumpy boy of seven who wants to be anything but average. He sets out to find a land of giants, flying things and anything else that will make him stand out.</span></p>\n<p><span>Please remember as you make plans to attend these performances to come prepared for whatever elements Florida\'s weather may bring and to review the health and safety guidelines. You can find more information about guidelines </span><a href=\"https://arts.cah.ucf.edu/theatre/#healthandsafety\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><span>here</span></a><span>.</span></p>\n<p><span>Tickets are on sale beginning Tuesday, Jan. 19 at noon.</span></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://arts.ucf.edu/theatre\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong><span>Click here to view the full schedule and purchase tickets</span></strong></a></p>\n<p><strong>Schedule at a glance</strong></p>\n<p><br><strong><em><span>Songs of Inspiration</span></em></strong><span> | <em>Orlando Shakes Courtyard</em></span></p>\n<p><span>Thursday, Feb. 4 at 7:30 p.m. | Friday, Feb. 5 at 7:30 p.m. | Saturday, Feb. 6 at 2:00 p.m. | Sunday, Feb. 7 at 2:00 p.m.</span></p>\n<p><strong><em><span>Scaramouch in Naxos</span></em></strong><span> | </span><a href=\"https://goo.gl/maps/AR77E18ZCiESfZjA7\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em><span>UCF Performing Arts Center Courtyard</span></em></a></p>\n<p><span>Feb. 20-March 7</span></p>\n<p><span>Saturdays at 2:00 p.m. and 4:30 p.m. | Sundays at 2:00 p.m.</span></p>\n<p><strong><em><span>The Grumpiest Boy in the World</span></em></strong><span> | </span><a href=\"https://goo.gl/maps/AR77E18ZCiESfZjA7\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em><span>UCF Performing Arts Center Courtyard</span></em></a></p>\n<p><span>Saturday, March 13 at 2:00 p.m. and 4:30 p.m. | Sunday, March 14 at 2:00 p.m.</span></p>\n<p><span> </span></p>\n<p><span></span> </p>','2021-01-13','2021-03-14','https://arts.cah.ucf.edu/theatre/','Steven Risko',NULL,'Steven.Risko@ucf.edu','Theatre UCF','Publish',166),(3236,'Virtual Event-Career Transitions: How To Change Lanes','virtual-event-career-transitions-how-to-change-lanes','<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong>Thursday, Jan. 28 via ZOOM</strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong>Noon-1 p.m.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\"><strong>Webinar is free for all alumni and friends.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">UCF Alumna, Lynn Chisholm \'80, Director of Internships and Career Readiness at the University of South Florida, will share tips and strategies on making a career change that works! Lynn will discuss how to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Edit your resume content for the position you want</li>\n<li>Develop and enhance your network on LinkedIn</li>\n<li>Identify and clarify your brand in today’s market</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;\">Whether you are a new graduate or seasoned professional needing to switch gears, join the conversation, and start 2021 in the right direction!</p>','2021-01-28','2021-01-28','https://www.ucffoundation.org/HowToChangeLanes','Ashley Turner','(407) 823-6203','Ashleyc.Turner@ucf.edu','UCF Alumni Engagement','Publish',285),(3237,'Register for 15th Annual Public Administration Research Conference','get-your-ticket-for','<p><span>The 15th Annual Public Administration Research Conference is </span><strong>March 19, 2021</strong><span>. And this time, we\'re bringing PARC to you with our first-ever fully virtual experience. Centered around the theme, </span><em>Public Service in Times of Uncertainty: Upholding Our Ideals of Justice, Inclusion and Public Purpose, </em><span>PARC brings together academics and practitioners to share innovative ideas and engage in discussions related to public administration and community leadership. We invite you to join us - and share the invitation with a colleague or friend. </span><br><br><span>Much of 2020 was characterized by the COVID-19 global pandemic and mass protests across the globe calling attention to racial and social issues. In the U.S., the challenges of moving forward and beyond these major events were exacerbated by disinformation and political divisiveness. At the same time, many of us have been repeatedly exposed to viral images and messages of police brutality, systemic racism, and citizen violence against each other. One thing that has emerged from all of this uncertainty and turmoil is a movement calling for inclusive justice that can no longer be ignored by public institutions and leadership.</span><br><br><span>The 15</span>th<span> annual PARC virtually brings together students, academics, and practitioners from across the globe to engage in conversations related to public service during difficult times and propose important solutions for moving forward with purpose for the betterment of our society in an inclusive and socially just way.</span><br><br><span>Early bird registration (<em>and early bird discounts</em>) end on <strong>January 29</strong>. <a href=\"https://ucfparc.wordpress.com/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Reserve</a> your space today!</span></p>','2021-01-15','2021-03-18','https://ucfparc.wordpress.com/','Justin Miller','(407) 823-3794','cpnm@ucf.edu','Center for Public and Nonprofit Management','Publish',155),(3238,'Call for Nominations for the 2021 Gabor A&P Excellence Award','call-for-nominations-for-the-2021-gabor-ap-excellence-award','<p>Sponsored by The Gabor Agency, the Gabor A&amp;P Excellence Award was established to recognize, reward, and celebrate the outstanding job performance of a selected non-unit Administrative &amp; Professional (A&amp;P) employee. The chosen candidate will be announced at the Knight Star Awards in May 2021 and will receive a check for $2,500.</p>\n<p><strong>All nominations must be received in Human Resources by 5:00 p.m. on Friday, February 26, 2021.</strong></p>\n<p>Eligibility criteria and additional information about the award: <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/</a></p>\n<p>Nomination form: <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/nominate.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/nominate.pdf</a></p>\n<p>Thank you for your active participation in recognizing UCF employees for their outstanding contributions!</p>','2021-01-14','2021-02-26','https://hr.ucf.edu/current-employees/employee-recognition/gabor-ap-excellence-award/','Human Resources Learning & Organizational Effectiveness','(407) 823-0440','HRLearning@ucf.edu','UCF Human Resources','Publish',287),(3239,'XXI Coloquio anual de literatura, lingüística y cultura hispanoamericanas y peninsulares','xxi-coloquio-anual-de-literatura-linguistica-y-cultura-hispanoamericanas-y-peninsulares','<p>A day full of presentations, discusions and cultural events in Spanish hosted by SaGA (Spanish Graduate Association). Join us virtually to celebrate \"La cultura hispánica entre máscaras y mascarillas\". This year we are meeting on Zoom. Our guest speaker is Señor José María Merino member of the Real Academia Española who is sharing with us ¿<em>Para qué sirve la ficción literaria?</em>. Contact us at <span>SaGA@ucf.edu for more information and access to our wonderful conversations and cultural expressions.</span></p>','2021-02-26','2021-02-26','https://knightconnect.campuslabs.com/engage/event/6638693','Patricia Camacho','(407) 488-7321','patricia.camacho@ucf.edu','Spanish Graduate Association','Publish',286),(3240,'Theatre UCF Spring Performances On Sale Now!','theatre-ucf-spring-performances-on-sale-now','<p>Theatre UCF presents three outdoor performances include a hopeful musical concert, a colorful Commedia dell’arte play and a family-friendly show about wanting to be anything but average.</p>\n<p>Tickets on sale now at <a href=\"https://arts.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">arts.ucf.edu</a>!</p>\n<p>To maintain the health and well-being of performers and audiences, groups will be seated with at least six feet of distance from others. Masks will be required for attendees and other<span> </span><a href=\"https://arts.cah.ucf.edu/theatre/#healthandsafety\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">health and safety guidelines</a><span> </span>will be enforced.</p>\n<p>Performers will also wear masks during the shows and are following safety guidelines throughout the rehearsal process.</p>','2021-01-20','2021-03-13','https://arts.ucf.edu/','Box Office','(407) 823-1500','boxoffice@ucf.edu','School of Performing Arts','Publish',116),(3241,'\"But Before Bone is Skin\" curated by Jonell Logan','but-before-bone-is-skin-curated-by-jonell-logan','<p>Tayari Jones’ book<span> </span><span><em>Silver Sparrow </em></span>is truly the story of women.</p>\n<p>Mothers and daughters struggling to find their identities and shed legacies that may not be their own. They are all on a quest to define themselves, often bruising and sometimes tearing their skin along the way as they bump against historical, cultural and familial boundaries.</p>\n<p><strong><em>But Before Bone is Skin</em></strong>, curated by Jonell Logan explores this space of women The path that we take to find peace and resolve in who we are. The artists in the show question and construct internal spaces that are secret, yet teased out and sometimes shared with others. They challenge notions of beauty and the definitions, often prescribed by others, of femininity and propriety. They share their individual questions and journey through womanhood.</p>\n<p><strong>Exhibiting Artists:</strong><span> </span>Melissa Alexander, Shanequa Gay, Yanique Norman, Sharon Norwood and Zipporah Camille Thompson<br><br><em>Learn more about the exhibition:<span> </span><a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/but-before-bone/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/but-before-bone/</a></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>Exhibition Dates: January 11 - February 5, 2021<br><br></strong></em>Our physical gallery space has reopened! Hours of operation are as follows:<em><strong><br></strong></em><strong>Monday - Thursday:<span> </span></strong>10 a.m. - 5 p.m.<strong><br>Friday:<span> </span></strong>10 a.m. - 4 p.m.<br><br><span>This exhibition is sponsored by the</span><span> </span><a href=\"https://bigread.cah.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Big Read</a><span> </span><span>and inspired by Tayari Jones’</span><span> </span><span><em>Silver Sparrow </em></span><span>(2011). NEA Big Read is a program of the</span><span> </span><a href=\"https://www.arts.gov/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">National Endowment for the Arts</a><span> </span><span>in partnership with</span><span> </span><a href=\"https://www.artsmidwest.org/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Arts Midwest</a><span>. For more programming associated with the NEA Big Read at UCF, visit</span><span> </span><a href=\"https://bigread.cah.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Big Read: Central Florida</a><span>.</span></p>','2021-01-11','2021-02-05','https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/but-before-bone/','UCF Art Gallery',NULL,'gallery@ucf.edu','UCF Art Gallery','Publish',200),(3242,'NEA Big Read Presents Keynote Address with Jonell Logan','keynote-address-with-jonell-logan','<p><span>Jonell Logan is an independent curator, arts advocate, and creative director for the McColl Center for Art + Innovation in Charlotte, NC. She will discuss her curatorial background and approach including the ways in which the themes from the novel \"Silver</span><span> Sparrow\" </span><span>informed her selection of artists and artworks for inclusion in </span><a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/but-before-bone/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong><em>But Before Bone is Skin<span> </span></em></strong></a><span>exhibition. </span></p>\n<p><span>Moderated by UCF Art Gallery director, Shannon Lindsey.<br><br>Friday, Jan. 22 | 6 p.m. ET<br><strong><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/8916069682443/WN_BIqUwyEJQlOiRnGBzuO_Eg\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register Here</a></strong><br><br>This programming is in association with the exhibition, <em>But Before Bone is Skin</em> sponsored by the <a href=\"https://bigread.cah.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Big Read</a> and inspired by Tayari Jones’ <em>Silver Sparrow </em>(2011). NEA Big Read is a program of the <a href=\"https://www.arts.gov/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">National Endowment for theArts</a> in partnership with <a href=\"https://www.artsmidwest.org/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Arts Midwest</a>. </span></p>','2021-01-20','2021-01-23','https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/8916069682443/WN_BIqUwyEJQlOiRnGBzuO_Eg','UCF Art Gallery',NULL,'gallery@ucf.edu','UCF Art Gallery','Publish',200),(3243,'\"But Before Bone is Skin:\" Artist Panel','but-before-bone-is-skin-artist-panel','<p><span><a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/but-before-bone/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em><strong>But Before Bone is Skin</strong></em></a> contributing artists Yanique Norman, Sharon Norwood, Melissa Alexander, Shanequa Gay and Zipporah Camille Thompson discuss their artwork and how the themes of <em>Silver Sparrow</em> inspired their work. Discussion moderated by Jonell Logan and Shannon Lindsey.<br></span><span><br>Thursday, Jan. 28 | 6 p.m. ET<br><strong><a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/4016069687314/WN_47u_y3I5TM-eog8Ty6vNnA\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Register Here</a></strong><br><br>This programming is in association with the exhibition, <em>But Before Bone is Skin</em> sponsored by the <a href=\"https://bigread.cah.ucf.edu/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">NEA Big Read</a> and inspired by Tayari Jones’ <em>Silver Sparrow </em>(2011). NEA Big Read is a program of the <a href=\"https://www.arts.gov/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">National Endowment for theArts</a> in partnership with <a href=\"https://www.artsmidwest.org/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Arts Midwest</a>. </span></p>','2021-01-26','2021-01-29','https://ucf.zoom.us/webinar/register/4016069687314/WN_47u_y3I5TM-eog8Ty6vNnA','UCF Art Gallery',NULL,'gallery@ucf.edu','UCF Art Gallery','Publish',200),(3244,'2021 Annual MFA Exhibition: \"Paper House\"','paper-house-2021-annual-mfa-exhibition','<p><strong><em>Paper House</em></strong> explores fragility, transparency, and validation of intimate relationships and experiences through a variety of mediums and processes. The exhibition showcases the thesis work of Master of Fine Arts candidates in the UCF School of Visual Arts and Design: Gabe Cortese, Danielle Culibao-Powell, Tim Reid and Annette Tojar.</p>\n<p>Gabe Cortese’s paintings and drawings depict codification of queerness through figuration and symbolism.</p>\n<p>Danielle Culibao-Powell creates paintings and collages to expand upon personal experiences of falling into, or between, multiple cultures at once.</p>\n<p>Experimental filmmaker and installation artist Tim Reid provokes viewers with specific and universal insecurities, contradictions, and hypocrisy.</p>\n<p>Embracing her passion as a former professional pastry chef, Annette Tojar creates paintings of food to explore her cultural identity and personal histories.</p>\n<p><em>Learn more about the exhibition: <a href=\"https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/2021-annual-mfa-exhibition/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/2021-annual-mfa-exhibition/</a></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>Exhibition Dates: February 17, 2021 - March 3, 2021<br><br></strong></em>Our physical gallery space has reopened! Hours of operation are as follows:<em><strong><br></strong></em><strong>Monday - Thursday: </strong>10 a.m. - 5 p.m.<strong><br>Friday: </strong>10 a.m. - 4 p.m.<br><br> <em>Virtual Exhibition link: <a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_6o0Cj2uHEhuQvwG\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_6o0Cj2uHEhuQvwG</a></em></p>','2021-02-17','2021-03-03','https://gallery.cah.ucf.edu/exhibit/2021-annual-mfa-exhibition/','UCF Art Gallery',NULL,'gallery@ucf.edu','UCF Art Gallery','Publish',200),(3245,'USPS Employee of the Month (November 2020): Richard Colón','usps-employee-of-the-month-november-2020-richard-colon','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for <strong>November 2020</strong>: <strong>Richard Colón</strong>.</p>\n<p>Richard Colón is a Financial Aid Specialist in the office of Student Financial Assistance. His nominators, Mitzy Gonzalez and Cyndia Morales Muñiz, had this to say about him:</p>\n<p><em>“We are experiencing a time in history like no other. During stressful times, employees can either leverage the stress and find balance through their connection to the purpose of their work or become overwhelmed and feel stuck. Ric is so deeply connected to the purpose of his work that despite high levels of stress, has remained committed to intentionally showing up with kindness and humility for students and families. Ric has been an integral member of the UCF community for over a decade and his colleagues and the university community have always been able to count on him. He is reliable, a team player, and a source of calm during tumultuous times. </em></p>\n<p><em>Ric shows up, puts in the time and the work in support of our students. He did this back in 2017-18 when UCF welcomed 250 students from Puerto Rico after Hurricane Maria and he’s doing it now in the face of the COVID pandemic. He embodies all the tenants of the UCF Creed and is always willing to roll up his sleeves to support the UCF familia.</em> <em>His commitment to UCF is clear and admirable and we are fortunate to have him as a member of the UCF team.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Richard receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, and a goody bag. He is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff.  We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees.  To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>','2021-02-01','2021-02-12','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3246,'USPS Employee of the Month (December 2020): Wendy McKnight','usps-employee-of-the-month-december-2020-wendy-mcknight','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for <strong>December 2020: Wendy McKnight</strong>.</p>\n<p>Wendy McKnight is an Administrative Assistant I in the Rosen College of Hospitality Management. Her nominators, Vanessa Gonzalez and Lori Safford, had this to say about her:</p>\n<p><em>        “Mrs. McKnight is incredibly deserving of this recognition as she consistently embodies UCF’s vision, mission, and values. In her 16 consecutive years with the UCF Rosen College of Hospitality Management, she has shown time and time again her commitment to supporting the student body and furthering the mission and growth of the institution. Many years ago, she proudly created the first Culture Diversity Luncheon at the Rosen College, something that was very well received and appreciated by all involved. This is one example of how she actively creates and promotes new initiatives that align with the university’s values.</em></p>\n<p><em>Ms. McKnight lives up to UCF’s highest ideals and continues to initiate efforts to support the wellbeing of our students. For example: after the campus closed due to covid-19, Ms. McKnight continued to meet with students facing hardships and layoffs within the industry to provide food and personal care items. To ensure the pantry remains stocked, she continuously creates outreach initiatives to gain support. Her call for support was answered with a generous donation of $10,000 to provide a refrigerator for the Rosen College pantry which will create the opportunity for additional dietary options for our students in need”.</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Wendy receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, and a goody bag. She is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>\n<p> </p>','2021-02-01','2021-02-12','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3247,'A Well-Dressed Lie and the Naked Truth: The Black and Southern Roots of American Sociology','a-well-dressed-lie-and-the-naked-truth-the-black-and-southern-roots-of-american-sociology','<p><strong>Friday, February 12, 2021</strong><br><strong>2:00 - 3:30 pm EST</strong><br><strong>Zoom Virtual Event</strong></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><em><strong>COSTalks</strong><br> A Distinguished Speaker Series Event</em></p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ucf.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_3r69p1oR5eGLin4\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Click here to RSVP</a></strong><br>RSVP required to receive virtual Zoom link.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><em><strong>Speaker: Earl Wright, II, Ph.D.</strong></em><br><em>                Professor of Sociology, Rhodes College</em></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The contributions of Blacks to sociology have been minimized or ignored since its emergence in the mid 1800’s. The exclusion of these scholars slowed the development of the discipline and simultaneously provided space for White scholars to be falsely credited for advances made by early Black sociologists many years prior.</p>\n<p>This lecture examines the contributions of Black Americans to the discipline of sociology in the United States with an emphasis on those at historically Black colleges and universities (HBCUs). Moving beyond the tremendous exploits of W. E. B. Du Bois and the Atlanta Sociological Laboratory, the significant sociological contributions of Black men and women at Atlanta University, Fisk University, Howard University and Tuskegee Institute are placed in their proper historical and contemporary context.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Speaker biography: </p>\n<p>Dr. Earl Wright, II is a tenured professor at Rhodes College in Memphis, TN. Dr. Wright received his Ph.D. from the University of Nebraska, and previously served on the faculty at the University of Cincinnati, Texas Southern University (as Chairperson of the Department of Sociology), Fisk University, and University of Central Florida.</p>\n<p>Dr. Wright’s primary research and teaching interests are on the contributions of Blacks to American sociology and the sociology of hip hop. In 2016, he was selected by the Southern Sociological Society (SSS) as the recipient of the Charles S. Johnson Award for excellence in research on race and the South and was recently elected president of SSS.</p>\n<p>While at the University of Cincinnati, Dr. Wright co-founded an initiative that promoted community-partnered research relationships with local stakeholders. Having been reared less than two miles from Rhodes’ campus, Dr. Wright is very excited about the opportunity to continue his community engaged works in his hometown and the neighborhoods where he once lived.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>For more information: <a href=\"https://sciences.ucf.edu/sociology/a-well-dressed-lie-and-the-naked-truth/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://sciences.ucf.edu/sociology/cos-talks</a></p>','2021-01-29','2021-02-12','https://sciences.ucf.edu/sociology/a-well-dressed-lie-and-the-naked-truth/','UCF College of Sciences',NULL,'COSMarketing@ucf.edu','UCF College of Sciences','Publish',278),(3248,'Be My Neighbor Day - Celebrate Kindness All Month Long','be-my-neighbor-day-celebrate-kindness-all-month-long','<p>Join us in celebrating kindness with Be My Neighbor Day activities, virtual events, and a Daniel Tiger TV special throughout the month of February.</p>\n<p>GRR-IFIC Neighbors with Daniel Tiger<br>What: Daniel Tiger and friends celebrate what it means to be a caring neighbor with music, story time and at-home activities.<br>When: Saturday and Sunday, February 27 and 28 at 8:30 and 10 a.m.<br>Where: WUCF TV, watch on-air or online at<span> </span><a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwucf.org%2Flive%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR2NSC10YKSUkFinnk82EpYN3JcMg_YoiMTUuqsnWbUWuCC2sdZtJq7WjFQ&amp;h=AT0blcOTv4A-kgyfanpihnT-rZBCtzuJNdo84bdluZQ09E5G-Kqp3F1ex_MNOcxATJ_2hTVUQHDR0c15l4uGo7A22BrYmW8v2Y2kjJuxnKvrFwSzQ-FJ1I9dIaT29S5Lflo_7psythOTaZUbfXOPzQ&amp;__tn__=q&amp;c[0]=AT13dRMiwA6TpqzxU6XrWnZ7YInUYPGdpsjOV5C6hpCYCDts5fsfCHrYYiS-T9p0e0soJs6Dx8BdlE62OVzzZ9HOL8lY4joaAXDj5UKPWFHlf0Bsd9sVcms8lvdw6g32DE-TougF1LrzWrS5KxBs8UpG7GxVWwbiIqhtfHvkHE7W51RQ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">wucf.org/live</a></p>\n<p>Kindness Kits<br>What: The Be My Neighbor Day kindness kit includes seven at-home activities for celebrating kindness and what it means to be a caring neighbor. Activities include Mom Tiger’s Banana Bread, a Firefighter Sticker Scene, Thank You Cards, Music Dance Party Mini Drum, Taking Care of Me Yoga, Story Time Theatre and Grow a Butterfly Garden.<br>When: All February long<br>Where: Visit<span> </span><a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwucf.org%2Fbemyneighborday%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR2hn7btEprUKXrCQSWtDwqZTv3yQAY_yQcOpzmuzKtlttGwg-Nvt-e_kdU&amp;h=AT1EEgqpLPhy4I_dRXb_HuW6GDyhYJ9YRHtkNh-oi0GVkasLoTd5V6Zo0vGe87MZgmTg0R6rEJBfUahby6Onbz4zLXmfUQiOoBLc6luKARx6CjmcaAoUyYrO7nhqSsVeEtcg484xtGTlzcQb9yzYEg&amp;__tn__=q&amp;c[0]=AT13dRMiwA6TpqzxU6XrWnZ7YInUYPGdpsjOV5C6hpCYCDts5fsfCHrYYiS-T9p0e0soJs6Dx8BdlE62OVzzZ9HOL8lY4joaAXDj5UKPWFHlf0Bsd9sVcms8lvdw6g32DE-TougF1LrzWrS5KxBs8UpG7GxVWwbiIqhtfHvkHE7W51RQ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">wucf.org/bemyneighborday</a><span> </span>to print the kit or find a location for pick up.</p>\n<p>Growing up is \"Grr-ific\" with Daniel Tiger and his friends!<br>What: WUCF will host two interactive Virtual LIVE PBS KIDS time events that explore the world using the senses. Costume characters will NOT be in attendance at this event.<br>When: Thursday, Feb. 11 at 10 a.m. and Saturday, Feb. 13 at 10 a.m. (Both sessions are the same program.)<br>Where: Registration is required by signing up at<span> </span><a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwucf.org%2Fevents%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR3q-CMtcHR4R4svVMqHxGihhObfpTXpdkZ7cUdE5eCRZbVtdCOESwYi3uo&amp;h=AT2mB-TP6k6L9H1E84vyfSWJPj9n7BONcvk8ghWgrqEoYVNhcgD9fUt1GxAHXfwYe0HBLKg3Q9jn6cjeTFlg6jR3T8h5s7Z7ZxANDGcOWIMRQLHiGM8pQhjZoJkXaJIBWzIRlw2FvkP4TUNPv1T8Cg&amp;__tn__=q&amp;c[0]=AT13dRMiwA6TpqzxU6XrWnZ7YInUYPGdpsjOV5C6hpCYCDts5fsfCHrYYiS-T9p0e0soJs6Dx8BdlE62OVzzZ9HOL8lY4joaAXDj5UKPWFHlf0Bsd9sVcms8lvdw6g32DE-TougF1LrzWrS5KxBs8UpG7GxVWwbiIqhtfHvkHE7W51RQ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">wucf.org/events</a></p>\n<p>Note: WUCF will not be hosting an in-person event in Winter Park’s Central Park due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.</p>\n<p>Visit<span> </span><a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwucf.org%2Fbemyneighborday%3Ffbclid%3DIwAR1u0ThzPFHbEbSoCebiG6RB_sJBlh2KYBIqeQM2wHIHw8WR1SGtlPLit-E&amp;h=AT1EEgqpLPhy4I_dRXb_HuW6GDyhYJ9YRHtkNh-oi0GVkasLoTd5V6Zo0vGe87MZgmTg0R6rEJBfUahby6Onbz4zLXmfUQiOoBLc6luKARx6CjmcaAoUyYrO7nhqSsVeEtcg484xtGTlzcQb9yzYEg&amp;__tn__=q&amp;c[0]=AT13dRMiwA6TpqzxU6XrWnZ7YInUYPGdpsjOV5C6hpCYCDts5fsfCHrYYiS-T9p0e0soJs6Dx8BdlE62OVzzZ9HOL8lY4joaAXDj5UKPWFHlf0Bsd9sVcms8lvdw6g32DE-TougF1LrzWrS5KxBs8UpG7GxVWwbiIqhtfHvkHE7W51RQ\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">wucf.org/bemyneighborday</a><span> </span>for show information and downloadable activities.<span> </span></p>','2021-02-02','2021-02-28','http://wucf.org/bemyneighborday','Andrea Dennis','(407) 823-5796','andrea.dennis@wucf.org','WUCF','Publish',288),(3249,'UCF Alumni presents: About the Issue of Race: The Taboo Unraveled','ucf-alumni-presents-about-the-issue-of-race-the-taboo-unraveled','<p></p>\n<p>Feb. 23  |  About the Issue of Race: The Taboo Unraveled</p>\n<p><strong>Location</strong>:  Virtual | <strong>Time</strong>: 11:30 a.m. - <span>12:30 p.m</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>UCF Alumni, in partnership with the UCF Office of Diversity and Inclusion, is hosting a two-part series exploring how we, as a society, can be more understanding, respectful and inclusive.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>This authentic, open dialogue will be led by UCF’s Interim Chief Equity, Inclusion and Diversity Officer, Dr. Kent Butler. He will be joined by other community leaders including members of his esteemed Leadership Council.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>We will discuss serious issues of race, ethnicity and culture as well as actionable steps we can take to become more open and inclusive allies.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Lead Presenter and Moderator:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dr. S. Kent Butler, Jr.</strong>, interim chief equity, inclusion and diversity officer at UCF</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Panelists:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dr. Jonathan Cox</strong>, assistant professor of sociology at UCF</li>\n<li><strong>Kristine Shrauger</strong>, UCF librarian and oversees the Department of Interlibrary Loan and Document Delivery Services</li>\n<li><strong>Shreya Trivedi \'05\'14MNM</strong>, UCF ombuds officer</li>\n<li><strong>Dr. Linda Rosa-Lugo</strong>, dean of Faculty Excellence and Graduate and Global Affairs and the vice president for Speech-Language Pathology Practice for the American Speech-Language-Hearing Association</li>\n</ul>','2021-02-03','2021-02-23','https://www.ucffoundation.org/EmbracingDiversity1','Laura Heiselman','(407) 823-1498','laura.heiselman@ucf.edu','Laura Heiselman, UCF Alumni','Publish',277),(3250,'UCF Alumni presents: ChargeOn Panel: A Splash of Homecoming History','ucf-alumni-presents-chargeon-panel-a-splash-of-homecoming-history','<p><strong>Location</strong>:  Virtual | <strong>Date:</strong> Feb. 25| <strong>Time</strong><span>: 11:30 a.m. - </span><span>12:30 p.m.</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>UCF Alumni takes our attendees on a journey that began in 1971, when UCF hosted its first homecoming after the inception of Florida Technological University.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Join us as we welcome six notable Knights who will walk us through the history of UCF Homecoming and Spirit Splash, the story of Knightro, reflections from a member of UCF’s first cheerleading squad, the ever-elusive duck (and the original “squishy Knightro) and plans for this year’s Spirit Splash.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>This all-star panel will definitely deepen your love for your alma mater and all things black and gold!</p>\n<p><br>Participants will also have the chance to win their very own Spirit Duck! </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Panelists:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Linda Gooch \'85</strong>, a former 4-year letter-winner, an alumna of UCF and a 2020 recipient of the UCF Alumni Distinguished Alumni award.</li>\n<li><strong>Trey Gordon </strong><strong>\'96</strong>, Executive Director of Hope for North Brevard Inc.</li>\n<li><strong>Sandy Pickett</strong>, Charter member, FTU first cheerleading squad</li>\n<li><strong>Erykah Tomlinson</strong>, a junior from Broward County, Florida.</li>\n<li><strong>Aakilah Strappy</strong>, a senior Business Management major from Jacksonville, Florida</li>\n</ul>','2021-02-03','2021-02-25','https://www.ucffoundation.org/SplashOfHomecoming','Laura Heiselman','(407) 823-1498','laura.heiselman@ucf.edu','Laura Heiselman, UCF Alumni','Publish',277),(3252,'A Conversation with Tayari Jones','a-conversation-with-tayari-jones','<p><strong>Tuesday, Feb. 23 | </strong><strong>7 p.m. – 8 p.m. EST | Zoom</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Register:</strong><em> <a href=\"https://www.ucffoundation.org/TayariJones\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ucffoundation.org/TayariJones</a></em></p>\n<p>Award-winning author Tayari Jones talks about her career journey, writing process and themes of her novels in the culminating event of the 2021 NEA Big Read: Central Florida. Her novel <em>Silver Sparrow </em>has been the subject of book clubs, an exhibition at the UCF Gallery, artist talks and more for the past month, as UCF and the Central Florida community celebrate literature and the joy of reading a great book.</p>\n<p>Tayari Jones is a New York Times best-selling author of four novels. Her most recent novel, <em>An American Marriage</em>, published in 2018, is an Oprah’s Book Club Selection and also appeared on Barack Obama’s summer reading list as well as his year-end roundup. The novel was awarded the Women’s Prize for Fiction (formerly known as the Orange Prize), Aspen Words Prize and an NAACP Image Award.</p>\n<p>Moderated by UCF English lecturer Jason Gregory ’19MFA, the event will conclude with an audience Q&amp;A.</p>\n<p><em>This event is a collaboration between the NEA Big Read: Central Florida, the Florida Prison Education Project, UCF Alumni and the UCF College of Arts and Humanities.</em></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Accessibility</strong></p>\n<p>UCF is committed to providing universal access. ASL interpreters and closed captioning will be provided for this event. Please contact us at <a href=\"mailto:knights@ucfalumni.com\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">knights@ucfalumni.com</a> or 407.823.3868 to request any other disability accommodations no later than Feb. 17.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p></p>','2021-02-08','2021-02-23','https://www.ucffoundation.org/TayariJones','UCF Alumni',NULL,'knights@ucfalumni.com','UCF Alumni','Publish',280),(3254,'Enhancing Resilience Against Climate Risk- A Discussion with Chris Marlin and Kathy Baughman McLeod','enhancing-resilience-against-climate-risk-a-geeologue-discussion-with-chris-marlin-and-kathy-baughman-mcleod','<p><em>GEEOlogue Webinar</em></p>\n<p><em></em></p>\n<p>- Wednesday, February 17<br>- Noon EST<br>- <a href=\"https://ucf.zoom.us/j/98455098071?pwd=MndTQnNOWVhXaTdJWjA1aWhtYkV3Zz09\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Join the webinar here</strong></a> </p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Over the last three-quarters of a century, the global population has seen remarkable advancements at all levels of society. Today there are historic lows of extreme poverty, child mortality, and illiteracy—and advancements in health, education, and technology continue to accelerate – even during the global pandemic. At the same time, the world currently faces a range of challenges that threaten natural resources and economic progress, political stability, and human safety.</p>\n<p>Addressing climate change, migration, and security challenges—affecting all geographies—is more urgent than ever. There is a critical need to build resilience for individuals, communities, and institutions to better understand, prepare for, and withstand these interrelated threats. The Adrienne Arsht–Rockefeller Foundation Resilience Center is dedicated to addressing these challenges, transforming ideas into action, and has committed to reaching one billion people with resilience solutions to climate change, migration, and security by 2030. The need is urgent and we are all vulnerable.</p>\n<p>Join James Bacchus, Distinguished University Professor of Global Affairs and Director of the <a href=\"https://sciences.ucf.edu/geeo/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Center for Global Economic and Environmental Opportunity (“GEEO”)</a> of the University of Central Florida, as he hosts a conversation between GEEO community fellow Chris Marlin, President of Lennar International and Kathy Baughman McLeod, Sr. VP and Director of the Atlantic Council’s Adrienne Arsht – Rockefeller Foundation Resilience Center as they discuss plans to reach one billion people with resilience solutions to climate change, migration and security by 2030.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>Speaker Biographies:</strong></p>\n<p><strong><span>Chris Marlin</span></strong><br>Chris Marlin is founder and president of Lennar International, a division of the largest and most innovative homebuilder in the United States - Lennar. Lennar International serves as Lennar’s global engagement hub, marketing and selling Lennar homes in the U.S. to buyers throughout the world, as well as curating foreign direct investment into Lennar’s portfolio of projects including PropTech, land development and multi-family ventures.</p>\n<p>Chris is a leading commentator on cross border investments into the U.S. and has presented at a variety of global forums and events including the World Economic Forum, the Global Future Council on Cities, and Boao Forum for Asia.  Chris has also been a featured expert on Bloomberg’s Daybreak Asia, CNBC’s Squawk Box Asia, and Singapore’s Channel NewsAsia.</p>\n<p>Chris is a Director of the Atlantic Council, where he supports the United Nations’ Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) 16 for peace, justice and strong institutions. Through his involvement with the World Economic Forum’s Cities, Infrastructure and Urban Services platform, Chris is able to support SDG 11 for sustainable cities and communities. In addition, his involvement with the World Economic Forum’s COVID Action Platform allows him to support SDG 3 for good health and well-being.</p>\n<p>Chris is a member of the Intellectual Council of the Boao Forum for Asia, A Fellowship for International Real Estate (AFIRE), and the Young Presidents’ Organization (YPO) – a global network of chief executives. During the summer of 2020, Chris served as Co-Chair of the working group on Digital Infrastructure and Economy for the non-partisan Commission on the National Response Enterprise, which focused on American security interests.</p>\n<p><span></span></p>\n<p><strong><span>Kathy Baughman McLeod</span></strong></p>\n<p>As Senior Vice President of The Adrienne Arsht – Rockefeller Foundation Resilience Center, Kathy Baughman McLeod is leading and expanding the Center’s work to develop scalable policy, financial and technological solutions to build the resilience capacity of individuals, communities and institutions. Baughman McLeod comes to the Atlantic Council from Bank of America where she was Global Environmental and Social Risk Executive, and is former managing director of Climate Risk and resilience at The Nature Conservancy. She was an Energy &amp; Climate Commissioner of the state of Florida, a policy fellow of the French Foreign Ministry and holds an MBA and MS in Geography.</p>\n<p>She leads creation and execution of the Center’s strategy to achieve its goal of reaching one billion people worldwide with resilience solutions to the challenges of climate change, migration, and security by 2030. She leverages the significant global network, policy expertise, and intellectual capital of the Atlantic Council with strategic partnerships to deliver innovative on-the-ground solutions. </p>\n<p>Baughman McLeod is the former senior vice president, Global Environmental &amp; Social Risk, for Bank of America. In this role, she led the bank’s environmental and social risk policy work including climate risk disclosure efforts across the enterprise, in select lines of business and throughout four global regions. She also helped use the bank’s global reach to advance low carbon and climate resilient investments toward reaching the bank’s commitment of deploying $125 billion in capital by 2025.</p>\n<p>In her prior role as managing director, Climate Risk &amp; Resilience for the Nature Conservancy, Baughman McLeod led a global team of fifty policy experts, scientists, and financial specialists focused on using natural infrastructure to reduce storm and flood risk throughout Latin America, Australia, Asia, the US, and the Caribbean. She also launched the organization’s insurance initiative that creates market-based products that protect nature and coastal economies, as well as the Conservancy’s humanitarian initiative focused on climate disaster risk reduction called “Nature Protects People.”</p>\n<p>A published author and award-winning producer of the documentary film series, The Nature of People, Baughman McLeod was a policy fellow of the French Foreign Ministry and an appointed member of the Florida Energy &amp; Climate Commission. She holds an MBA from Duke’s Fuqua School of Business, an MS in geography, and a BS in international affairs from Florida State University.</p>','2021-02-08','2021-02-17','https://events.ucf.edu/event/2027383/enhancing-resilience-against-climate-risk-discussion-with-chris-marlin-and-kathy-baughman-mcleod/','Alexandra Ramirez',NULL,'Alexandra.Ramirez@ucf.edu','UCF College of Sciences','Publish',278),(3255,'USPS Employee of the Month (January 2021): Samuel Waters','usps-employee-of-the-month-january-2021-samuel-waters','<p>Please join UCF Human Resources in congratulating the newest USPS Employee of the Month (EOM) for January 2021: Samuel Waters.</p>\n<p>Samuel Waters is the Administrative Assistant I in the School of Performing Arts. His nominators, Michael Wainstein and Arlene Flores, had this to say about him:</p>\n<p><em>“He is committed 100%. He believes in the mission and values of UCF. This year has been really tough for everyone at UCF, and Sam\'s total commitment to the theatre department has been a critical part of our success in navigating these rough waters. Especially the way he has reached out to students and managed the student population in our school. He has a very positive attitude and always steps up.</em></p>\n<p><em>When Sam is not in the office, we go crazy. He is the one who knows everything that you would need to know about the Theatre program and always willing to go the extra mile to help the faculty, staff, and students. When the undergraduate advisor needs any assistance, Sam is always willing to help in anyway necessary.”</em></p>\n<p>As USPS Employee of the Month, Samuel receives a $200 cash award, $25 from UCF Business Services and UCF Bookstore, and a goody bag. He is now eligible for the USPS Employee of the Year $2,500 award, announced at the UCF Knight Star Awards.</p>\n<p>The University of Central Florida USPS Employee of the Month and Year Awards recognize exceptional performance of currently employed USPS staff. We welcome your nomination and assistance in recognizing exceptional university employees. To see eligibility criteria or to nominate someone, visit <a href=\"https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf</a></p>','2021-02-19','2021-02-26','https://hr.ucf.edu/files/USPS-Employee-of-the-Month-Nomination-Process.pdf','Theresa Scipione','(407) 823-6711','theresa.scipione@ucf.edu','Human Resources','Publish',265),(3256,'Knights Write 2021','knights-write-2021','<p>DEPARTMENT OF WRITING &amp; RHETORIC CELEBRATES WRITING EXCELLENCE</p>\n<p>The Department of Writing and Rhetoric (DWR) invites you to attend the virtual Knights Write 2021 on February 23rd-25th (times vary per day).  </p>\n<p>Knights Write provides an opportunity for faculty, staff, students, parents, and the public to see the exciting projects completed by students in various majors during their Composition I: ENC1101 and Composition II: ENC1102 courses. Since ENC 1102 is a pre-requisite for many upper division courses, faculty and staff can gain a glimpse of the writing knowledge and experience that students who take ENC 1102 at UCF may bring to their upper division work. Additionally, this event features upper division and graduate-level writing and research from students in writing and rhetoric courses, many of whom draw from diverse disciplinary perspectives.   </p>\n<p>We’d love to see you at this event that features writing—a knowledge-making activity that crosses our (inter)disciplinary boundaries and our various kinds of work.</p>','2021-02-23','2021-02-25','https://tinyurl.com/4vjerbgp','Jennifer Cunningham','(407) 823-0576','jennifer.cunningham@ucf.edu','Jennifer Cunningham','Publish',291),(3257,'45 Years of Collecting: UCF Libraries\' Special Collections & University Archives','45-years-of-collecting-ucf-libraries-special-collections-university-archives','<p>Exhibit:</p>\n<p><em><strong>45 Years of Collecting: UCF Libraries’ Special Collections &amp; University Archives</strong></em> showcases the University of Central Florida (UCF) Libraries’ Special Collections &amp; University Archives’ distinct collection. From a 13th century religious text to UCF memorabilia, the broad range of materials on display reflects the diverse nature of the department’s holdings. This exhibit, curated by department staff, highlights the collection’s evolution over the past forty-five years. While not every item exhibited is the most unique, most valuable, or most rare, they all are essential in telling the department’s history.</p>\n<p>The exhibit runs from February 2021 through April 2021 in the new 4th floor Special Collections &amp; University Archives’ Gallery in the John C. Hitt Library.</p>\n<p>Hours of operation are as follows:</p>\n<p>Monday - Friday: 9:00 a.m. - 4:00 p.m.</p>\n<p><em>The gallery capacity is limited to 2 guests at any given time. All guests must wear a face covering and maintain at least 6 feet of physical distancing within the gallery space.</em></p>\n<p><em>For more information, email speccoll@ucf.edu.</em></p>','2021-02-16','2021-04-26',NULL,'Special Collections & University Archives','(407) 823-2876','speccoll@ucf.edu','UCF Libraries\' Special Collections & University Archives','Publish',198),(3258,'Knight Vision Virtual Open Forum','knight-vision-virtual-open-forum-finance-spotlightfeb-23-3-pm','<p>UCF has begun the implementation phase of <a href=\"https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fknightvision.it.ucf.edu%2F&amp;data=04%7C01%7CThomas.Diaz%40ucf.edu%7Ca23f6a8aa3c543be6ac208d8c7c05181%7Cbb932f15ef3842ba91fcf3c59d5dd1f1%7C0%7C0%7C637478976103636056%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&amp;sdata=2vwzFNWGxoR4FEMJouOfQR18WsoF0khrFfGzHM2kUms%3D&amp;reserved=0\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Knight Vision</span></a>, a multi-year project to transform the way we operate in serving our students, faculty, and staff by increasing the effectiveness and efficiency of our administrative processes. Knight Vision will replace PeopleSoft financial, human resources and student information systems with Workday, a modern, cloud-based enterprise resource planning (ERP) platform. It will also transform many of our business processes to match leading practices that have been proven effective at other institutions of higher learning.</p>\n<p>To learn more about this critical initiative, the entire campus communit